<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0695 02-21 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0695,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Returns To Government Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to ADD Shiite background of Kishtmand and
UPDATE with rebels trying to break deadlock on forming interim govt. Pick
up 8th pvs, `The guerrillas'...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sultan Ali Kishtmand, a ranking member
of the ruling Communist Party's Politburo and a hard-liner, Tuesday
took over many of the duties of prime minister, government sources
said.
   Moslem guerrillas, meanwhile, fired a salvo of rockets into the
Afghan capital, killing one person and injuring three others on the
ninth anniversary of an uprising against the Soviet-backed
government.
   Mohammad Hasan Sharq stepped down as prime minister Monday, and a
21-member Supreme Military Council took power.
   State-run Kabul Radio said Kishtmand, who served as prime
minister for seven years until May 1988, is in charge of supervising
the government's council of ministers.
   Government sources, speaking on condition of anonyumity, said
this means the 52-year-old Kishtmand will effectively be the prime
minister.
   The return to power of of Kishtmand, the only prominent Shiite
Moslem in President Najib's government, is seen as another move by
Najib to consolidate the power of his communist government.
   Shiites make up only 17 percent of Afghanistan's population, but
they account for about 40 percent of the refugees from which many of
the guerrillas are drawn.
   Najib appointed Sharq, a non-communist, as prime minister last
May in an unsucessful bid to seek a power-sharing agreement with the
Moslem guerrillas.
   In Islamabad, Pakistan, a committee of Afghan field commanders
and scholars sought to reach a consensus Tuesday on the makeup of an
interim government for Afghanistan. More than 400 delegates to a
special Afghan council or ``shura'' cancelled Tuesday's session
while the committee wrestled with a blueprint for a provisional
government.
   The commanders and scholars took over the job of nominating an
interim government after guerrilla leaders, paralyzed by differences
between moderates and fundamentalists, failed to break a deadlock
Monday.
   The guerrillas' rocket attack on Kabul was the first since
Thursday, when at least seven people were killed.
   The Foreign Ministry said the fatal rocket in Tuesday's assault
hit near a government refugee office in northern Kabul. Three other
rockets hit southeastern Kabul, but there were no reports of
casualties.
   The guerrillas hold most of the countryside and are trying to
close in on the cities, which mainly are held by government troops.
   At the headquarters of the secret police, the Foreign Ministry
displayed a huge cache of arms and explosives and said the
guerrillas had planned to use them Tuesday to attack buildings and
bazaars.
   Many had markings from the United States, Britain, Egypt, Sweden,
China and Italy. Officials said others were made in Pakistan, where
the most powerful guerrilla groups are based.
   Moammad Omar, a state security agent, said the weapons were
seized Monday in a well in eastern Kabul.
   Business was brisk at some shops in Kabul Tuesday, but others
were closed to mark the anniversary of the anti-Soviet uprising.
   The 1980 revolt occurred two months after Soviet troops entered
Afghanistan to bolster a Marxist government. Soviet soldiers fired
on Moslem protesters who emerged from their homes shouting ``God is
Great!''
   Dozens of people were reported killed.
   Among the weapons displayed by the government were plastic
explosives that agents said came from Pakistan, Chinese-made hand
grenades, British mortar shells, Egyptian rockets, Italian fuses for
mines, Swedish circuit testers and Chinese rifles.
   There also were political pamphlets. One, printed in English and
the local language Dari, said: ``We will contine our Jihad (holy
war) until the withdrawal of the last Soviet soldier.''
   The final Soviet troops, once estimated at more than 100,000 in
Afghanistan, withdrew last Wednesday under a U.N.-mediated accord.
   Over the weekend, Najib declared a state of emergency and shook
up his government to consolidate control.
   In Geneva Tuesday, an investigator appointed by the United
Nations said both sides in the civil war continue to violate the
human rights of Afghans.
   Austrian law professor Felix Ermacora said reliable reports
suggest dfghan police still widely use torture and mistreatment as
part of interrogations.
   His report also listed alleged incidents, cited by ``a variety of
corroborating sources,'' in which rebels had killed more than 100
Afghan soldiers and civilians since September.
</TEXT>
