<FIRST>r a PM-BadTimesonBayouII     02-21 1211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bad Times on Bayou II,1246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Part II: Economic Reform Comes Hard In Populist Louisiana</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   When the oil and the good times were flowing,
Louisiana's populist system of government seemed to make sense. Give
the people a free ride and let the businesses pay. Now oil has
crashed, Louisiana has suffered through four years of economic
depression, and economists say recovery isn't possible without a new
system. A reformist governor is trying to do just that, but breaking
with the populist past doesn't come easy. This second of two parts
of ``Bad Times On The Bayou'' explores this Louisiana revolution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 34-story Louisiana state capitol
casts a long shadow over the white marble statue of Huey Long, but
these days, it seems the statue is casting the longer shadow.
   ``An unconquered friend of the poor,'' the inscription on Long's
adjacent tomb says, ``who dreamed of the day when the wealth of the
land would be spread among the people.''
   The populist ideas of ``the Kingfish,'' who governed from
1928-1932, still influence the fiscal structure of the state.
   Spread the wealth, protect the poor.
   Homeowners receive a $75,000 property tax exemption, making the
average home tax free. Automobile license plates cost only $3 a
year. City councils can't raise taxes without a vote of the people.
Businesses bear much of the burden through taxes and fees.
   But the way of doing business that Huey Long helped build is
crippling the state now, economists say. Without the oil windfall,
state and local budgets can't be balanced. Schools and hospitals are
suffering. Unemployment has soared. And new businesses are scared
away by the tax structure.
   ``It's ironic. What is supposed to be good for the people now
acts to their detriment,'' said University of New Orleans economist
Tim Ryan.
   Added business leader Eugene Schreiber, director of New Orleans'
World Trade Center: ``We've got to change. We cannot do business in
the old ways. ... Painful as it is, it's forced us to wake up.''
   But waking up isn't easy in the land of ``The Big Easy,'' as New
Orleans is called.
   After a string of legislative victories and a fierce round of
budget cutting and borrowing, Gov. Buddy Roemer's initial attempt at
overhauling the tax structure failed in the state House.
   The Harvard-educated conservative Democrat has, in his own words,
``poked every bear in the forest'' while inciting a revolution in
Louisiana.
   He won education reform, campaign finance reform, tort reform,
worker's compensation reform, even unemployment insurance reform.
But when it came to fiscal reform, when it came to dismantling the
last vestiges of the populist past, Roemer lost.
   Can't a family's home be the one thing that's not taxed, Roemer's
opponents asked?
   ``I believe in paying our own way. That is a break from Louisiana
tradition,'' Roemer said. ``It doesn't come easy.''
   Along the way, Roemer is also compiling a spectrum of political
enemies ranging from populists to labor unions to teachers. Public
opinion polls are divided on the maverick reformer.
   The question remains, what happens if he can't complete the
revolution?
   ``It would be more of the same. We'd be a slave to Saudi Arabia
... a wasteland, a welfare state,'' Roemer said, adding that people
with the means to move away would do so.
   Politicians, he said, ``are beginning to realize that.''
   Fiscal reform has become the vortex of Louisiana's struggle to
climb out of a depression that began when the price of oil fell by
more than half in 1984-85. Tens of thousands lost jobs, and both
businesses and workers left the state.
   And taxes on oil _ which used to account for 40 percent of the
Louisiana state budget _ plummeted. The state, long known for its
big spending ways, hadn't put anything aside for dry years. It
hadn't spent much on developing a strong economic base, outside of
oil. In fact, it hadn't even had a balanced budget in the 1980s
until Roemer took office 10 months ago _ even though it has a
balanced budget law.
   It's debt reached $2 billion.
   ``We could not make the payroll the week after I took office,''
Roemer said.
   Now, state promoters, planners and business leaders all buzz with
talk about Louisiana's recovery _ if there is fiscal reform.
   ``When the price of oil was $40 a barrel, hardly anybody
worried,'' said Schreiber, the businessman who chaired a governor's
task force on labor.
   ``Having all these advantages made everyone in the state very
lazy. Louisiana has not been competitive in business,'' Schreiber
said. ``It's only really now that the state is pulling its act
together.''
   The day after reform failed last October, two companies
considering Louisiana announced plans to build in Texas. Other
businesses considering a relocation or expansion in the Bayou State
are holding off until they see if reform passes, said Louisiana's
chief of economic development, Connie Lewis.
   Wall Street bond brokers set out informal guidelines for what
would be necessary to raise the state's bond rating, currently just
one notch above junk bonds. Low bond ratings means the state must
pay higher interest on its debt. Roemer has accomplished all but one
item _ fiscal reform, said his chief of staff, Steve Cochran.
   ``They watch us very closely,'' he said.
   The battle will probably be waged this spring when Roemer comes
back to the Legislature with a plan. Last time, his package passed
the state Senate, but came up 10 votes short of the necessary
two-thirds margin in the House.
   The opposition focused on Roemer's plan to cut by two-thirds the
$75,000 homestead exemption _ the nation's highest. It was led by a
county tax assessor, Lawrence Chehardy, who saw reform as an attempt
to raise taxes and cripple the average homeowner.
   ``People in Louisiana read horror stories in other states where
property taxes did go wild,'' said Chehardy. ``Government taxes
everything. Can't there be one thing in life a person can have
without being taxed?''
   Chehardy says lawmakers should cut the budget, and if there are
any tax increases, taxpayers should get a chance to vote.
   But Roemer and his top aides insist the budget has been cut so
much _ more than $500 million _ that further reductions could
cripple the state. Already, they worry about the declining quality
of care at state-financed charity hospitals and the ability of
cities like New Orleans to get by without the traditional state
support.
   And the next fiscal year budget has a projected deficit of $734
million. The total budget is $4.2 billion, but only $2.2 billion is
discretionary spending _ money that isn't tied to court orders or
debt payments.
   ``Cutting that much ($734 million) would shut more and more
hospitals, cut transportation money and higher education,'' said
Commissioner of Administration Dennis Stine. ``That is, in my mind,
shutting down government.''
   Still, the early talk of next June's budget is a revolutionary
concept by itself in Louisiana, a state that at times balanced its
budget for only three-quarters of the year and hoped oil prices
would go up.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Scott McCartney is the AP Southwest regional
reporter, based in Dallas.
</TEXT>
