<FIRST>r w PM-NorthTrial-Keker     02-21 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial-Keker,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lead Prosecutor a Creature of the Courtroom</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-North Trial Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Keker, the lawyer prosecuting Oliver North
in the Iran-Contra trial, has a reputation for intuitively making
the right move in a courtroom.
   In a civil lawsuit, lawyers for a bank abruptly asked one of
Keker's clients whether he would waive the attorney-client privilege
of confidentiality.
   Reacting to the unorthodox request, Keker quickly said his client
_ an investor who alleged he had been defrauded _ would agree to a
waiver if the bank was willing to waive the same privilege covering
conversations with its attorneys.
   The bank backed down.
   Representing an insurance company accused of overcharging its
customers, Keker on cross-examination asked an expert witness to
select from a stock of well over 100 files the one he considered to
be the most egregious example of overcharging.
   Robert A. Van Nest, a partner in Keker's San Francisco law firm,
recalls that Keker spent a minute familiarizing himself with the
contents of the file selected by the expert and ``then proceeded to
tear the witness apart.''
   ``Two things about John,'' said Van Nest, his tenacity and his
intuition.
   ``He doesn't let a point drop. He will fight all the way to
whatever is there.
   ``He's remarkably intuitively skilled in a courtroom. It's a
great athlete's intuition, to know where the ball is and where
everything is on the field. John has that kind of intuition. He has
an ability to respond to the evidence.''
   Keker's ability ``to kind of sense where the witness is going''
is ``a rare skill in today's lawyer,'' said Van Nest. ``So many of
us take deposition after deposition and there's nothing to predict.''
   Keker's weaker points? ``He has as many weaknesses as the San
Francisco 49ers,'' said Van Nest.
   The North case will be Keker's first as a prosecutor, but his
abilities as a defense lawyer translate easily to the other side of
the courtroom, says William T. McGivern Jr., chief assistant U.S.
Attorney for the northern district of California.
   ``He's always been aggressive and he can bring that aggression to
the prosecution side,'' said McGivern. ``He's aware of the moves of
a defense lawyer, having been one himself.''
   In short, Keker ``can try a case there's no doubt about that,''
said McGivern, who as a prosecutor has been involved in several
cases in which Keker has been a defense attorney.
   A Vietnam War veteran who served in the Marines and was wounded
in combat, Keker is a graduate of Princeton University and Yale Law
School and a founding partner of Keker &amp; Brockett in San Francisco.
   He has successfully defended movie maker George Lucas in a civil
lawsuit and won a case in which his client, a San Francisco society
figure and architect, was accused of vehicular manslaughter.
   After the Iran-Contra affair erupted in 1986, Keker sought work
with independent counsel Lawrence Walsh.
   ``John felt there was an important lesson here for Americans who
care about the democratic process and he was intent in participating
in the investigation for that reason,'' said Van Nest.
   Van Nest said Keker had concerns that those involved appeared to
have been ``hiding the ball, running foreign policy without the
consent of representatives of the people.''
   ``The political and legal implications struck me as enormous,''
Keker said of the Iran-Contra episode in an interview last year with
The Los Angeles Times.
   Keker, 45, has more than 15 years as a trial lawyer and relishes
the role.
   ``When you go to court,'' he told the Times, ``you get a chance
to be a hero, which is a thing that most people repress the desire
for. You also get a chance to fail enormously.
   ``That sort of edge is something that people who are trial
lawyers usually like. You get a chance to do the right thing. You
get a chance to do it in a stylish way.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
