<DOCNO> AP890221-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0056EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Kenya     02-21 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Kenya,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kenyans Lobby Congress To Maintain Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenyan diplomats are lobbying Congress to block
a threat by several congressmen to limit aid to Kenya because of
alleged human rights abuses.
   The effort follows some acerbic criticism by the head of the
House panel that appropriates money for foreign aid. ``It will be a
cold day in you-know-where before this committee earmarks money for
Kenya,'' said Rep. David R. Obey, D-Wis., at a recent hearing on
human rights in Africa.
   ``Earmarking'' is a method Congress uses to guarantee that select
countries receive a certain amount of foreign aid, making them
immune from administration attempts to shift assistance to other
priorities. The bulk of U.S. foreign aid is earmarked for about 20
countries, leaving the administration little room for maneuvering
with the aid.
   Economic aid for Kenya has been earmarked for the past three
years. Skillful efforts by Kenya and its lobbyists last year brought
the military component of the assistance under the protection of the
earmark too, despite Obey's objections.
   Kenya got $15 million in military aid, which accounts for about
60 percent of all U.S. military assistance to sub-Saharan Africa,
and an additional $45 million in economic and development funds.
   Kenya supporters in the administration and on Capitol Hill cite
the access granted by the strategically placed country to U.S. Navy
ships at Mombasa and to Air Force planes at its airfields as reason
enough for the financial support.
   But since last fall, when the aid was appropriated for fiscal
year 1989, several other congressmen have joined Obey, head of the
House Appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations, in
criticizing what they view as Kenya's deteriorating human rights
situation.
   William Gray, a member of Obey's committee who also serves as
chairman of the Democratic caucus in the House, issued a statement
at the same hearing critical of Kenya.
   Gray said Kenya, which had been a ``shining star in Africa and a
model for its neighbors over many years,'' had been turning in a
different direction in recent years, resulting in an erosion of its
human rights record.
   Specific charges against Kenya by human rights groups, as well as
the State Department's annual international human rights report,
include the stifling of political opposition by banning political
parties and jailing dissidents.
   Critics also object to recent constitutional amendments that
allow President Daniel arap Moi to dismiss judges and to detain
criminal suspects without trial for up to 14 days.
   But Kenyan Ambassador Denis Afande said critics fail to
understand that Kenya is acting strictly within the bounds of its
own constitution and laws. ``Kenya is trying very hard to respect
the rule of law,'' he said in an interview. ``The criticism here is
very demoralizing to my people.''
   Other African nations have much worse records than Kenya, he
said, and many Kenyans feel their country is being picked on
unfairly. ``We were very surprised by all this,'' Afande said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ChemicalLeak 1stLd-Writethru a0681 02-20 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Leak, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0681,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homes Evacuated After Chevron Plant Chemical Leak</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 10-11, `He estimated ... he said' with three grafs
to UPDATE with quotes, evacuation to continue until at least 7 a.m.; picks
up 12th graf pvs: `At least ... '</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ARTHUR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as 7,000 people were evacuated
from their homes Monday after a leaking crude oil tank at a Chevron
plant created a noxious cloud of gas with traces of hydrogen
sulfide, officials said.
   More than 20 people were treated and released at hospitals for
minor reactions to the fumes, most for fume inhalation, officials
said.
   Chevron officials said they were monitoring air quality in the
area of the leak since it was discovered in the early afternoon, and
described the gaseous release as a miminum health hazard that
created a terrible odor.
   ``Most crude oils in Texas have sulphur in them, and that means
their gas containes hydrogen sulfide, which is listed as one of the
hazardous chemicals,'' said Chevron spokesman Art Spencer.
   Hydrogen sulfide is a flammable, poisonous gas with a
characteristic odor of rotten eggs.
   ``We're doing continuous monitoring and we're finding that
there's nothing there that is hazardous to health and we're also
finding that the hydrocarbon smell in the air is lessening,''
Spencer said.
   ``But the odor got so strong that the city emergency response
unit decided to go ahead and evacuate people downwind of it,'' he
said.
   Authorities described the evacuation as the largest in recent
years in this coastal city, a heavily industrial area near the
Louisiana border.
   ``We've had some real bad fires at these plants where people were
injured and killed, but even then we never had an evacuation of this
magnitude and I've been here 28 years,'' said Port Arthur police
Sgt. Cedric Clayton.
   Sgt. Mark Blanton estimated late Monday that 5,000 to 7,000
people were evacuated from a densely populated 14- by 17-block area
on Port Arthur's west side. About 3,000 people were being housed at
three schools that were opened as emergency shelters, he said.
   Officials decided after a late meeting with Chevron officials
that the evacuation would continue until at least 7 a.m. Tuesday,
Blanton said.
   ``It appears the spill is under control, but the odor is still
present and we're going to keep it evacuated until then,'' he said,
adding that Chevron tests show a mimimal amount of hydrogen sulfide
is present.
   At least 24 people were examined at local hospitals as a result
of the leak, officials said.
   ``As far as I'm aware, plans are just to treat and release
them,'' said Doctors Hospital spokesman Dan Bleyhl. ``Nobody
suffered anything really bad.''
   A Chevron employee discovered the leak around 1:30 p.m. Monday,
officials said. The leaking tank has a capacity of about 300,000
gallons, but its exact content was not known because it was
connected to an automatic pump that fed into a refining unit,
Spencer said.
   Crews were using vacuum trucks Monday evening to remove the
spilled crude from a ditch surrounding the tank, but Spencer
estimated the task could take two or three days to complete.
</TEXT>
