<FIRST>u i PM-ScornedScholar Bjt   02-21 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scorned Scholar, Bjt,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>China's Intellectuals: Once They Ruled, Now They're ``Less Than Beggars''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young woman's scathing public reply to a college
student's classified ad seeking a wife has touched off a heated
public debate over the low social status of intellectuals in a
country that once prized learning.
   ``Wielders of pens like you are less than beggars; people like
you who take the world prize for being behind the times are nothing
but fools,'' she wrote in a letter published in the Zhejiang
Workers' News, where the lovelorn student placed his ad.
   The tale was retold Monday in the national newspaper for
intellectuals, the Guangming Daily. Neither the woman nor the
student was identified.
   ``Learning is not food on the table, ideals are not money to
spend,'' the woman wrote. ``Modern women eat money and people like
you who wield pens and don't have money can only marry 50-year-old
housewives. If you do marry a housewife, advise your children not to
go to school. Five years of elementary school is enough, everyone
nowadays uses calculators.
   ``Tell them to sell soft-shelled turtles'' _ an expensive
delicacy _ ``and they can become multimillionaires.''
   The letter, published in coastal Zhejiang province late last
year, ``touched a sensitive spot in society,'' the Guangming Daily
said.
   The Zhejiang Workers' News was inundated with phone calls and
nearly 700 letters from readers who agreed with the woman or offered
consolation to the young man.
   ``This view that learning has no value is just a temporary
phenomenon,'' wrote one reader, Shao Guoqin.
   But many teachers, researchers and writers fear their low status
has become a permanent feature of modern Chinese society. After
centuries in which scholars ruled China and learning was the only
way to advance, those with college degrees have become one of the
poorest-paid groups in cities.
   A survey by the Beijing Statistics Bureau last year found that
college graduates earned an average of $9 less each month than
illiterates.
   Most college professors earn far less than the $54 per month that
is common for factory workers.
   Scholars' traditional status first was undermined by Mao
Tse-tung's distrust of them and the revolutionary leader's emphasis
on the wisdom of simple peasants.
   Since Mao's death in 1976, intellectuals no longer face attack as
class enemies. Instead, in a society newly concerned with making
money, they have watched inflation erode the spending power of their
fixed salaries while factory workers have been encouraged with pay
bonuses.
   ``Our brains are stuffed with learning, but are our pockets
jingling?'' one college graduate wrote to the Zhejiang Workers'
News. ``We can only haggle with the peddlers _ a penny for cabbage,
two cents for radishes. Women treat college students with disdain
and some people in society look down on them _ isn't it because
there's no money in studying?''
   Surveys found that intellectuals have less leisure time than
other urban residents and live an average of 58 years, 10 years less
than the national average, due apparently to poor nutrition and hard
work.
   College students, worried about their futures, repeatedly have
put up posters protesting the poor status of intellectuals.
   The problem has been a theme of all student protests in recent
years, including rallies and a poster campaign last June at Beijing
University that began when a student was killed by a group of
unemployed youths.
   Students also have protested by dropping out. Official reports
said the number of undergraduates quitting school rose 45 percent
last year, while the number going on to postgraduate studies fell 75
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
