<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Opera     02-21 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Opera Sets New `Salome' in 20th Century</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the curtain rises on the Metropolitan
Opera's two-story new production of ``Salome,'' it looks like a set
for a Kurt Weill opera or maybe ``Cabaret.'' It cries out ``German
decadence'' in the time the Nazis came to power.
   It doesn't make ``Salome'' any more universal to set it in the
century in which Richard Strauss composed it rather than in biblical
times, but it works. Even for an audience which has heard ``Salome''
often before, the production and Eva Marton as Salome provided some
chilling moments.
   Miss Marton is exceptional. Her voice soars through dense
orchestration. Mature technique gets her there but she keeps her
voice sounding young.
   Salome is young and director Nikolaus Lehnhoff has directed
carefully in that direction. Her acting conveys that Salome doesn't
understand the lust that draws her to John the Baptist. When he
flings her from him, she has childish tantrums.
   After John the Baptist is beheaded, Miss Marton's voice becomes
mature-sounding and she seems to be bragging about a kinky lust she
now does understand.
   Two or three small excesses could be trimmed so the theatrical
experience isn't broken by inappropriate laughter. The stage is
slanted but a woman pushed away by a man probably wouldn't roll over
twice from the shove. When Miss Marton starts her dance, she removes
the long pink gloves that match her girlish gown and twirls the
gloves like a stripper before throwing them to Herod.
   Richard Cassilly sounded Wagnerian as Herod, keeping a full voice
centered to punch it authoritatively through the large orchestra.
Helga Dernesch was glamorous as Salome's mother, Herodias. Mark
Baker sounded very good as Narraboth, the young guard captivated by
Salome. He replaced Neil Rosenshein, who was ill.
   The set is like nothing else the Met has seen. The main stage
looks like the basement of a castle, with walls of black bricks, a
gate at the back and a rectangular hole in the floor, the dungeon
where John the Baptist, called Jochanaan in the opera, is kept.
   Bernd Weikl sounded commanding as Jochanaan. But his standing
against the gate, arms outstretched like Jesus on the cross, was
another effect used too often.
   Miss Marton's dance of the seven veils was a success. She began
with graceful arm motions and no veils in sight. As she danced, she
removed the skirt of her dress and sheer underskirts, throwing them
into the dungeon. She finished in a simple white dress.
   Marek Janowski conducted superbly. Gil Wechsler had spotlights
follow principals through the general gloom and put two fixed
spotlights on Jochanaan. Lehnhoff, from Hannover, Germany, was
making his Met directing debut. Set and costume designer Jurgen
Rose, a native of Bernburg-Saale, East Germany, also made his Met
debut.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
