<FIRST>u a AM-People-Jackson-Brown     02-21 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Jackson-Brown,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Pleads For ``Earliest Possible'' Release Of James Brown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BENJY HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson made an appeal Monday for the
``earliest possible'' parole of soul singer James Brown, saying
Brown had been a model prisoner and an inspiration to others.
   Jackson met with Brown for more than 90 minutes to discuss the
singer's health, his trouble with the law and his stay at the State
Park Correctional Institute near Columbia.
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, a self-styled civil rights activist from
New York and longtime protege of Brown, met Jackson at the airport.
Sharpton asked to join the meeting with Brown, but South Carolina
corrections officials refused.
   Neither Sharpton nor Jackson was not on Brown's list of approved
visitors, but Jackson had received prior permission, authorities
said. The Chicago minister and South Carolina native said he wanted
to meet with Brown and learn more about the case.
   He said he had spoken with Gov. Carroll Campbell and Sen. Strom
Thurmond, R-S.C., to see what could be done for Brown.
   Jackson said his intention was not to criticize any of the legal
aspects surrounding the case, including the six-year sentence Brown
received.
   ``The appeal really is for mercy,'' Jackson said.
   He said he also wanted to clear up misconceptions about Brown's
convictions. Jackson said Brown is concerned that the public
mistakenly thinks he was charged with the use or possession of drugs
and that he shot at police.
   Brown, in a statement read by Jackson, said, ``I am not on
drugs.''
   The 55-year-old entertainer, who lives in Beech Island, is
serving a six-year sentence at the minimum-security prison after
being convicted in January of an array of charges stemming from a
two-state, high-speed chase on Sept. 24.
   Judge Hubert Long said then that Brown must undergo examination
and treatment for any drug or alcohol problem he might have as part
of his sentence on the South Carolina conviction. Brown was
convicted in Georgia and South Carolina.
   Authorities said the chase began after Brown disrupted an
insurance seminar in an Augusta, Ga., office building by walking in
with a shotgun. Before officers could arrive, Brown left the
building and a chase began.
   Brown pleaded guilty in Georgia to having no state license tag,
reckless driving, driving with a suspended license, attempting to
flee or elude police, carrying a deadly weapon to a public
gathering, simple assault and improper lane change.
   He was fined $1,000 and given a six-year sentence that runs
concurrently with the six-year sentenced he received in South
Carolina for failing to stop for authorities during the chase.
   Brown will be eligible for parole in South Carolina in August
1991. But Georgia authorities say their state law provides Brown
must serve until March 10, 1992 on the six-year sentence before he
would be eligible for parole.
   Jackson said prison officials told him Brown was an inspiration
to other prisoners and to corrections department employees.
   Brown is popular with other inmates, said Francis Archibald,
director of the South Carolina Department of Corrections. Some
prisoners have had their pictures taken with the man who is known as
the ``Godfather of Soul,'' Archibald said.
   Brown works in the kitchen and sings in a church choir at the
center, he said.
 
</TEXT>
