<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     02-21 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Down in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged at the Tokyo Stock Exchange on
Tuesday, but the dollar finished higher against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected shares, a 3.69-point
winner for a record close of 32,177.08 on Monday, lost 197.00
points, or 0.61 percent, to finish the day's session at 31,980.08.
   The dollar closed at 127.15 yen, up 1.40 yen from Monday's
125.75-yen finish. The currency opened at 126.60 yen and was traded
in a range of 126.60-127.35 yen.
   Dealers said many market participants hesitated to make major
moves before Congressional testimony by U.S. Federal Reserve Board
Chairman Alan Greenspan scheduled for later Tuesday.
   They added that the dollar moved higher because speculative
investors bought up the currency in anticipation of a tighter U.S.
economic policy.
   On the stock exchange, profit-taking erased earlier gains made by
the index, which had won about 48.40 points shortly after the market
opened for trading.
   Dealers said many speculative investors backed off in fear that
the main market barometer may rise too sharply.
   Attention focused on medium-sized shares, they said.
</TEXT>
