<FIRST>u a AM-AirForceCrash 3rdLd-Writethru a0448 02-21 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Force Crash, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0448,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cargo Plane Crashes in Florida Panhandle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf, ``It remained ...,'' to UPDATE
with details of search, ADD that there was bad weather in area; picks up
5th graf pvs, ``The plane ...;'' May stand for AMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HURLBURT FIELD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force cargo plane with eight
people on board crashed and exploded in a swampy forest just north
of this base in the Florida Panhandle, officials said.
   The C-141 Starlifter cargo plane left from Norton Air Force Base
in Southern California, refueled in Colorado Springs, Colo., and was
on its final approach to land here when air traffic controllers from
adjacent Eglin Air Force Base suddenly lost radio and radar contact
around 8 p.m., Air Force officials said.
   Army Rangers reported an explosion about four miles north of the
field, said Airman Joe Geraci, duty officer at the airfield.
   It remained unknown early Tuesday whether there were any
survivors, said Hurlburt spokesman Lt. Doug Kinneard. Seven people
on board were crew members and one was a civilian passenger,
Kinneard said.
   Military and civilian fire and rescue units reached the crash
site by 10:10 p.m., Kinneard said.
   ``It's an extremely rugged area,'' Capt. Thom Connell, a Hurlburt
spokesman said early Tuesday. ``They're still working to get to the
actual wreck itself.''
   He said a helicopter had been dispatched to the site.
   The area around the base was hit by strong thunderstorms and
flashes of lighting through much of the night. Air Force officials
said it was too early to tell if the bad weather played a part in
the crash.
   The plane crashed in a forested swamp in the middle of the
testing range at Eglin, the Air Force's headquarters for non-nuclear
arms testing, the spokesman said.
   ``They've found one of the engines in a creek,'' said Lynn
Jurkovic, a dispatcher at the nearby Fort Walton Beach Fire
Department, which sent three rescue units to the scene.
   The C-141, capable of carrying up to 200 troops, belonged to the
63rd Military Airlift Wing at Norton, which is about 60 miles east
of Los Angeles, said base spokesman Capt. Gary A. Jacobs.
   The names of those aboard will be withheld pending notification
of next of kin, Jacobs said.
</TEXT>
