<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MallardCapital Bjt   02-21 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mallard Capital, Bjt,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tiny Illinois Town Is Duck Dealer To The World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the 1960s, Leo Whalen watched a news
report about the home of the nation's 36th president and decided
that Lyndon B. Johnson's ranch needed a few ducks.
   So he wrote a letter and proposed a trade: mallards to put in the
water on Johnson's property in exchange for a Lone Star LBJ Ranch
hat.
   ``It seems that you have a deal,'' LBJ's aide, Earl Deathe Jr.,
replied.
   The presidential pact was a feather in Whalen's cap, but no big
deal for his Whistling Wings Inc., beak broker to the world. The
Whalen family is to mallards what the Wrigleys are to gum. Only more
so.
   Each year, 200,000 mallards are born in this town of 1,100, which
lies 10 miles east of the Mississippi River in the northwestern
corner of Illinois. They're sold to conservation groups, university
researchers, hunting clubs, foreign palaces and even a few
restaurants _ around the globe.
   ``We originally started as a hunting club, but it never really
got off the ground,'' said the founder's son, Bill Whalen, who
shares duck-keeping duties with his sister, Marianne Whalen Murphy.
   ``Dad brought the idea home from Europe after World War II. But
at that time we were too far from any major city to draw hunters, so
we diversified and simply went into raising the birds,'' he said.
Because mallards are the most popular hunting ducks, Whistling Wings
stuck with them.
   ``We've grown up with it,'' says Mrs. Murphy, ``and it's grown
with us. ``When you pick up the phone you never know who you're
going to be talking to.''
   Once it was a caller from Japan, inquiring about ducks for
Emperor Hirohito. Chilean officials asked if they could send a plane
to get some eggs, and the Brookfield Zoo in suburban Chicago bought
a duck each week for an 11-foot anaconda snake.
   ``It just wouldn't take anything else,'' said zoo reptile curator
Ray Pawley.
   Whistling Wings has 4,000 breeding ducks. Each hen produces at
least 40 eggs that hatch in incubators after 27 days.
   Ducks sell for $1.55 to $15.50 depending on the age of the duck
and size of the order. Younger ducks cost less.
   Mrs. Murphy and her brother deal ducks out of a small office in
the center of Hanover. A few miles south, near the town sign that
welcomes travelers to the ``World's Mallard Duck Capital,'' is the
farm where ducks are kept in pens during late fall and winter.
   When the weather turns warm, most newborn mallards are driven to
a chain of small, private lakes on 300 hilly acres in Jo Daviess
County.
   ``We want to raise them in their own environment,'' Bill Whalen
explained as he took a visitor around the scenic duck territory, icy
and bare in winter.
   By truck or plane, they're shipped to 48 states and points beyond
_ sometimes unintentionally.
   ``Mom took some into Chicago once for a flight to Florida,'' Mrs.
Murphy said. ``The plane was hijacked to Cuba. One-thousand birds
headed to Tallahassee became Cuban ducks.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
