<DOCNO> AP890221-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-ParachutingDeath     02-21 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Parachuting Death,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record-Holding Parachutist Dies In Jump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHERIDAN, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Frenchman who made a world-record 14,000
parachute jumps fell to his death when his chute didn't open
properly, officials said.
   Roch Pierre Charmet, making his seventh jump of the day Monday
from Pacific Parachute Center, plunged into a stack of lumber at a
lumberyard near the airport here, according to Yamhill County
sheriff's Sgt. John Kowalik.
   The 59-year-old Montlhery man had jumped out of an airplane at
2,500 feet, said Pacific Parachute founder Ted Mayfield.
   ``He was just tumbling and falling to 500 feet,'' Mayfield said.
``I saw his pilot chute come out and then a ball of garbage. It was
just like the parachute didn't inflate. It was just a big ball.''
   Mayfield said Charmet had folded his own parachute.
   Charmet learned to jump in 1958 as a paratrooper with a French
army unit in Algiers. An instructor with the Parachute Institute of
France, Charmet broke the world record in Sheridan last year when he
made his 14,000th jump, Mayfield said.
   The Guinness Book of World Records lists Charmet as the man with
the most jumps. Valentina Zakoretskaya of the Soviet Union, who has
made 8,000 jumps, holds the record for women.
   Charmet had been staying at the Sheridan Airport since the
beginning of this month, Mayfield said. He had come to Sheridan,
about 45 miles southwest of Portland, through a program sponsored by
the Portland Parachute Club and Mayfield's organization.
   Charmet's death was the 10th at the center since February 1974,
Mayfield said.
</TEXT>
