<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-21 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Drop in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading stock index today
plunged from its latest record high, and the dollar gained sharply
against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 197.00 points, or 0.61
percent, closing at 31,980.08. That was its first closing below the
32,000-yen level since Feb. 14, when it ended at 31,982.89.
   It had set a record high closing of 32,177.08 on Monday.
   The plunge in the index resulted mainly from the dollar's quick
rise on the foreign exchange market, said an analyst with Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   He also said prospects for a tighter economic policy in the
United States, possibly leading to higher interest rates,
discouraged investors from buying stock while awaiting Congressional
testimony by U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
scheduled later today.
   Expectations of higher interest rates generally discourage stock
buying, the analyst added.
   In addition, he said, institutional investors feared the Nikkei
had risen too high recently and were selling to take profits.
   In active trading, with first section volume estimated at 1.2
billion shares, steel and real estate shares were among losers.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 127.15 yen, up 1.40
yen from Monday's 125.75-yen finish. The dollar opened at 126.60
yen, its low for the day, and went as high as 127.35 yen.
   The dollar's sharp rise was prompted by expectations of Greenspan
suggesting a tighter U.S. economic policy later today, dealers said.
   Higher U.S. interest rates tend to make dollar-denominated
investments more attractive to foreigners.
   Some traders avoided major moves before Greenspan's testimony,
dealers added.
</TEXT>
