<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     02-21 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWBURGH, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moose is keeping a vigil near four mares
on a farm here, but the horses' owner says the animal is lonely, not
lovestruck.
   The yearling moose appeared in the area Thursday and moved close
to John Calderwood's farm Sunday.
   ``He's not going to leave now,'' Calderwood said Monday.
   Calderwood and a state game warden believe the moose is male, but
they don't think it has amorous intentions.
   ``The game warden said he probably wandered off from his mother
and is lonely,'' said Calderwood, who raises horses on his Burnt
Swamp Farm.
   The mares aren't fond of the onlooker and move to the far side of
their enclosed pasture whenever the moose approaches the fence, he
said.
   ``They're not letting him out of their sight,'' Calderwood added.
   Calderwood said he isn't feeding the animal because he doesn't
want to encourage it to stick around. He said he hopes the moose
will depart before his mares begin going into heat in the next three
weeks.
   If a Vermont farmer's experience in October 1986 is any guide,
Calderwood could have a long wait. A lovesick moose wandered onto
Larry Carrara's farm in Shrewsbury, Vt., became enamored with his
Hereford cow, Jessica, and stayed for 76 days. The romance attracted
attention worldwide and prompted a Nashville, Tenn., man to write a
song about the unlikely couple.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An effort to have the magpie declared the
state bird was beaten back by ruffled lawmakers, but only after a
legislator proposed a unique designation: state scavenger.
   State Sen. Bill Yellowtail extolled the magpie's virtues in
pushing a bill to have it replace the meadowlark as the state bird.
   He said the magpie is self-sufficient and hardy, like Montanans,
and praised it for staying in the state during bad weather as well
as good, unlike the migrating meadowlark.
   ``The meadowlark right now reclines on a Bahama beach, bedecked
in sunglasses and Bermuda shorts and drinking a mint julep,''
Yellowtail said.
   But other lawmkers denounced the magpie's eating habits and its
noisy chattering.
   Sen. Judy Jacobson said legislators who live in the capital for
part of the year shouldn't criticize those who head south for the
winter.
   ``Where would you be living today if people in Helena didn't go
south for the winter?'' she asked. ``We'd all be in tents on the
Capitol lawn.''
   Jacobson suggested the meadowlark retain its post and the magpie
be designated as the state scavenger, a move the Senate approved
34-14.
   ``I'd like to honor both of these birds in the way that they
ought to be honored,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
