<FIRST>u i PM-Iran-Rushdie 1stLd-Writethru a0477 02-21 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Rushdie, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0477,a0478,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Recalls Ambassadors From Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: COMBINES urgent series. ADDS that report does no specify the
countries from which Iranian ambassadors were withdrawn, background. ADDS
byline. No pickup. ^By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran recalled all its ambassadors from
Common Market countries today, a day after the 12 European countries
recalled their envoys to protest Ayatollah Khomeini's execution
order against novelist Salman Rushdie.
   The move by the Foreign Ministry was in direct reponse to the
Common Market foreign ministers' decision in Brussels, Belgium, on
Monday to recall their ambassadors from Tehran, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
   IRNA did not specify the countries from which the Iranian
ambassadors were withdrawn and it was not immediately known in what
Common Market countries Iran has maintained ambassadors.
   In Britain, for example, Tehran has been represented by a charge
d'affaires.
   Iran's Foreign Ministry said in a statement that respect for
Islam and its values will remain an inviolable principle in
relations between Iran and other countries, IRNA said.
   The communique said that Khomeini's week-old order for Rushdie's
death for blaspheming Islam with his book ``The Satanic Verses'' was
a ``consensus judgement of all Moslem leaders throught the world,''
the agency reported.
   The dispatch, monitored in Nicosia, said the Foreign Ministry
deplored the refusal of the European community to condemn the book
and criticized the community's support for a work it said blasphemes
Islam.
   Britain announced Monday it would withdraw all its diplomats from
Tehran and request that Iran recall its representatives in London.
   Khomeini had refused to accept Rushdie's apology for offending
Moslems with the book, affirming his call for Moslems to kill the
naturalized Briton, who is reportedly in hiding under police guard.
   Britain stopped short of actually severing ties, while its
partners in the Common Market said they would recall their envoys
for consultations.
   Many Moslems say ``The Satanic Verses'' portrays the prophet
Mohammed's wives as prostitutes and suggests that he _ rather than
God _ wrote the Koran, Islam's holy book.
   The novel has been banned in Pakistan, Bangladesh, Iran, India,
Egypt and South Africa. Publishers in France, West Germany, Greece
and Turkey have canceled plans to publish it and it has been pulled
from bookstore shelves in Japan. Many U.S. bookstores have also
removed the novel from display.
   The novel has also prompted Moslem protests around the world. In
Pakistan and India earlier this month, seven people were killed in
protests against it.
</TEXT>
