<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0602EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BubbleBoy-Anniversary     02-21 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bubble Boy-Anniversary,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Years After Bubble's Boy Death, Babies With Same Disorder Surviving</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY17 of Feb. 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experimental bone-marrow transplant that ended
in death five years ago for David, the ``boy in the plastic
bubble,'' is helping other children with the same immune system
disorder to survive without isolation.
   ``His life certainly had an impact on mankind. If only our lives
could have as much of an impact,'' said Dr. William Shearer, David's
primary physician at Texas Children's Hospital.
   David was born with severe combined immune deficiency syndrome,
or SCIDS, a disorder that left him without protection against
disease. At the time, children with the disorder died because there
was no treatment.
   Doctors placed David in a clear plastic bubble immediately after
birth and increasingly bigger bubbles as he grew to protect him from
germs while researchers worked on a treatment.
   David, whose family name was never released to the public, died
Feb. 22, 1984, of blood cancer contracted shortly after he underwent
a bone-marrow transplant designed to free him from the bubble.
   No other child lived like David and, because of the treatment,
there has not been another ``bubble boy.''
   Today, at Texas Children's Hospital, many children with SCIDS are
being treated successfully with the improved transplant treatment,
Shearer said. A handful of hospitals across the country also perform
the transplant.
   Gone are the strict sterile conditions that made David a prisoner
of his disorder. Children with the condition stay in the hospital
before and after transplant. Visitors need only wash their hands and
be healthy.
   SCIDS also is being identified earlier, thanks to pediatricians
who are more aware of the disorder. ``When they see children who
have unusual infections, they think maybe this child has a similar
problem (to David),'' Shearer said.
   About one out of 100,000 babies have SCIDS.
   The treatment involves taking about a quart of bone marrow from a
donor, either a sibling or a parent, and injecting it into a vein.
If the transplant is successful, cells known as lymphocytes in the
marrow form the core of a healthy immune system.
   Sixteen children have been treated at Texas Children's in the
past five years, including one boy who successfully underwent the
procedure while David was dying. Eleven are still alive.
   Three-month-old Ana Ruth Calderon was released from the hospital
three weeks ago after receiving a marrow transplant.
   ``She is fat and sassy, doing well,'' Shearer said.
   Shearer said neither he nor David's parents look back at whether
anything could have been done differently.
   ``They went for a chance at the time when the technology was
right,'' the doctor said, ``and for one reason or another, it worked
out in a very sad way.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0049 </DOCNO>
