<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-21 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Both Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was stronger in late morning European
trading today. Gold prices also were slightly higher.
   Foreign currency dealers said they did not expect much movement
before U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's scheduled
testimony before Congress later in the day.
   The dollar rose in Asian and early European dealings on
expectations Greenspan would emphasize the Fed's commitment to
fighting inflation, they said.
   But the run started to lose steam midmorning because of the
market's reluctance to take large positions ahead of what is
considers to be the key event of the week, they said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.40 yen to a closing 127.15. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 127.35 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8535 West German marks, up from 1.8435
   _1.5770 Swiss francs, up from 1.5683
   _6.3113 French francs, up from 6.2825
   _2.0920 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0820
   _1,358.25 Italian lire, up from 1,350.50
   _1.1895 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1897
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7560, cheaper for buyers
than $1.7665 late Monday.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price for
gold at midmorning today of $382.75 a troy ounce, unchanged from the
opening bid but up slightly from late Monday's bid of $382.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $382.70, up from $382.20 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 33 cents to close at a bid
$384.34.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.93 a troy ounce,
unchanged from Monday.
