<FIRST>r i PM-Gorbachev     02-21 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev to Go to Chernobyl for First Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will for the first
time visit the Chernobyl power plant, site of the world's worst the
nuclear disaster, during his current trip to the Ukraine, Radio
Moscow reported today.
   Gorbachev found out Monday in Kiev, the republic's capital, that
the dangers of nuclear power are still very much on the minds of
Ukrainians.
   In a street encounter broadcast by Soviet television, an elderly
woman asked Gorbachev why another nuclear power plant was being
built in the Crimea.
   The area contains some of the country's most popular beach
resorts and is home to 2 million people.
   Gorbachev said he was aware of worries about the plant's safety.
He also said American specialists who helped plan nuclear power
plants in earthquake-prone Japan had been asked to study the Crimean
facility.
   ``Construction is under way,'' Gorbachev said. ``But if the
conclusion (of the specialists) is that it is not advisable to build
a station there, then it will be turned into a training center for
personnel, not an atomic power station.''
   He assured the woman that the government now takes a cautious
approach to nuclear power.
   Radio Moscow said today that Gorbachev was preparing visits to
Chernobyl and Slavutich, a nearby town built to house plant workers.
   The broadcast did not say exactly when Gorbachev would be at
Chernobyl, where an explosion and fire at a nuclear reactor on April
26, 1986 killed at least 31 people and sent a radioactive cloud
around the world.
   Gorbachev today arrived in Lvov, a center of railway engineering,
automobile assembly and oil refining. The city of 753,000 residents
is about 260 miles west of Kiev, where Gorbachev began his trip
Monday.
   Last month, 10 Soviet scientists wrote a letter to the Communist
Party newspaper Pravda calling for construction of the Crimean plant
to be stopped. They said it was not designed to withstand
earthquakes of the magnitude possible there.
   Since the Chernobyl accident, the Soviets have moved away from
complete faith in the safety of nuclear power, and public opposition
to it has grown.
   Nikolai Lukonin, the nuclear power minister, announced in
December that six projects to build nuclear plants or add more
reactors at existing stations had been scrapped because of
earthquake danger or tougher standards.
   The Soviet press is also increasingly reporting on the growing
health problems from Chernobyl. Last week, Moscow News said cancer
cases have doubled and calves are often born without heads and limbs
in a region 30 miles from Chernobyl where people were not evacuated
during the disaster.
   Also at Monday's street encounter in Kiev, Gorbachev said the
confusing electoral system he ushered into law in December already
needs reform.
   ``We will review the results of the campaign, carry out the
necessary corrrections,'' Gorbachev said. He was not specific.
   The new law creates a 2,250-member Congress of People's Deputies,
a two-thirds of whose members will be elected by the public on March
26.
   One-third of the deputies, however, will be chosen by the
Communist Party, its affiliates, unions, social and political
organizations.
</TEXT>
