<FIRST>r a PM-HousingProjectDeath     02-21 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Project Death,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Tapes Dispute Paramedics In Boy's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for the mother of a boy who died
during an asthma attack says emergency dispatcher tapes prove
paramedics were not attacked before they refused to enter a housing
project to help the child.
   However, the speech pathologist who prepared a transcript of the
tapes found a key segment was unintelligible, and neither supported
nor contradicted the paramedics' contention that they were driven
away by a barrage of eggs and rocks.
   The 9-year-old boy's mother, Sharon Jarnagin, has said there was
no such attack on the ambulance on Dec. 12, when her son, Carl, was
stricken.
   Her attorney, David Kremin, contends that the tape recordings,
which were released publicly at a news conference Monday, refute the
Fire Department paramedics' version, which has been supported by
city officials.
   On the recording, neither paramedic says anything about being the
target of missiles, Kremin said.
   The Fire Department, which oversees emergency medical activities,
``is still vigorously defending the paramedics and their actions,''
spokesman Scott LaGreca said after the tapes and transcripts were
released.
   ``It was a sad, sad case but we feel our people were correct in
their actions and our policy is sound.''
   He declined to comment further, citing the $60 million lawsuit
filed by Mrs. Jarnagin against the department and the city.
   Harry Dubnick, an attorney for the city, said Kremin was wrong.
   ``There's no doubt in my mind. They did the proper thing,'' he
said of the paramedics.
   But Kremin said more than a dozen witnesses will swear that
nothing was thrown at the rescue workers.
   The recordings cover about 32 minutes of telephone and radio
conversations among the two paramedics, the ambulance dispatcher,
the Police Department and the boy's relatives, who made eight calls
to an emergency number Dec. 12.
   According to the transcript Northwestern University speech
pathologist Thomas D. Carrell prepared from recordings Kremin said
he had obtained from city authorities, Ms. Jarnagin initially called
at 4:14 p.m.
   She requested an ambulance at the Dearborn Homes housing project
on the South Side, saying her son was having a severe asthma attack
and losing consciousness.
   About five minutes later, an ambulance was dispatched, followed
by a police squad car, the tapes show.
   At 4:28 p.m., one of the paramedics radioed the dispatcher that
they were leaving the housing project.
   In Carrell's transcript, the exchange goes:
   Ambulance: Uh, we had a (unintelligible) we're leaving the scene.
   Dispatcher: I'll get the police in there.
   Ambulance: No, we're not hanging around. We're leaving the scene.
   There is no indication on the tapes that officers in the police
car saw any attack on the ambulance.
   At 4:30, Mrs. Jarnagin called again, sobbing.
   Mother: There was an ambulance here and they left! They didn't
even come upstairs.
   After getting the address, the dispatcher tells her: You know
why? People were beating up the paramedics, ma'am.
   Mother: Huh? What people? ... There was no one out there. My son
went out there.
   According to the tapes, the police officers entered the
fifth-floor apartment minutes later and radioed at 4:32 p.m. to
request an ambulance.
   The same ambulance was directed to return to the housing project,
the tapes show. The unconscious boy was picked up and taken to a
hospital, where he died.
</TEXT>
