<FIRST>r a PM-WashQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0474 02-21 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wash Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0474,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Golden, Colo.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Minor Quake Rattle Seattle Suburbs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: PRECEDES to Seattle; LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with police
receiving no phone calls, background on last quake; picks up penultimate
graf, ``The Richter ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small earthquake rattled suburbs south of here,
but there were no reports of damages or injuries, authorities said.
   The quake at 10:48 p.m. Monday was centered about 20 miles
southwest of Seattle and registered 3.0 on the Richter scale,
according to the National Earthquake Information Center at Golden,
Colo.
   The qauke was felt in Federal Way, Renton, Enumclaw and Skyway,
the center said.
   State Patrol offices in Bellevue and Tacoma, however, said they
received no phone calls from residents living in the area.
   The last quake in the Puget Sound area occurred last Tuesday, and
was centered near Mount Vernon about 60 miles north of Seattle. It
measured 4.0 on the Richter scale and also caused no damage or
injuries.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the scale can cause slight damage.
</TEXT>
