<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0905EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-HungerStrike     02-21 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Hunger Strike,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Frees 50 Detainees, But Hunger Strikes Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government freed 50 more
detainees today after hunger strikes were halted at two prisons, but
scores of detainees continued to fast elsewhere and police said 20
were hospitalized.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok told Parliament he had signed
release warrants for 50 detainees. He did not say how many took part
in hunger strikes to demand they be freed or brought to court.
   About 225 detainees still are refusing food at prisons in the
southern cities of Durban, Pietermaritzburg and East London, their
lawyers said.
   Police reported 20 hunger strikers in East London were
hospitalized Monday, four days after they and six fellow detainees
began fasting.
   Civil rights lawyers said about 200 detainees in Durban and
Pietermaritzburg have begun hunger strikes in the past two weeks.
Vlok has agreed to meet lawyers for the detainees, but no date has
been set.
   The first wave of hunger strikes started Jan. 23 and involved
nearly 300 detainees held without charge in Port Elizabeth and at
Diepkloof Prison outside Johannesburg. Some detainees at those
prisons went three weeks without food then broke their fast after
Vlok promised to review their cases and release ``a substantial
number.''
   Eight detainees were freed Friday.
   Vlok has won widepsread praise, even from anti-government
leaders, for agreeing to meet with lawyers, parents and clergymen
representing the hunger strikers. He told Parliament he would
continue these discussions ``and I trust the entire hunger strike
will soon be something of the past.''
   The Rev. Frank Chikane, general secretary of the South African
Council of Churches, on Monday visited a Johannesburg hospital where
some Diepkloof hunger strikers are recovering. He said it was
possible the fast would resume if the detainees were dissatisfied
about the numbers released in the next two weeks.
   Many of the hunger strikers have been held more than two years.
   Under the 32-month-old national state of emergency, police can
arrest anyone they believe may be a danger to the public safety.
Vlok decides periodically, based on police reports, whether the
detainee should remain incarcerated. Detainees do not have to be
brought to court and charged, and they can be kept in custody for as
long as the government pleases.
   Monitoring groups say more than 30,000 people, mostly blacks,
have been detained during the state of emergency. Vlok has never
given a total figure, but he said two weeks ago that there were
fewer than 1,000 people in detention at that time.
</TEXT>
