<FIRST>r a PM-CheeverStories     02-21 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cheever Stories,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules That Cheever's Widow Has Fulfilled Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Illinois judge ruled that the widow of writer
John Cheever has done her part to settle a contract dispute with an
independent publishing house over a collection of her husband's
stories.
   The order from Cook County Circuit Judge Roger J. Kiley Jr. says
Mary Cheever fulfilled her obligation to Academy Chicago Publishers
by providing it 15 uncollected stories of her choosing, The New York
Times reported today.
   The publisher had planned a volume of 68 stories but was stopped
from bringing it out last year when Mrs. Cheever sued, contending
the August 1987 contract was invalid because promises to her of
consultation and control over the book's content had not been kept.
   Last September, Kiley ruled that the contract was valid. He also
proposed a compromise under which Mrs. Cheever would submit 12 to 15
of the 68 stories. Last week, he ruled that the stories she
submitted fulfilled that obligation.
   Thomas Leavens, a lawyer for the publishers, said Academy Chicago
had not decided whether to appeal.
   Mrs. Cheever's lawyer, Martin Garbus, said she was now free to
edit her husband's stories in a collection of her own.
   Cheever, who was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for fiction in 1979,
died in 1983.
</TEXT>
