<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan-Resignation     02-21 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan-Resignation,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Quits Over Government's War Stance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Abdel-Magid Khalil has
resigned, charging the government's reluctance to negotiate an end
to Sudan's southern civil war has isolated the country, two
newspapers reported today.
   The independent newspaper Al-Ayam said Khalil quit after
returning from an unannounced visit to Jordan and Iraq, where he
apparently was refused new military and financial aid.
   Al-Adwa, another independent newspaper, said Khalil's letter of
resignation charged ``the foreign policy adopted by the government
does not lead to a unified internal front nor to stability, and has
also led to the isolation of the country both in the Arab and
outside world.''
   The newspapers quoted Information Minister Beshir Omar as saying
Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi has accepted Khalil's resignation. He did
not name a successor. Al-Ayam speculated that Mahdi will assume the
defense portfolio he held from the time he was elected prime
minister in 1986 to June 1988, when he appointed Khalil.
   Mahdi canceled a trip to Japan to attend the funeral of Emperor
Hirohito because of the ``emergency circumstances,'' according to
Omar's statement. Vice President Idris Banna and the five-member
Supreme Council will represent him at the funeral, the statement
said.
   Khalil's letter said government policies ``have weakened the
country's ability to acquire military and economic assistance ...
   ``The government's rejection of the peace plan and its reluctance
to move in the direction of peace in the country has affected
Sudan's reputation in the outside world.''
   The United States this month urged an end to the almost
6-year-old civil war and said it would try to promote a peace
settlement. Washington has linked further U.S. aid to ending the
war, and other friendly Western and Arab donors say there is an
urgent need to end the fighting.
   John Garang, the U.S.-educated renegade colonel who leads the
Sudan People's Liberation Army, signed a peace plan Nov. 16 with
Mohammed Osman Mirghani, leader of Sudan's Democratic Unionist
Party. At the time, the Democratic Unionists belonged to the
governing coalition of Mahdi's Umma party and the National Islamic
Front of Moslem fundamentalist Hassan Turabi.
   Although his party endorsed the plan, Mahdi refused to let the
government act on it. In December, the Unionists left the coalition
because of the government's position on the peace plan and its
handling of the economy. Mahdi formed a new government in February
with the National Islamic Front as the junior partner.
   The front rejects a key rebel demand _ abolition of harsh Islamic
laws that are applied to all Sudanese regardless of religion.
   Sudan is divided into the minority Christians and animists of the
south, a black people, and the dominant Moslems of the north, who
are Arabic.
   The Sudanese economy is faltering under the $1 million a day
costs of the civil war, a $13-billion foreign debt and decreasing
foreign aid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
