<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-IranAssets     02-21 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Iran Assets,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Agrees To Review Ruling On Iranian Assets Procedure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to referee a
dispute between the U.S. government and American businesses stemming
from the 1981 settlement of the Iran hostage crisis.
   The court said it will review a ruling that businesses recovering
money from Iran's government do not have to pay a portion of it to
the U.S. government.
   The financial deal that freed the 52 American hostages from Iran
included release by the U.S. government of billions of dollars in
frozen Iranian assets. The settlement also set up a process
permitting those with claims against Iran to take them to an
international tribunal.
   The Supreme Court in 1981 upheld the power of former President
Jimmy Carter to approve the settlement.
   That question was not at issue in the case acted on today, in
which Sperry Corp. and Sperry World Trade Inc. made a claim against
Iran.
   The companies leased computer systems to Iran during the 1970s,
before the hostage crisis severed relations between the United
States and Iran.
   After the hostages were freed in January 1981, the Sperry
corporations were awarded $2.8 million by the international tribunal
set up to handle claims against Iran.
   Congress in 1985 passed a law requiring those who win such claims
to pay to the federal government 1.5 percent of the first $5 million
recovered and 1 percent of amounts over that.
   The fee is to reimburse governmental expenses in helping resolve
the claims.
   The government said the Sperry corporations owed it $42,000.
   A federal appeals court here ruled last August that the fee is an
unconstitutional seizure of private property by the government.
   ``Whatever (the fee) was thought to be, it was a taking of
Sperry's money to help settle the national crisis, a burden the
government must bear on behalf of all of us,'' the appeals court
said.
   Justice Department lawyers, in seeking Supreme Court review, said
tens of millions of dollars are at stake. Some $12.7 million already
has been deducted by the government from awards to successful
claimants.
   The government's appeal said it is reasonable to require those
that win claims against Iran to defray the $4 million the U.S.
government spends each year to help operate the Iran claims process.
   The case is U.S. vs. Sperry Corp., 88-952.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0071 </DOCNO>
