<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Guardian,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Long Island Guardian Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today threw out an emergency
request by anti-abortion activists who had sought to prevent a Long
Island, N.Y., man from having an abortion performed on his comatose
wife.
   The abortion was performed earlier this month after state courts
and Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall rejected the request.
   In a highly unusual move, the anti-abortion activists persisted
in seeking Supreme Court action even after the case was made moot by
the abortion. They sought help from Supreme Court Justice Antonin
Scalia, who referred it to the full court.
   John Short and John Broderick of the Long Island Right-to-Life
group, had challenged rulings that appointed Martin Klein of Upper
Brookville as legal guardian of his wife, Nancy.
   That designation allowed him to order the abortion.
   Mrs. Klein, 32, fell into a coma after suffering brain damage in
a car accident Dec. 13. She was about 18 weeks pregnant when the
abortion was performed.
   Her husband had been told by doctors that Mrs. Klein would have a
better chance of survivla if the fetus she was carrying was aborted.
   The case is Short vs. Klein, A-641.
