<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Freeholders     02-21 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Freeholders,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Agrees To Hear Challenge To Makeup of St. Louis Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether people who do not own property may be excluded from
membership on a public body authorized to recommend a reorganization
of local government in the St. Louis area.
   The court said it will hear a challenge to the make-up of the St.
Louis City-St. Louis County Board of Freeholders.
   The board of freeholders was created to write a proposed charter
for reorganizing the city and county government structure. The board
also was empowered to recommend new taxes to finance the city and
county governments.
   Any proposals by the board would be submitted to the voters in a
referendum.
   Board members were ppointed by the mayor of St. Louis, the county
executive and the governor of Missouri.
   State Representative Robert J. Quinn, a St. Louis County resident
who does not own property, said his rights were violated by a state
constitutional requirement limiting membership on the freeholder
board to property owners.
   Quinn, suing for himself and all others in the city and county
who do not own property, said the exclusion violated the U.S.
Constitution's guarantee of equal protection under law.
   But the Missouri Supreme Court ruled last September that the
federal constitutional protection does not apply because the
freeholder board does not have ``general governmental powers.''
   ``The board of freeholders serves only to recommend a plan of
reorganization to the voters of St. Louis City and St. Louis
County,'' the state court said. ``It can recommend ... property
taxes and sales taxes, but it cannot levy and collect them. In sum,
the board of freeholders has no general governmental powers.''
   The state court said the St. Louis case is not covered by past
U.S. Supreme Court rulings that struck down property ownership as a
qualification for membership on a city school board or regional
airport commission.
   The case is Quinn vs. Millsap, 88-1048.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-SummaryTrials     02-21 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Summary Trials,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Newspapers Open-Trial Plea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court let stand rulings that the
public has no right to attend the so-called ``summary jury trials''
held in some legal disputes.
   The justices, without comment, rejected arguments by newspapers
in three Ohio cities that trial judges should be barred from
conducting such proceedings in secret.
   The newspapers' lawyers had asked the high court to rule, for the
first time, that the Constitution provides a public right of access
to judicial proceedings in civil, or non-criminal, cases.
   The court in 1980 ruled that the public has a right to attend
criminal trials even when defendants object. The justices since have
expanded that ruling to cover jury selection and pretrial
proceedings in criminal cases.
   But the court never has ruled that such a right of access exists
as well for civil trials and proceedings.
   The appeal acted on today stems from a 1984 lawsuit by three Ohio
utilities against General Electric Co., over the design and
construction of the William H. Zimmer Nuclear Power Plant.
   The suit alleged that GE sold the utilties _ Dayton Power and
Light, Columbus and Southern Electric and Cincinnati Gas and
Electric Co. _ a nuclear reactor container system it knew was
incapable of ``operating in a safe manner.''
   U.S. District Judge S. Arthur Spiegel presided over a summary
jury trial in the case, in which lawyers for both sides presented
summaries of their evidence.
   The jury's verdict in such proceedings is advisory and
non-binding unless both sides agree otherwise. The verdict is
supposed to be a reliable indicator of a full trial's outcome _
sparking attempts to settle so a full trial will not be necessary.
   Since first introduced in 1980, summary jury trials have been
used in at least 65 federal courts in about half the states.
   In the GE case, the judge ruled that the summary trial would be
closed to the public and ordered the parties, lawyers and jurors
never to reveal anything that occurred during the proceeding. He
also permanently sealed the trial transcript.
   The Cincinnati Post, The Dayton Daily News and The Columbus
Dispatch challenged the closure, but the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruled against them last Aug. 18.
   The appeals court said summary jury trials are more akin to
settlement conferences than real trials, and that the public
therefore has no right to attend or see the transcript.
   ``There is no historically recognized of right to summary jury
trials in that this mechanism has been in existence for less than a
decade,'' the appeals court said, adding, ``There is general
agreement that historically settlement techniques are closed
procedures.''
   In seeking Supreme Court review, lawyers for the three newspapers
argued, ``Public confidence will be lost if judges may respond to
their expanding dockets by disposing of cases through secret
courtroom proceedings and permanent gag orders.''
   ``This court cannot expect that public confidence, so vital to an
effective judiciary, will thrive where judges conduct decisive
courtroom proceedings behind closed doors in permanent,
court-imposed secrecy,'' the appeal contended.
   But lawyers for GE discounted what they called the appeal's
``great flourishes of hyperbole,'' and urged the justices to reject
it.
   The case is Cincinnati Post vs. GE, 88-813.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0077 </DOCNO>
