<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-Attack     02-21 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Attack,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Army Brigade In Capital, Civilians Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas bombed the
headquarters of an army brigade in the capital today, killing two
civilians and wounding three others, authorities said.
   Rebels also used rocket-propelled grenades and rifle fire in a
pre-dawn attack on a military engineers' base in Zacatecoluca, 35
miles southeast of the capital. Radio reports said the assault
killed three soldiers.
   The rebel attack on the 1st army brigade base, which killed an
elderly couple who live nearby, was the fifth since November on a
major military installation in San Salvador.
   As in the earlier attacks, guerrillas used pickup trucks fitted
with a catapult-like device to launch the bombs against the 1st
brigade. The detonation of one explosive charge launches the bombs
and simultaneously blows up the vehicle.
   Two vehicles exploded today, killing Pedro Martinez, about 70
years old, and his wife Maria Teresa, about 65.
   Martinez's body lay on the sidewalk in front of his home an hour
after the vehicle parked in front of it exploded.
   Mrs. Martinez, whose legs were blown off by the blast, died on
the way to the hospital, said Col. Orlando Zepeda, who commands the
4,000-troop brigade. Three civilians were wounded by the explosions,
Zepeda said.
   The bombs launched by the vehicles did not fall inside the
grounds of the 1st brigade, he said. Journalists were denied entry
to the installation to verify the report.
   The explosions damaged about 10 homes, breaking windows, gouging
walls and blowing doors off hinges.
   In Zacatecoluca, Marxist-led guerrillas and soldiers battled for
three hours near the headquarters of the Detachment of Military
Engineers, radio reports said.
   Radio YSU reported from the scene that rebels hit an army truck
with a rocket-propelled grenade, killing two soldiers inside. The
radio said another soldier was killed in the fighting.
   There was no immediate word on army wounded or civilian or
guerrilla casualties.
   The attacks came as two guerrilla commanders and representatives
of El Salvador's political parties began a second day of meetings in
Mexico to discuss a rebel proposal to postpone the March 19
presidential election.
   The rebels say they are willing to end a decade-long election
boycott if the vote is postponed and security conditions guaranteed.
   The 9-year-old civil war has killed an estimated 70,000 people,
most of them civilians.
</TEXT>
