<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Copyright     02-21 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Copyright,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Turns Away Virginia Case On Federal Copyright Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to let states
and state agencies be sued for alleged violations of federal
copyright law.
   The court, without comment, turned away a Radford, Va., case that
highlighted a conflict between the Constitution's 11th Amendment
shielding states from federal lawsuits and copyright law requiring
all suits be filed in federal court.
   Photographer Richard Anderson sued Radford University, a
state-run school, and some school officials over the unauthorized
use in 1982 of copyright photographs.
   A federal trial judge dismissed the school and its officials as
defendants, ruling that the 11th Amendment protects them against
such suits.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the dismissal by a
2-1 vote last July 20.
   The appeals court noted a 1985 Supreme Court decision that
``Congress may abrogate the states' constitutionally secured
immunity from suit in federal court only making its intention
unmistakably clear in the language of the statute.''
   Congress did not do so in passing the Copyright Act of 1976, the
appeals court said.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for Anderson argued that
the 4th Circuit court misinterpreted the 1976 copyright law. They
said the law was intended to make states generally accountable for
copyright violations.
   ``Because the jurisdiction of the federal courts is exclusive (in
copyright cases) the effect of the 11th Amendment defense is not
simply to relegate the injured party to a suit in state court but to
deny any damage recovery at all against state infringers,'' the
appeal said.
   The Association of American Publishers, the Association of
American University Presses and the American Intellectual Property
Law Association sided with Anderson in ``friend of the court''
briefs.
   ``Whenever the 11th Amendment has previously been found to
preclude federal court jurisdiction some other forum has been
available,'' one of those briefs told the justices. ``For (Anderson)
and all others holding copyrights, however, no relief can be sought
in state courts.''
   The case is Anderson Photography vs. Radford University, 88-651.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
