<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-CannibalTrial     02-21 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Cannibal Trial,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dubuque Captain Says He's Accused Unfairly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUBIC BAY NAVAL BASE, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Navy captain said
today he would have rescued Vietnamese boat people his ship found in
the South China Sea if he had been correctly informed of their
desperate plight.
   Capt. Alexander Balian, 48, of Los Angeles, accused critics of
unfairly judging him in hindsight.
   He has been before a Navy court-martial since Feb. 10 on charges
of failing to adequately assist the more than 80 Vietnamese refugees
his ship, the USS Dubuque, encountered June 9 as it sailed for the
Persian Gulf.
   Thirty-one of the refugees died and survivors resorted to
cannibalism before they were rescued by Filipino fishermen June 27
after 37 days at sea, United Nations officials said.
   Balian, his voice choking with emotion, said if he had known the
desperate conditions aboard the Vietnamese craft, ``there is no
doubt in my mind I would tow them to my side and embark them. That's
what I did on two previous occasions.''
   He said he ordered his executive officer, Lt. Cmdr. Stanley
Halter, to determine if the refugee boat was seaworthy.
   ``Finally, the report came back `no engine,' and I surmised they
had a good sail,'' Balian said.
   He also said he was told ``they could make it on their own if we
gave them food and water,'' which were provided.
   Under cross-examination, Balian insisted he was not responsible
for the refugees resorting to cannibalism.
   ``I am being charged with giving insufficient assistance,'' he
said. ``What is sufficient assistance? You're saying I should have
embarked them. I should have embarked them _ on hindsight.''
   During the afternoon session, trial judge Capt. James Freyer
rejected a prosecution attempt to offer as evidence a fitness report
on Balian.
   Freyer said out of the jury's presence that the report was
``highly prejudicial'' and implied Balian was guilty.
   Balian was relieved of command of the Dubuque in August after the
Vietnamese reported the incident to U.N. officials in the
Philippines.
   He was acquitted Thursday of a charge of failing to assist a
Vietnamese who drowned.
   Balian today denied allegations that he ordered crew members not
to throw life rings to some of the Vietnamese who swam toward the
ship. He said he did order an interpreter to tell swimmers to move
away for fear they would be injured by the ship's propellers.
   He also denied previous testimony by a crew member, Chief Petty
Officer Luis Ilano, that he had advised the Vietnamese simply to
follow the sun to reach land.
   Balian said he ordered the interpreter to give the refugees a
navigational chart and mark their position.
</TEXT>
