<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-AnimalDrugs     02-21 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Animal Drugs,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court, in Illinois Case, Backs FDA Rules on Animal Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today allowed the Food and
Drug Administration to impose strict controls on the use of drugs by
veterinarians for ``experimental'' treatment of some animal diseases.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments by an Illinois
drug distributing company that the government wrongly is interfering
with the treatment of serious animal illnesses.
   The FDA seized a large quantity of drugs July 9, 1986, from
Schuyler Laboratories Inc. in Rushville, Ill.
   The drugs are in bulk form. Veterinarians mix them with other
drugs to create new medications to treat certain diseases for which
the FDA has not approved finished drugs.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which upheld the FDA
seizure last July, said the federal agency had ``looked the other
way for decades'' in declining to enforce rules against the
veterinarians.
   But the appeals court said the FDA reacted to the growing
practice of mixing experimental drugs by deciding to cut off
supplies.
   Schuyler Laboratories acts as a middleman, purchasing the
unblended drugs from the manufacturer and selling them to
veterinarians.
   Schuyler was accused of violating FDA regulations that require
drug labels to carry directions for their use. The bulk drugs do not
carry directions.
   The company said preventing veterinarians from mixing their own
drugs could have ``devastating consequences for the animals that
provide the basics of the American food supply.''
   Schuyler said there are no FDA-approved drugs to treat acute
inflammations, respiratory infections and other diseases that can
wipe out dairy herds and other cattle.
   But the federal agency defended its cautious approach to
licensing new drugs for treating animals. It can take years of
testing to determine, for example, whether new animal drugs can
cause cancer in humans who consume the animal products, federal
officials said.
   The 7th Circuit court, while noting that ``many veterinarians
find this state of affairs deplorable,'' said the FDA is acting
within its powers.
   ``No individual veterinarian will possess complete knowledge of
the efficacy of a novel drug compound _ let alone of its persistence
in the food chain,'' the appeals court said.
   Schuyler Laboratories failed to show that the FDA policy is
arbitrary or capricious, the appeals court said.
   The case is 9@1 KG Containers vs. U.S., 88-614.
</TEXT>
