<HEAD>Swaggert Fails to Block Evangelist's Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television evangelist Jimmy Swaggart failed
today in his Supreme Court bid to kill a $90 million lawsuit by a
defrocked evangelist who Swaggart accused of adultery in 1986.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that Marvin
Gorman's suit against Swaggart and others unconstitutionally
entangles Louisiana state courts in matters of church doctrine and
discipline.
   Gorman was a pastor of the First Assembly of God Church in New
Orleans when Swaggart accused him of ``immoral dalliances'' with
several women.
   Gorman resigned from his ministry a day after a July 1986 meeting
of church leaders in which Swaggart aired his allegations and Gorman
admitted to one instance of immoral conduct.
   Swaggart and other Assembly of God officials did not consider
Gorman's resignation valid, however, and he was formally dismissed
only after the accusations were read to his congregation.
   In February 1988, Swaggart himself tearfully confessed to an
undisclosed sin. A New Orleans prostitute later said Swaggart paid
her to perform sex acts while he watched.
   Swaggart was defrocked by the Assemblies of God last April 8
after refusing to step down from the pulpit for at least a year.
   He returned to his ministry's Family Worship Center in Baton
Rouge, La., and resumed his television programs. But the fortunes of
Jimmy Swaggart World Ministries have not recovered fully from the
1987 scandal.
   Last month, Penthouse magazine published an article in which a
New Orleans stripper told about performing sexual acts for Swaggart.
   Calling her story ``diabolical and slanderous fiction,'' Swaggart
has threatened to sue the magazine. He also said his television
ministry would end this month unless he received enough donations to
overcome ``pornographers'' who are trying to sabbotage his
broadcasts.
   Penthouse said the stripper, Catherine Mary Kampen, detailed the
alleged relationship with Swaggart in a deposition for lawyers
representing Gorman in his lawsuit against Swaggart and others.
   Gorman contends, among other things, that he was defamed and
libeled by Swaggart.
   Swaggart and the 13 other defendants sought to have Gorman's suit
dismissed, arguing that it violates religious freedoms for courts to
preside over disputes stemming from church discipline.
   ``The secular courts are without jurisdiction to hear his
claim,'' lawyers for Swaggart contended.
   The cases are Swaggart vs. Adler, 88-1080, and Treeby vs. Gorman,
88-1058.
