<HEAD>Court Rejects Challenge of Texas Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected a
constitutional attack against a Texas seat belt law, letting stand
the $35 fine a Houston lawyer was assessed in 1986 for not buckling
up.
   The court, citing the lack of a ``substantial federal question,''
refused to hear Raymond D. Richards Jr.'s arguments that requiring
him to wear a seat belt while driving a motor vehicle violates his
fundamental right to be free from bodily restraints.
   Texas courts also rejected Richards' arguments, although along
the way one judge, Ben G. Levy, voted for him.
   Dissenting from an opinion of the Court of Appeals for the First
Supreme Judicial District of Texas, Levy wrote that allowing the
state to punish someone for not wearing a seat belt might lead to
punishment ``for smoking cigarettes, for not brushing one's teeth or
for being foolish.''
   In a recent interview, Richards said he had spent ``a lot of
time'' but not a significant amount of money in contesting his $35
fine.
   The case is Richards vs. Texas, 88-1097.
