<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Pandering     02-21 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Pandering,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Pandering Case Against Hollywood Film Producer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reinstate
the pandering conviction of a Hollywood movie producer who hired
actors to peform sex acts in a pornographic film.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a California Supreme
Court ruling that Harold Freeman's conviction on charges of
procuring people for purposes of prostitution violated his freedom
of expression.
   Freeman, president of the Hollywood Video Production Co., is in
the business of producing and marketing ``adult'' films. He produced
and directed a 1983 film called ``Caught From Behind, Part II.
   For the movie, Freeman hired actors and actresses who, as part of
their roles, engaged in various sex acts.
   Los Angeles County prosecutors charged Freeman with five counts
of pandering, based on his hiring five actresses who performed in
the movie. Freeman was not charged with any violation of the state's
obscenity laws, and the movie was not formally judged to be obscene.
   Freeman was convicted and sentenced to 90 days in jail amd five
years probation. He also was ordered to pay $10,000 in restitution
and a $100 fine.
   The state Supreme Court threw out Freeman's conviction last Aug.
25, ruling that California's pandering law should not have been
applied to him.
   Freeman was not procuring people for the purpose of prostitution,
the state court said, because ``there is no evidence (he) paid the
acting fees for the purpose of sexual arousal or gratification, his
own or the actors.''
   The state court added that even if what the film's participants
engaged in could be classified as prostitution, ``the application of
the pandering statute to the hiring of actors to perform in the
production of a non-obscene motion picture would impinge
unconstitutionally upon First Amendment values.''
   The Constitution's First Amendment guarantees freedom of speech
and expression.
   On Feb. 1, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor turned down an emergency
request by county prosecutors seeking to postpone the effect of the
state Supreme Court's ruling until their formal appeal was
considered.
   O'Connor predicted that the prosecutors' formal appeal would be
rejected because the state court ruling was based on an
interpretation of state law, and was thus ``binding upon this
court.''
   The cases are California vs. Freeman, 88-1054, and Applegate vs.
Freeman, 88-1050.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
