<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Mining     02-21 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Mining,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal By Mining Companies On Hazardous Wastes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by
mining companies seeking an exemption from federal environmental
rules for certain hazardous wastes.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the
Environmental Protection Agency must regulate the wastes.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last July that a 1980
federal law exempting some ``high volume, low hazard'' mining wastes
from environmental rules does not apply to six types of waste
produced from smelting.
   The appeals court said the exemption does not apply to six types
of dust, sludge and other waste from the smelting of copper, lead,
zinc, aluminum, ferrochromium and ferrochromium-silicon.
   In a victory for environmental groups, the appeals court
overturned an EPA decision and ordered the agency to apply
hazardous-waste rules to the six types of smelter waste.
   The American Mining Congress, the Aluminum Association and
Kennecott said the 1980 law was intended to apply to ``all mining
industry processing wastes.''
   The case is American Mining Congress vs. Environmental Defense
Fund, 88-848.
</TEXT>
