<FIRST>u a PM-AirForceCrash 3rdLd-Writethru a0498 02-21 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Force Crash, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0498,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fate of Eight Aboard Air Force Plane Unknown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with no sign of crew found by mid-morning,
new quote; Picks up 4th graf, ``It's just ...'; SUBS 17th graf, `The C-141B
...' with plane dimensions. Thom is cq in 5th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HURLBURT FIELD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers battling treacherous swamps
today could not find survivors or bodies near the wreckage of an Air
Force cargo plane that crashed with eight people on board, officials
said.
   The C-141B Starlifter crashed three miles north of this base
Monday night while coming in for a landing, Air Force officials
said. The plane was from Norton Air Force Base in Southern
California.
   The fate of the eight people on the aircraft _ seven crew members
and a retired military passenger who boarded the plane during a
refueling stop in Colorado Springs, Colo. _ remained unknown,
officials said.
   ``I understand it's about five feet of water, underbrush and a
swamp area, just difficult getting through on land,'' said Technical
Sgt. David Torrence, adding search crews still had found no sign of
the fliers by mid-morning.
   ``It's just too early to make any kind of a guess'' on the
chances of finding anyone alive, said Capt. Thom Connell, a base
spokesman.
   The wreckage did not appear to be spread out and the C-141B's
large, distinctive T-shaped tail was intact, said Capt. Dale Stovall
of the 1st Special Operations Wing at Hurlburt, who was in charge of
the search.
   Small fires still burned hours after the crash.
   Controllers at adjacent Eglin Air Force Base lost radio and radar
contact with the plane around 8 p.m. CST Monday as it was on final
approach to this base 40 miles east of Pensacola, officials said.
   The first rescuers did not reach the area of the crash until
12:30 a.m. The search was suspended about four hours later, and was
to resume at daylight.
   The searchers, who had to climb down ropes from hovering
helicopters, found ``just terrible terrain, terrible conditions,''
said Connell. ``It's stumps and rocks and fallen trees.''
   He said bulldozers would attempt to plow a path to the crash site
today.
   ``We are having difficulty reaching the site,'' said Stovall.
``The water in the area is five feet deep.''
   At the time of the crash, Army Rangers heard an explosion, but
Stovall said the sound may have been that of the plane hitting the
ground. The aircraft was not carrying munitions, he said.
   There were thunderstorms in the area, Stovall said, but he
declined to say if weather figured in the crash. An Air Force safety
team is investigating the accident.
   The first rescuers arrived in an Army UH-60 Blackhawk helicopter.
   ``They've found one of the engines in a creek,'' said Lynn
Jurkovic, a dispatcher at the nearby Fort Walton Beach Fire
Department, which sent three rescue units to the scene.
   The aircraft was on a regularly scheduled flight to pick up
personnel and cargo bound for Howard Air Force Base in Panama,
Stovall said.
   The C-141B, capable of carrying up to 200 people, belonged to the
63rd Military Airlift Wing at Norton, about 60 miles east of Los
Angeles, said base spokesman Capt. Gary A. Jacobs. The four-engine
plane is 168 feet long and has a wingspan of 160 feet.
   Hurlburt is headquarters for Air Force Special Operations, which
trains for small-unit actions behind enemy lines using specially
modified helicopters and cargo planes that fly low to avoid radar
detection.
   Eglin is home of the Air Force Armament Divsion, which is
responsbile for developing and testing non-nuclear weapons, and a
wing of F-15 Eagle fighters.
</TEXT>
