<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Klan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0563,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Glenn in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>Court Refuses To Hear Appeal Of Former Carolina Klan Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to hear the
appeal of a former Ku Klux Klan leader in North Carolina convicted
of criminal contempt for his role in a paramilitary organization.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that former Klan
leader Glenn F. Miller was denied a fair trial.
   Miller was sentenced to six months in prison and placed on
probation for three years for criminal contempt.
   He also was sentenced to five years in prison in a subsequent
case in which he pleaded guilty to illegally possessing hand
grenades and issuing a ``declaration of war'' againsts blacks, Jews
and homosexuals.
   Miller, who testified for the government in prosecutions against
other white supremacists, was placed in the federal witness
protection program and given a new identity.
   The case acted on today stems from a 1984 lawsuit filed by Bobby
L. Person accusing Miller and the Carolina Knights of the Ku Klux
Klan with violently intimidating blacks to prevent them from
exercising their rights.
   A court consent decree that settled the suit in 1985 barred
Miller and the Klan from operating a paramilitary organization or
engaging in military exercises or training ``in furtherance of a
civil disorder.''
   About a year later, Miller was accused of criminal contempt for
violating the consent decree. The Klan organization, meanwhile, had
changed its name to the White Patriot Party.
   Morris Dees of the Southern Poverty Law Center, which represented
Person, filed the criminal contempt complaint and, in an unusual
development, acted as prosecutor in the contempt proceeding for
about two months.
   In June 1986, the U.S. attorney's office in North Carolina was
placed in charge of the case. Dees was allowed to continue as an
assistant to the U.S. attorney's office in prosecuting the complaint.
   Miller was convicted of criminal contempt after a jury heard
testimony that his ultimate goal was the armed overthrow of the
government.
   Miller said his rights were violated for a number of reasons. He
argued that Dees continued to be in charge of the prosecution after
June 1986 and was biased against him.
   Miller also said all blacks should have been barred as
prospective jurors because they stood to benefit from the court
order Miller was charged with violating.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld his conviction last
August.
   The appeals court said there was adequate evidence that the U.S.
attorney's office, and not Dees, was in control of the case.
   The appeals court also said Miller failed to show that no black
could serve as an impartial juror in a case involving a white
supremacist.
   The case is Miller vs. Person, 88-792.
</TEXT>
