<HEAD>Man Arrested For Vandalism Near Ben Franklin's Tombstone</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to CORRECT that Franklin's tombstone was
not damaged. Picks up 3rd graf pvs., `The gates...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was arrested for vandalizing a
centuries-old cemetery containing the grave of Benjamin Franklin,
authorities said today.
   George Guido, 36, of Philadelphia, was accused of knocking over
six grave markers Monday night and smashing an ornament on a wall
next to Franklin's grave, which was undamaged in the attack.
   Officials initially had thought the man vandalized Franklin's
grave, but later learned that a crack and chips off the corners of
the tombstone were the products of age rather than vandalism, said
the Rev. David Laquintano of Christ Church.
   Franklin's tombstone was undamaged, Laquintano said, and concrete
chips found nearby were from a smashed ornament from the wall next
to the grave.
   Guido was charged with institutional vandalism, criminal
mischief, desecration of venerated objects and criminal trespass. He
was held pending arraignment.
   The colonial statesman, inventor, publisher and scientist was
buried at the cemetery of Christ Church April 21, 1790, four days
after his death at age 84. Franklin was the oldest delegate at the
Constitutional Convention, which drafted the U.S. Constitution in
1787 at Philadelphia's Independence Hall.
</TEXT>
