<FIRST>u w PM-Grant-Profile 1stLd-Writethru a0568 02-21 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grant-Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0568,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Newest GOP Congressman from Increasingly Republican District</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Inserts 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs, For his, with Wright comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Bill Grant, a two-term congressman who
switched to the Republican Party today, represents much of Florida's
Panhandle, where Republicans have been displaying increasing
strength in recent elections.
   Grant, 46, appeared at the White House with President Bush, who
announced Grant's defection from the Democratic Party.
   ``This is good news for our party not only in Florida, not only
in the South, but nationally,'' Bush said.
   For his part, Grant told reporters at the nationally televised
announcement, ``After a period of prolonged and careful
deliberation, I have determined that I can better represent the
values and the priorities of north Floridians in the State of
Florida as a Republican.''
   House Speaker Jim Wright, asked about Grant's defection from the
majority party, said:
   ``It took me by surprise, but that's everyone's choice. I hope
he's happy.''
   Grant was a banker from Madison, a rural town in northern
Florida, when he first won election to the House in 1986, after four
years in Florida's state Senate.
   His conversion tips the balance of Florida's delegation to
Congress, giving the state 10 Republicans and nine Democrats.
   Grant is the second Florida congressman to switch parties in five
years. Former Democratic Rep. Andy Ireland became a Republican in
1984.
   Grant's district is the largest, geographically, east of the
Mississippi River. The 2nd congressional district stretches along
the state's northern border from near Panama City to just west of
Jacksonville and includes Tallahasse, the state capital.
   Voters in the Florida Panhandle have long voted for Democratics
in state elections but recently have been showing more support for
Republican candidates, especially in the last two presidential
elections.
   Last fall, two Republican upsets in races for traditionally
Democratic congressional seats _ the 4th and 6th congressional
districts _ eroded the Democrats' majority in the delegation. In the
Senate, Republicans gained one of Florida's seats when Connie Mack
defeated Democratic Rep. Buddy MacKay to replace the retired
Democrat Lawton Chiles.
   Grant won his seat after 12-term Rep. Don Fuqua, a Democrat,
decided to retire. Grant won 51 percent of the vote in a
five-candidate primary. He had no Republican opponent in the general
election.
   Grant has been active in the Democratic Party and had figured in
speculation for a possible run for governor in 1990. He drew
publicity last summer for his unsuccessful campaign in support of
Sen. Bob Graham for the Democratic vice presidential nomination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
