<HEAD>Thunderstorms, Tornadoes Lash Gulf Coast, Bring Floods</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with wind damage in North Carolina,
new twister sightings, Georgia outages, other details. Pickup 8th graf,
`Several roads...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm centered over western Kentucky today lashed Gulf Coast
states with severe thunderstorms and tornadoes and caused renewed
flooding in parts of the Ohio and Tennessee valleys.
   Tornadoes hit several parts of northwest Alabama and central
Louisiana, downing power lines, throwing mobile homes and knocking
trees on cars. No serious injuries were reported. School was
canceled today in Alabama's Houston County due to the poor weather
and road conditions.
   In North Carolina, tornado-like winds flipped mobile homes in
Moore County, injuring four people, tore off a roof of a school and
overturned several small planes in Anson County, authorities said.
No children in the school were hurt.
   Twisters also were sighted in east-central Mississippi. Heavy
rain accompanied the thunderstorms and caused flash floods in
Alabama and Louisiana.
   Rainfall measured from 3 to 7 inches Monday in Rapides Parish in
central Louisiana, where twisters hit in seven locations, said Bill
Godron, the parish's civil defense director. Parts of the Florida
Panhandle had more than 3} inches of rain in the six hours ended at
1 a.m. EST. Tupelo, Miss., received just over 3 inches of rain in
the period.
   Golfball-size hail pelted Fort Walton Beach on the Florida
Panhandle.
   Wind gusting to 80 mph downed trees and power lines in Jackson,
Miss., Monday evening, knocking out power to several thousand homes.
Strong winds also led to power outages in Birmingham, Ala., and
southwest Georgia, early today.
   Several roads were flooded in central Tennessee, where more than
2{ inches of rain fell Monday. The Ohio River rose over its banks
from Louisville, Ky., to Cairo at the southern tip of Illinois.
   Flash flood watches were in effect in northern Mississippi,
northwest Alabama, Tennessee, parts of Kentucky and West Virginia,
southwest Virginia and southern Ohio.
   Rain was widespread early today along the East Coast from the
Carolinas to Connecticut.
   In the Midwest, a band of snow stretched from southern Michigan
to Iowa and northern Missouri. Quincy in western Illinois received 7
inches. Snow advisories were posted for northern and central
Illinois and southern Michigan, and a winter storm watch was in
effect for northern Maine.
   Light snow also fell on the central and northern Plains.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms in much of
the East, including the Atlantic states, the central and eastern
Gulf Coast, the Tennessee and Ohio valleys and the lower Mississippi
Valley; thunderstorms from Mississippi to the Atlantic Coast between
South Carolina and northern Florida; rain along the northern Pacific
Coast; snow in Illinois and the upper Great Lakes region, northern
Maine, Montana and Wyoming.
   Highs were forecast to be in the teens and 20s from western
Montana across the northern Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley
to western portions of the upper Great Lakes; the 30s and 40s in
much of Nevada and Idaho, the central Rockies, the central Plains,
the Ohio Valley, the remainder of the Great Lakes and northern New
England; the 50s and 60s along the Pacific Coast, southern Nevada,
the southern Rockies, Texas, the Gulf Coast, the Tennessee Valley,
the mid-Atlantic coast and southern New England; the 70s in Southern
California and southern Arizona; and the 70s and 80s in Florida,
southern Georgia and the coast of the Carolinas.
   At 2 a.m. EST, temperatures ranged from 1 below zero at Grand
Forks, N.D., to 76 degrees at Key West Naval Air Station and Miami,
Fla.
   Other reports:
