<HEAD>Nine Children Die in Fires in Pennsylvania, New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to CORRECT that officials now saying fire was not
caused by explosion; SUBS grafs 7-9 with origin of fire under bed, matches
suspected, Picks up 10th graf, `Marlon was ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Five children died when a fire raged through an apartment complex
in Chester, Pa., and four children died in a New York City row house
blaze while playing with matches or a lighter, authorities said.
   In both fires Monday, hysterical mothers watched helplessly as
flames destroyed their homes and families.
   In New York, two mothers desperately threw buckets of water on
what authorities called a ``wall of fire,'' but to no avail.
   In the Pennsylvania fire, police Officer Michael Kruczaj said he
arrived at the scene to find 25-year-old Michelle Arnold outside her
burning apartment, holding one of her six children, a critically
injured 13-month-old boy.
   ``My babies! My babies! They're still inside!'' Ms. Arnold
shouted at Kruczaj, he recalled later.
   But the officer said the fire and smoke were too thick for him to
attempt rescuing Ms. Arnold's other five children, three boys and
two girls 2 to 6 years old. All died in the blaze.
   The fire started Monday afternoon under a bed and officials
suspect the children may have been playing with matches, fire Capt.
Joseph Cliffe said. The official cause remains undetermined.
Authorities said early reports of an explosion were erroneous.
   Thirty-nine of the 80 two-story units in the Crosby Square
apartment complex were damaged, authorities said. It was not known
how many people were in the building at the time of the fire or how
many were evacuated.
   Witnesses said Ms. Arnold was outside the apartment building
talking to friends when the fire broke out. She ran inside and was
able to rescue her 13-month old son, Marlon, just before Kruczaj
arrived, authorities said.
   Marlon was in critical condition today with burns over 70 percent
of his body and suffering from smoke inhalation, officials said.
   The New York fire broke out Monday afternoon in a Brooklyn
apartment.
   According to Fire Department spokesman Efrain Parrilla, four
children were playing in a bedroom and their mothers, sisters Gail
and Devoria Murray, were in a kitchen at the rear of the home when
they smelled smoke.
   When they went to investigate, they found one door blocked by a
mattress and another door blocked by a bunk bed, Parrilla said.
   ``Devoria and Gail tried to put out the fire with pots and pans
of water but it was to no avail. That mattress was like a wall of
fire,'' Parrilla said.
   Harry Isaacs, a neighbor, said the sight of the two hysterical
mothers trying to douse the flames was enough to ``give you
nightmares.''
   ``By the time we got there, they were gone _ they had no
chance,'' said fire Lt. Philip McDonnell.
   He said firefighters found the children, ages 4 to 8, atop one
another on the lower portion of a bunk bed on the top floor of the
three-story brick building.
   Fire Marshal John Regan said it appeared the children had been
playing with matches or a lighter.
   An unused smoke detector was found in a closet, Regan said.
</TEXT>
