<HEAD>Soccer Players, Fans Rescue Passengers of Sinking Ferry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Players and spectators of a soccer match
saved about 100 passengers from a sinking ferry in northeastern
Bangladesh, witnesses and police said Tuesday.
   There were no injuries.
   The ferry was carrying more than double its sanctioned capacity,
and sank near the banks of River Karala at Mahasingh, 110 miles
northeast of Dhaka on Monday, they said.
   Most of the 22 players of a soccer match and hundreds of
spectators who heard the screams of the passengers jumped into the
river, witnesses said. They rescued women and children from the hull
of the sinking ferry.
   Almost all male passengers already had reached safety.
   ``The passengers could survive as the ferry sank near the bank
and it took 30 minutes to sink,'' a police officer said.
   Ferry accidents are common in Bangladesh. Officials estimate 900
people have died in about 60 such accidents in the past seven years.
</TEXT>
