<HEAD>Seventh Person Dies of Injuries From U.S. Jet Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REMSCHEID, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has died of injuries
suffered in December's crash of a U.S. Air Force jet in Remscheid,
bringing the death toll to seven, officials said Tuesday.
   Truck driver Paul Gerd Kuepper, 47, died in a hospital Feb. 11,
according to authorities in Remscheid, 24 miles northeast of Cologne.
   Kuepper suffered severe burns when an A-10 Thunderbolt II
warplane crashed into a residential area Dec. 8. Fifty people were
injured.
   A series of military air crashes killed more than 100 people in
West Germany last year, causing a public outcry against low-level
training flights.
   The most serious disaster occurred on Aug. 28, when three Italian
stunt-flying jets collided at U.S. Ramstein Air Base and one of them
plunged into a crowd of spectators, killing 70 people and injuring
hundreds of others.
   The U.S. Air Force announced last week it was canceling all
public air shows in West Germany this year because of that crash.
