<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Postal     02-21 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Postal,630</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postal workers accused of traffic violations
must stand trial in state courts, a unanimous Supreme Court ruled
today.
   The decision limits the federal government's power to block some
state prosecutions of federal workers.
   The justices ordered two U.S. Postal Service mail carriers to
stand trial in California state courts.
   Both cases stem from traffic accidents in Santa Clara County.
   In one, Kathryn Isabella Mesa was accused of
misdemeanor-manslaughter after her mail truck collided with and
killed a bicyclist. In the other, Shabbir A. Ebrahim was charged
with speeding and failing to yield after his mail truck collided
with a police car.
   Both defendants succeeded in tranferring their cases to a federal
court. But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in 1987 sent the
cases back to the state courts.
   The Supreme Court today upheld the appeals court ruling.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing for the court, rejected
Justice Department arguments that permitting state prosecutions in
such cases could interfere with federal officials in performance of
their duties.
   Only if a federal issue is directly at stake may a prosecution be
shifted to federal court, O'Connor said. She also noted that
transferring cases like traffic violations to federal court would
impose heavy burdens on local state prosecutors.
   ``We can discern no federal interest in potentially forcing local
district attorneys to choose between prosecuting traffic violations
hundreds of miles from the municipality in which the violations
occurred or abandoning those prosecutions,'' O'Connor said.
   A federal law providing for removal of states cases to federal
court was enacted in response to New England's opposition to a trade
embargo declared during the War of 1812 between the United States
and Great Britain.
   Federal customs officials were given authority then to board
vessels in order to collect duties, assuring they would avoid
prosecution in state courts for any alleged misconduct in the
performance of their duties.
   The 9th Circuit court had noted that in the California case there
was no claim by the mail carriers that their allegedly illegal
conduct was justified by the duties they were performing.
   The case is Mesa vs. California, 87-1206.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
