<FIRST>u w BC-Bush-Glance     02-21 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush-Glance,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>President's Comments in Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the main topics
President Bush covered in his news conference Tuesday:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>IRAN-RUSDIE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush sharply criticized the Ayatollah Khomeini for ``exhorting
people to go out and commit murder'' against Salman Rushdie, author
of ``Satanic Verses.'' Bush said that ``however offensive that book
may be, inciting murder and offering rewards for its perpetraton are
deeply offensive to the norms of civilized behavior.'' He warned
that, ``In the light of Iran's incitement, should any action be
taken against American interests, the government of Iran can expect
to be held accountable.'' He supported the European Community's
unified stance against Iran's threats, and said he would discuss the
possibility of sanctions with the president of France and other
leaders in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>MIDDLE EAST</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president said the Soviets' role in the Middle East ``should
be a limited role, and I think that's what it's going to be.'' He
said he was not going to be ``stampeded'' into pressing ahead on
Middle East policy simply because Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze is visiting the region. The U.S. policy is ``to
encourage discussions between King Hussein (of Jordan) and the
Israelis and to build on the progress that has been made already.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TOWER</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush reaffirmed his support for John Tower, saying an FBI report
had ``gunned down'' allegations of misconduct against the nominee
for secretary of defense. He said, ``Anybody that's been through
this ordeal will be stronger, not weaker'' in running the Pentagon.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DAVID DUKE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president said it may have been ``improper or overkill'' for
him to urge Metairie, La., voters to reject former Ku Klux Klan
leader David Duke's bid for a seat in the state house as a
Republican. The voters who elected Duke may have resented the
intervention, Bush said, but Duke's record ``is one of racism and
bigotry and, I'm sorry, I just felt I had to speak out.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>STAR WARS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush said he was ``not ruling anything in or out'' on the
Strategic Defense Initiative, popularly known as Star Wars, but the
administration has ``some tough choices'' ahead on defense. He
reiterated his support for the principle of SDI, but said he was not
in favor of ``premature deployment'' and would not close or open any
doors until a review of overall defense policy is completed.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>URBAN VIOLENCE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The president said the federal government has a responsibility to
help curb violence in Washington, D.C., and across the nation, but
he rejected stiffer gun controls. He said his forthcoming anti-drug
program will address his campaign promises to get tough on criminals
and build more prisons. He said he wants to enforce ``the laws that
are already on the books about automated AK-47s coming into this
country.'' He said he wants to help the police ``who are out there
on the line all the time,'' but he also wants ``to be the president
that protects the rights of people to have arms.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>JAPAN</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush defended Japanese investment in the United States, saying it
is only the third-largest foreign investor behind Britain and the
Netherlands. He said the Japanese and other foreign investors are
helping the United States finance its ``horrendous deficits,'' and
it is important to keep U.S. markets open even as it presses for
``more openness for American investors in other countries.'' He
promised to exercise his responsibility to protect U.S. technology
and national security.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>PARTY SWITCH</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush welcomed the defection of Rep. William Grant from the
Democratic to the Republican Party, saying the switch ``is good news
for our party not only in Florida, not only in the South, but
nationally.''

</TEXT>
