<DOCNO> AP890221-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-HirohitoFuneral     02-21 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hirohito Funeral,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Begin Arriving For Funeral, Projectiles Found Near Airport</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos TOK1,2,5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of 16 countries arrived Tuesday for
Emperor Hirohito's funeral, and concern for the safety of visiting
world leaders grew with the discovery of two homemade projectiles
near Tokyo's airport.
   The projectiles were in launchers aimed at the heavily guarded
airport, about 40 miles east of the city, and apparently were
planted by radicals opposed to Friday's state funeral, a police
official said.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a timer
also was found. He declined to say at what time it was set.
   Cargo traffic and flights through Narita International Airport
and Tokyo's domestic airport will be restricted this week, and
32,000 police have been mobilized in Tokyo.
   Officers were stationed at checkpoints throughout the city and
patrolled downtown neighborhoods. They also have searched homes
along the funeral route.
   Authorities say the massive police presence is justified by
Japan's small but active radical groups and by fears that
international terrorists could attack as visiting leader.
   Officials say representatives of 163 countries will attend the
funeral.
   Workers on Tuesday made final preparations at the funeral site in
a Tokyo park.
   Hirohito's son, Emperor Akihito, and Empress Michiko met briefly
with Finnish President Mauno Koivisto and his wife, Tellervo, at the
Akasaka Palace. It was the royal couple's first meeting with foreign
dignitaries since Hirohito died Jan. 7.
   They are expected to meet other heads of state and visiting
royalty during the week.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita is to meet with about 40 of the
55 heads of state who plan to attend the funeral, and Foreign
Minister Sousuke Uno will meet about 90 foreign officials, the
Foreign Ministry says.
   Many of those talks will last less than half an hour, but
Takeshita plans longer meetings with President Bush and President
Francois Mitterrand of France.
   The diplomatic contacts began Tuesday with a meeting between
Deputy Foreign Minister Takakazu Kuriyama and his Soviet
counterpart, Igor A. Rogachev.
   They discussed plans for talks in March on a peace treaty to
formally end World War II hostilities and settle a long-standing
territorial dispute involving Soviet-held islands, the Foreign
Ministry said.
   Foreign officials also will meet among themselves. British
Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe has scheduled talks with Chinese
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen to discuss Hong Kong's return to
Chinese control.
   Many Japanese proudly see the large number of countries attending
as a sign that Japan finally has been accepted internationally after
its disastrous role in World War II.
   But there were reminders of lingering ill feelings. In several
nations, including South Korea, China, Australia, New Zealand and
Britain, there were disputes over who to send to the funeral because
of memories of the war, fought in Hirohito's name.
   Japanese who oppose the state funeral, including radicals, say
Hirohito led Japan into World War II and failed to stop the
oppressive actions of the militarist government of the time.
   Japan's Parliament adjourned Monday until after the funeral,
giving Takeshita a respite from criticism at home over an
embarrassing stock-profiteering scandal that has shaken his
governing Liberal Democratic Party. Three Cabinet members have
resigned in connection with the scandal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
