<FIRST>r p PM-Duke     02-21 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duke,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Confirm That Former Klansman Won Legislative Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>METAIRIE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elections officials cracked seals on voting
machines today and confirmed that former Ku Klux Klan grand wizard
David Duke won a seat in the Lousiana Legislature by a 227-vote
margin.
   ``We were very careful,'' said Sam Altobello, registrar of voters
for Jefferson Parish in the New Orleans suburb.
   The official count from Saturday's special election was taken to
the courthouse, where the numbers will be shipped by special courier
to Baton Rouge in time for the opening of a special legislative
session Wednesday.
   However, Duke's opponents were checking possible ways to block
his taking office at the outset of the session.
   State Rep. Odon Bacque, a freshman legislator, said he plans to
challenge the seating of Duke when he is to be sworn in.
   Bacque, the only registered independent member in the House, said
he will challenge Duke's seating on grounds that Duke did not live
in the district for a year as required by law.
   Duke has maintained that he did live in the district and on
Sunday dismissed further questions about it as frivolous.
   Duke, 38, defeated homebuilder John Treen, 63, in Saturday's
election for a seat in the Louisiana House of Representatives
despite endorsements for Treen by President Bush, former President
Reagan and the most powerful political figures in the suburban New
Orleans area. Both candidates were registered as Republicans.
</TEXT>
