<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1306EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-JapanMemories Bjt   02-21 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Japan Memories, Bjt,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Puts War Behind Him As He Heads To Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's journey to Japan will take him
inexorably down a path of war memories punctuated by visions of
being shot down at sea and losing two Navy buddies in combat.
   But if attending Emperor Hirohito's funeral on Friday presents a
painful reminder of the war with Japan, Bush isn't saying so.
   ``I'm doing what's right,'' he said recently.
   Bush, a former Navy aviator whose plane was shot down over the
Pacific by the Japanese in 1944, said, ``We have a good relationship
with Japan. I want to see it even better. And this doesn't concern
me a bit. And you're talking to a person who was in combat in World
War II. I feel you look ahead, not always look back. You do what's
right.
   ``It's the right thing to do.''
   Bush visited Japan twice as vice president, in 1982 and 1984.
   In his 1987 autobiography, ``Looking Forward,'' Bush shows little
reluctance to talk about what happened Sept. 2, 1944.
   The young Navy officer and two other crew members _ gunnery
officer William G. ``Ted'' White and radioman-tailgunner Jack
Delaney _ had taken off in a TBM Avenger on a mission to knock out a
Japanese radio facility on Chichi Jima, one of three islands in the
Bonin chain about 600 miles from Tokyo.
   Bush described in graphic detail how his plane was blown from the
sky and how he managed to ride a torn parachute to the water,
ultimately to be picked up by a Navy rescue ship, the USS Finback.
   As he neared the water, Bush wrote, ``I looked around for Delaney
and White, but the only thing in sight was my parachute drfiting
away.''
   Bush wrote about the letter he sent his parents six days after
his rescue, in which he ``described my feelings at the time.''
   ``I try to think about it as little as possible,'' he wrote in
the book. ``Yet, I cannot get those two out of my mind. ... I know I
won't be able to shake the memory of this incident and I don't
believe I want to completely.''
   Two days before his inauguration Jan. 20, Bush was reunited with
about three dozen of his war buddies, hosting a nostaligic party for
surviving fellow pilots, radiomen and gunners and sharing
remembrances with them.
   In a recent telephone interview from his home in Rogers, Ark.,
Don Kohler, the submarine torpedoman who helped pull Bush from his
bobbing life raft, said, ``I think he feels the need to go there for
the total relationship between their country and our country.
They're a major entity in the world economy.''
   Kohler, who is 64, like Bush, said he shares the president's view
that ``you should forgive and forget. ... I don't know what part
Hirohito had in running the country into war, but, believe me, I
think most people in Japan today want to forget about the war.''
   Kohler added, ``I know there are other people'' in the United
States ``who have strong feelings the other way.''
   Former Sen. Jeremiah Denton, R-Ala., who was a North Vietnamese
prisoner of war for eight years, described Bush as ``a giant of a
man'' who wants to avoid showing any feeling of vindictiveness
toward the Japanese.
   Bush is traveling to Japan with an interest in ``the commonality
of humankind'' and ``with altruism toward his fellow man,'' Denton
said in a telephone interview.
   ``He seems to understand the Japanese people and the Japanese
people understand him,'' said Denton.
   Denton said that while he has not returned to Vietnam, he
believes that Americans caught in wars seldom hold lingering
bitterness toward the people of a nation that has warred against the
United States.
   ``I feel very lovingly frustrated toward the people of Vietnam,''
he said.
   A presidential scholar at the University of Virginia, Larry
Sabato, said that Bush ``is in the noblesse oblige tradition and
part of noblesse oblige is sublimating oneself to the common good.''
   ``My personal feeling is that if he does have lingering
bitterness; he's suppressed it,'' Sabato said. ``He's going to be
busy having meetings with world leaders. He really won't have that
much time to concentrate on the personal aspect of it. He'll be so
busy that I don't think he'll have much time for personal
reflection.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
