<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Merger     02-21 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Merger,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Limits Damages in Georgia Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a case involving alleged
fraud in a 20-year-old business merger, today limited the ability of
people to seek additional damages after winning a lawsuit.
   The 9-0 ruling in a case from Georgia restricts the ability of
purported fraud victims to sue a leading accounting firm.
   The case arose out of the 1969 merger of Cavalier Bag Co. and
E.T. Barwick Industries Inc.
   The owners of Cavalier Bag _ Myles, Guy-Kenneth and Robert
Osterneck _ charged in a 1975 lawsuit that the financial health of
Barwick Industries was overstated.
   The Osternecks sued Barwick officials and Ernst &amp; Whinney, an
accounting firm that had prepared the allegedly inflated financial
statements.
   After nearly 10 years of pre-trial maneuvering, the case went to
trial in 1984 and the Barwick company and its offficials were
ordered to pay the Osternecks more than $2.6 million in damages plus
$946,000 in interest.
   But the Osternecks lost their case against Ernst &amp; Whinney.
   They then appealed, seeking to revive the case against the
accounting firm. That appeal was filed at the same time that the
Osternecks' request for interest payments against the Barwick
officials was pending in court.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the Osternecks'
bid for damages against the accounting firm must be treated as a
motion to amend the original judgment that the Osternecks had won.
   Therefore, the appeals court barred the Osternecks from pursuing
a separate appeal against Ernst &amp; Whinney while at the same time
they were seeking additional interest payments against the Barwick
officials.
   The Supreme Court today upheld the appeals court ruling.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, writing for the court, said handling
appeals in this manner helps avoid piecemeal appellate court review
of lower court judgments.
   The case is Osterneck vs. Ernst &amp; Whinney. 87-1201.
</TEXT>
