<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-LawyerFees     02-21 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lawyer Fees,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Gives Lawyers Extra Fee in Louisiana Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A unanimous Supreme Court today gave lawyers
added incentive _ the possibility of bigger-than-bargained-for legal
fees _ to represent those who claim their civil rights were violated.
   The court ruled in a Louisiana case that the losing side in some
civil rights lawsuits may be forced to pay the winning side's
lawyers more than the lawyers originally had sought.
   The normal rule in U.S. courts is that each side pays its own
lawyers. But Congress has altered that rule in about 200
fee-shifting laws, and allowed the winning side to collect its
lawyer fees from the losing side.
   Most notably, such fee awards are available to people who
successfully sue over civil rights violations.
   Arthur J. Blanchard, who said he was assaulted without
provocation by a St. Martin Parish sheriff's deputy, James Bergeron,
was awarded $10,000 in damages by a federal jury.
   The presiding judge also awarded Blanchard $7,500 in lawyer fees,
which Bergeron was ordered to pay.
   But the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reduced the lawyer-fee
award to $4,000 after noting that Blanchard and his lawyer had a
contingency-fee agreement in which the lawyer was to get 40 percent
of any damage award.
   The appeals court said the 40 percent contingency agreement
effectively placed a cap on any lawyer-fee award that could be made.
   Writing for the Supreme Court today, Justice Byron R. White said
no such cap exists.
   ``If a contingent fee agreement were to govern as a strict
limitation on the award of attorney's fees, an undesirable emphasis
might be placed on the importance of the recovery of damages in
civil rights litigation,'' White said.
   ``The intention of Congress,'' he said, ``was to encourage
successful civil rights litigation, not to create a special
incentive to prove damages and shortchange efforts to seek effective
injunctive or declaratory relief.''
   The justices told the 5th Circuit court to reconsider its
lawyer-fee award ruling in Blanchard's case.
   The case is Blanchard vs. Bergeron, 87-1485.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
