<FIRST>u a PM-AmocoCadiz     02-21 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amoco Cadiz,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Increases Damages In 1978 French Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today recommended that Amoco Corp. be
ordered to pay about $115 million to France and nearly 90 French
citizens or businesses damaged by millions of gallons of oil spilled
in a 1978 supertanker accident.
   Retired U.S. District Judge Frank McGarr, sitting as a special
master, recommended an increase of about $30 million in his original
$85.2 million judgment against the oil company.
   U.S. District Judge Charles Norgle will enter a final judgment.
   Virtually all parties to the case had asked McGarr to reconsider
his January 1988 decision, issued before his retirement as a federal
judge.
   Amoco and the French plaintiffs immediately indicated they were
likely to appeal today's ruling.
   ``A lot of people won't be happy. The recommendation is a mixed
bag. But the oyster growers, for one, will be pleased. They're in
line for the biggest revision,'' said attorney Warren Marwedel, who
represented a number of oyster syndicates, two French regions and a
number of other plaintiffs affected by the spill from the Amoco
Cadiz supertanker.
   ``It's a very conservative, traditional opinion,'' Marwedel said.
``Things like the loss of enjoyment and environmental claims were
not given the consideration we had sought.''
   Amoco attorney Franck Cicero said the company was pleased with
McGarr's recommendation.
   `If you look at the total awarded so far, they've only got about
3 percent of what they originally claimed,'' Cicero said. ``The
judge indicated again he thought they were overreaching and there
were some duplicate claims.''
   Cicero said Amoco is proceeding with litigation against the
Spanish builder of the Amoco Cadiz, Astilleros Espanoles S.A.
   The Amoco Cadiz ran aground two miles off the Brittany coast
March 16, 1978. The huge tanker, which had lost the use of its
rudder, had been under tow through the English Channel by a
German-owned tug when the towlines snapped in hurricane-force winds
and heavy seas.
   The Liberian-registered supertanker carried 223,000 tons, or 68
million gallons, of mostly Iranian light crude oil valued at $24
million. The spill, the largest ever from a tanker, caused an oil
slick more than 10 miles across and 80 miles long.
   The plaintiffs include more than 90 villages from France's
Brittany coast, groups of oystermen and fishermen, property owners
and environmentalists. They had initially sought more than $1.1
billion in damages.
</TEXT>
