<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     02-21 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>50 Detainees Freed; Hunger Strike Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government freed 50
detainees Tuesday after a hunger strike in two prisons was halted,
but at least 226 detainees still are fasting elsewhere, police and
lawyers said.
   Police said they have hospitalized 20 of the hunger strikers, who
are demanding they be freed or put on trial. Many have been held
without charge for more than two years.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok told Parliament he signed
release warrants for 50 detainees.
   He said the hunger strikes were orchestrated outside prisons by
opposition groups seeking ``to discredit the South African
government.''
   ``Inside the prisons it is the work of a small group of
ringleaders _ hardened leftist activists _ who by means of cruel
intimidation control the group to such a degree that many detainees
are too afraid to break away,'' Vlok said.
   Veteran anti-apartheid legislator Helen Suzman said detainees
decided on their ``extremely dangerous course'' only after
exhausting all avenues for airing their grievances.
   ``By what criteria does the minister (Vlok) decide that people
must be kept away from the community?'' she asked. ``He should not
be worried about saving face, he should be worried about saving
lives.''
   Hunger strikes continued in the southern cities of Durban,
Pietermaritzburg and East London.
   Police said 20 hunger strikers in East London were hospitalized
Monday, four days after they began fasting with six fellow detainees.
   Civil rights lawyers said at least 200 detainees in Durban and
Pietermaritzburg have begun hunger strikes in the past two weeks.
Vlok has agreed to meet lawyers for these detainees, but no date has
been set.
   The first hunger strike started Jan. 23 and involved nearly 300
detainees held without charge in Port Elizabeth and at Diepkloof
Prison outside Johannesburg. That strike was suspended last week
when Vlok promised to review detainees' cases and release ``a
substantial number.''
   Eight detainees were freed Friday.
   Vlok has been commended, even by anti-government leaders, for
agreeing to meet lawyers, parents and clergymen representing the
hunger strikers.
   However, anti-apartheid leader Rev. Frank Chikane said Monday
some detainees who recently quit their hunger strike could resume if
they are dissatisfied by the number of releases in the next two
weeks.
   Under the 32-month state of emergency, police can arrest anyone
they believe might endanger public safety. Vlok decides
periodically, based on reports from police officers, whether the
detainee should remain incarcerated.
   Monitoring groups have said more than 30,000 people, mostly
blacks, have been detained for some period of time during the
emergency. Vlok has never given a total figure, but he said earlier
this month there were fewer than 1,000 people in detention.
   On Tuesday, he said no youths under 16 were in detention. He said
there were 22 detainees who were 16 years old and 30 who were 17.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
