<DOCNO> AP890221-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     02-21 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Quits Over War Stance; Soldier Replaces Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former general was named Tuesday to
replace the defense minister, who resigned and reportedly alleged
that government reluctance to end Sudan's southern civil war has
isolated the country.
   The independent newspaper Al-Ayam said Defense Minister
Abdel-Magid Khalil quit after returning from an unannounced visit to
Jordan and Iraq, where he apparently was refused new military and
financial aid.
   Information Minister Beshir Omar said Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi
named Salah Abdul-Salam defense minister. Abdul-Salam is a member of
the prime minister's Umma party. Khalil, who also was an army
general, is an independent.
   Omar said Mahdi canceled a trip to Japan to attend the funeral of
Emperor Hirohito because of the ``emergency circumstances.'' Vice
President Idris Banna and the five-member Supreme Council will
represent him at the funeral, the statement said.
   Another newspaper, Al-Adwa, said Khalil's letter of resignation
charged ``the foreign policy adopted by the government does not lead
to a unified internal front nor to stability, and has also led to
the isolation of the country both in the Arab and outside world.''
   It said government policies ``have weakened the country's ability
to acquire military and economic assistance.''
   The United States has urged an end to the nearly 6-year-old civil
war and said it would try to promote a peace settlement. Washington
has linked further U.S. aid to ending the war, and other friendly
Western and Arab donors say there is an urgent need to end the
fighting.
   John Garang, the U.S.-educated renegade colonel who leads the
Sudan People's Liberation Army, signed a peace plan Nov. 16 with
Mohammed Osman Mirghani, leader of Sudan's Democratic Unionist
Party. At the time, the Democratic Unionists belonged to the
governing coalition of Mahdi's Umma party and the National Islamic
Front of Moslem fundamentalist Hassan Turabi.
   Although his party endorsed the plan, Mahdi refused to let the
government act on it. In December, the Unionists left the coalition
because of the government's position on the peace plan and its
handling of the economy. Mahdi formed a new government in February
with the National Islamic Front as the junior partner.
   The front rejects a key rebel demand _ abolition of harsh Islamic
laws that are applied to all Sudanese regardless of religion.
   Sudan is divided into the minority Christians and animists of the
south, who are black, and the dominant Moslems of the north, who are
Arabic.
   The Sudanese economy is faltering under the $1 million a day
costs of the civil war, a $13 billion foreign debt and decreasing
foreign aid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
