<DOCNO> AP890221-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Mideast     02-21 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Mideast,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Won't Be Rushed into New Middle East Policy by Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Tuesday he would not be
rushed by high-profile Soviet diplomacy into framing a new U.S.
policy to deal with the Arab-Israeli confict.
   He said the Soviets should play only a secondary role in the
region ``and I think that's what it's going to be.''
   ``I don't worry about a trip by Mr. Shevardnadze to the Middle
East,'' Bush said at a White House news conference. ``I have no
worry about that.''
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze is in the area for
talks with Arab leaders and also Moshe Arens, the Israeli foreign
minister. The session with Arens in Cairo is widely interpreted as a
bid by Moscow for a larger role in trying to set up Mideast peace
talks.
   Bush and James A. Baker III, the U.S. secretary of state, are
pondering their moves after a month in office. During a tour of NATO
capitals last week British, Spanish and Dutch leaders, among others,
urged Baker to take advantage of what they perceived to be
moderation by the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Baker told them he would have U.S. diplomats explore the
situation in the area and that he would report back to the Western
Europeans at the opening of arms control negotiations between the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization and the Warsaw Pact in Vienna
early next month.
   At Bush's news conference, when the president was told by one
questioner there was a perception he did not have a foreign policy.
he said: ``I've never heard such an outrageous hypothesis.''
   In fact, Bush said, ``we have a foreign policy'' in which
East-West relations, South America and the Middle East are all under
review.
   He said Shevardnadze's trip, which involves the first visit by a
high-level Soviet official to Egypt in 17 years, ``doesn't trouble
me one bit.''
   Besides, Bush said he would ``have an opportunity to discuss a
lot of things'' with other nations' leaders on his own trip with
Baker to Tokyo for the funeral of Emperor Hirohito of Japan.
   Bush and Baker are expected to meet with King Hussein of Jordan,
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and President Chaim Herzog of
Israel while they are in Tokyo.
   The president said his policy was meant to encourage
``discussions'' between Hussein and Israel ``and to build on the
progress that has been made already.''
   At the same time, Bush said the PLO had advocated ``very useful''
changes. Apparently he was referring to Chairman Yasser Arafat's
declaration last year that he accepted Israel's right to exist and
had renounced terrorism.
   ``The question is what specific steps we take next,'' Bush said,
``and I don't want to be rushing out because Mr. Shevardnadze went
to the Middle East. I'd like to have for the first step we take of
that nature to be a prudent step.''
   The president added: ``I don't want to be stampeded by the fact
that the Soviet foreign minister takes a trip to the Middle East.''
   In the past, the Soviets have backed radical Arabs and kept their
distance from Israel, with whom they broke relations after the 1967
Middle East war.
   Shevardnadze's meeting with Arens on Wednesday could step up a
resumption of diplomatic ties, while his stop in Cairo where he will
also see Arafat separately on Wednesday suggests support for Egypt
and mainstream Arab positions.
   And yet, Bush said the role of the Soviets in Mideast diplomacy
``should be a limited role, and I think that's what it's going to
be. ... And that's exactly the way it should be and I think the
people in the Middle East feel that way. But the fact that he goes
there really shouldn't be bad.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
