<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BundyMeeting     02-21 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bundy Meeting,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Gather At Quantico To Compare Notes On Bundy Crimes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain; conference is closed to public.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUANTICO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement officers from around the
country Tuesday met to analyze what Ted Bundy said before his
execution and determine which victims can be tied to the serial
killer.
   The FBI is holding the weeklong conference of about 20 law
enforcement officers at its National Center for the Analysis of
Violent Crime.
   ``There are a lot of people out there, a lot of agents who have
wondered if Bundy has committed crimes in their area,'' FBI
spokeswoman Kathy Bradford said. ``They've done them before on other
serial killer cases because they (serial killers) have a tendency to
move around the country.
   ``It's just a matter of sifting through the facts and seeing what
we can come up with.''
   The goal is to learn as much as possible about Bundy so other
convicted killers, present or future, cannot file appeals attempting
to shift guilt for their crimes onto Bundy, said Florida Deputy
Attorney General Jim York.
   ``I sure don't want a bunch of spurious appeals trying to blame
everything in the world on Bundy,'' he said.
   Ms. Bradford said details of the closed-door conference will be
annouced Friday or Monday.
   Bundy was executed in Florida last month for the murder of a
schoolgirl.
   The former law student maintained his innocence during 10 years
on death row, but as his appeals ran out and his execution date
neared, he confessed to at least 23 slayings in Washington state,
Colorado, Utah and Florida.
   In some instances, Bundy implicated himself in slayings in which
he had not been a suspect or ones that investigators were unable to
match to any known killings.
   Some law enforcement experts claim Bundy may have been involved
in 100 or more slayings of young women in Oregon, Idaho, Vermont,
New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
   Agents will try to establish Bundy's movements from the time he
reached puberty in Washington until his arrest in Florida, the FBI
said.
   Defense attorneys had asked the governor of Florida to delay
Bundy's execution to give him time to tell more about unsolved
slayings. The appeal was denied.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
