<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan-Flag     02-21 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan-Flag,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flag Maker Defends Label-switching Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The company that suggested U.S. importers
of its American flags switch the ``Made in Taiwan'' label to ``Made
in USA'' said it wants nothing more to do with U.S. protectionism.
   General Manager Ni Feng-ming said his company has switched to
making national flags for Canada, Japan, West Germany and Australia
after the 1987 suggestion to switch labels failed to get many U.S.
orders.
   ``We stopped sales to the United States about two years ago
because our products were strongly rejected,'' Ni Feng-ming, general
manager of Ming Teh, said in an interview. ``I guess Americans hate
to see their national flag made by foreigners.''
   The businessman added: ``American protectionism is really scary.''
   Although Ni says his company no longer exports American flags to
the United States because of protectionism and the appreciation of
the Taiwan dolla, both U.S. and Taiwan officials have expressed
concern over Ming Teh's label-switching suggestion.
   The U.S. Customs Service has ordered closer scrutiny of American
flags from Ming Teh following complaints from American flag
manufacturers and several members of the U.S. Congress.
   An official at Taiwan's Board of Foreign Trade said Tuesday
authorities have started an investigation to determine whether Ming
Teh violated any law.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Taipei
would take measures to ``discourage any label-switching ideas.''
   Ni stressed his company never changed the labels on its flags. He
said a salesperson suggested in June 1987 promotional letters that
U.S. importers remove ``Made in Taiwan'' tags from the company's
half-finished exports and add a ``Made In USA'' label once
processing was completed in the United States.
   Ming Teh dyed and printed the American flags and U.S. companies
did cutting and sewing, according to Ni.
   The huge Taiwan trade surplus with the United States has led to
friction between the two countries. Last year, the surplus was $10.4
billion on total trade of $36.43 billion.
   Mou Tun, an official at the China External Trade Development
Council, said Ming Teh was just ``trying to be considerate'' by
offering an alternative to U.S. importers who wanted to buy
Taiwan-made flags but did not want to upset U.S. flag makers.
</TEXT>
