<FIRST>r i AM-Thatcher-Crash     02-21 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thatcher-Crash,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Joins Survivors, Mourners at Boeing 737 Crash Memorial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
joined rescuers and survivors of last month's British Midland air
crash at a memorial service Tuesday for the 47 people who died.
   Before a gathering of 1,300 people at St. Anne's Anglican
Cathedral, leaders of Ireland's four main churches unveiled a scroll
for permanent display listing the names of those who died when the
Belfast-bound Boeing 737 crashed in central England on Jan. 8.
   British Midland Airways Chairman Michael Bishop read a passage
from the Bible and Archbishop Robin Eames, primate of the Anglican
Church of Ireland, talked of the responsibility borne by those who
provide public transport.
   ``It is at times like this that we are made aware of the awesome
responsibility of those who provide public transportation, of those
who for a few hours hold so many human lives in their hands,'' Eames
said.
   But he praised the airline, saying: ``From the chairman to the
youngest stewardess their reaction and their humanity went far
beyond the call of duty.''
   The jet crashed into the side of a major highway, close to the
runway of East Midlands Airport, after reporting engine trouble. The
cause is under investigation.
   Among the congregation were some of the 79 survivors of the
crash, some in wheelchairs or on crutches, and relatives of those
who died. Twenty-six of the victims were from Northern Ireland.
   Mrs. Thatcher flew to Belfast from Frankfurt at the end of a
two-day summit with West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   She and other dignitaries spent 30 minutes talking with survivors
and relatives after the service.
   It also was attended by Tom King, the British government's
secretary for Northern Ireland, Transport Secretary Paul Channon and
the Duke of Gloucester, a cousin of Queen Elizabeth II.
