<FIRST>r i AM-NATO     02-21 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador to NATO Expected to Leave in Summer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. ambassador to NATO plans to
leave his post this summer to return to the United States and a job
in private business, a knowledgeable source said Tuesday.
   Alton G. Keel Jr. will stay on at the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization through a summit of President Bush and other leaders of
the 16 alliance nations, said the source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   No formal date has yet been set for the high-level gathering,
although officials have said they expect it to be in late May in
Brussels.
   Keel will likely leave his job soon after the summit, probably in
June, said the source.
   ``He intends when he goes back to the United States to go in the
private sector,'' he said.
   The source noted reports that Keel might be in the running for
other jobs in the Bush administration but said Keel has asked that
his name not be considered. A successor has not been announced.
   Keel, 45, was sworn in as the U.S. representative to NATO on
March 13, 1987. Prior to that, he was acting assistant for national
security affairs to former President Reagan.
   The Hampton, Va. native was appointed a Congressional Science
Fellow in 1976 and from 1978 to 1981 was a senior staff member of
the Senate Armed Services Committee.
   In 1981, he was named assistant secretary of the Air Force for
research, development and logistics. A year later, he was chosen
associate director for national security and international affairs
of the Office of Management and Budget.
   For five months in 1986, he directed the presidential commission
investigating the accident of the space shuttle Challenger and then
joined Reagan's National Security Council staff.
   Keel's wife, Franmarie Kennedy-Keel, returned to Washington in
November to take a position at the White House.
</TEXT>
