<FIRST>r i AM-Lithuania     02-21 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lithuania,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lithuanian Now Official Language of Lithuania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lithuanian's Council of Ministers on Tuesday
published a decree making Lithuanian the official language of the
Baltic republic to be used in all spheres of life, including
education and government, Tass said.
   At the same time, a plenum of the Communist Party Central
Committee in the capital of Vilnius issued a warning to nationalists
to avoid a policy of confrontation.
   The decision to make Lithuanian the official language was adopted
by the republic's legislature in October after years of pressure
from nationalist groups and came into force with the publication of
the decree by the Council of Ministers.
   ``Congresses, sessions, plenary meetings and other forums are to
be held in Lithuanian,'' the official news agency said in a dispatch
from Vilnius, the capital of Lithuania. ``If need be, translation of
reports into Russian or from Russian into Lithuanian will be
organized. The same goes for contacts with citizens at governmental
or public institutions, at public health and communal services and
judicial bodies.''
   Lithuanians account for approximately 80 percent of the 3.6
million population. ``Most Russians, Poles, Byelorussians and Jews
living in the republic speak Lithuanian,'' Tass said, a factor taken
into consideration when drafting Tuesday's decree.
   In a separate dispatch, Tass said a plenum of the republic's
Central Committee on Tuesday discussed the implications of the
nationalist movement on President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's program of
economic restructuring, known as perestroika.
   ``In Lithuania, forces have been formed which in words are for
the speeding-up of perestroika, but in deeds hamper it by their many
actions,'' Tass said.
   The news agency said a situation had been created in which there
was a threat of splitting Lithuanian society.
   ``The plenum stressed the urgency of the adoption of decisions
and resolute measures for cohesion of the republican party
organizations and demanded from party organizations and from all
communists to meet any threat of nationalist hostility and
nationalist chauvinism,'' Tass said.
   It said the Central Committee would continue to assess the
activities of unofficial nationalist movements.
</TEXT>
