<FIRST>r w AM-PeaceGarden     02-21 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peace Garden,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Garden Design Competition Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of a proposed public garden in the
nation's capital to provide a ``living monument to peace'' opened a
national competition Tuesday for its design.
   Congress approved the idea _ the inspiration of Elizabeth
Ratcliff, a former teacher from Berkeley, Calif. _ and President
Reagan signed it into law in June 1987, giving organizers five years
to raise the $4 million to $6 million for the project.
   Applicants must register with the Peace Garden Competition by May
26 and submit designs by the end of August. The winning design will
be announced in September.
   The National Endowment of the Arts has given the Peace Garden
Project a $75,000 grant to help finance the competition, and the
California-based Columbia Foundation and LEF Foundation also have
donated money.
   Organizers estimate it will cost $250,000 to conduct the design
contest, including awarding prizes of $20,000 for the winner,
$10,000 for second place, $5,000 for third place, and $500 prizes
for honorable mention.
   The project will be constructed with the help of private funds.
The federal government will own and maintain it the garden, located
on six acres at Hains Point near the Jefferson Memorial.
   Mrs. Ratcliff said the inspiration for a National Peace Garden
came to her when she was visiting Washington in 1985.
   ``I just looked around and saw all the great monuments to the
past and all the wars we've been involved in,'' Mrs. Ratcliff said.
``It just suddenly came into my mind that what we needed in our
capital is a living monument to peace.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITORS: Applicants for the garden design competition should</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   register with Peace Garden Competition, P.O. Box 27558, Washington
D.C., 20038.
</TEXT>
