<FIRST>r w AM-SpottedOwl     02-21 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spotted Owl,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Says Agency Officials Ordered Changes in Report on Spotted Owl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fish and Wildlife Service officials, in an
effort to keep the spotted owl off the endangered list, ordered
changes in a report which originally said the bird may face
extinction, according to a General Accounting Office report released
Tuesday.
   The GAO, an arm of Congress, said officials ignored scientific
evidence and ordered revisions in a study prepared by biologists in
the agency's Northwest regional office. Scientists had concluded
that unless logging was slowed in ancient forests of the Northwest,
the owl could face extinction.
   The timber industry in the Northwest has opposed any effort to
name the owl a threatened or endangered species, fearing that such a
move would disrupt logging in public forests. Environmentalists have
advocated protecting the owl as part of their campaign to halt
logging of old growth forests.
   ``While changes are an inevitable part of any draft report review
process, the nature of the changes made in this case and the way
they were made raise questions about whether objectivity was
maintained,'' the GAO said.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service, an Interior Department agency
which determines what should be designated for protection as
threatened or endangered, is required to consider only ``biological
factors'' in making its decision.
   The service concluded in December 1987 that the owl, which lives
only in old growth forests of Oregon, Washington and northern
California, was not endangered, and refused to grant a petition
requesting that the bird be protected.
   The GAO said decisions on whether to classify a bird, animal or
plant as endangered ``can often be surrounded by highly emotional
debates centered on the decision's possible economic consequences
rather than its biological merits.
   ``In such cases especially, the Fish and Wildife Service needs to
be able to demonstrate that its review process and ultimate
decisions have been thorough, independent, and objective as
possible,'' GAO said. ``There is evidence the spotted owl process
did not meet such standards.''
   The GAO said agency ``management officials substantially changed
the body of scientific evidence'' found in the original report.
   ``The revisions had the effect of changing the report from one
that emphasized the dangers facing the owl to one that could more
easily support denying the listing petition,'' the GAO said.
   The agency's decision not to list the owl as endangered was
challenged in court and a federal judge has given the service until
May 1 to provide additional information on how it reached its
decision.
   An agency spokesman on Tuesday declined comment on the GAO
report. ``We would like to at least read it first,'' said Craig
Reiben, a Fish and Wildlife Service spokesman.
   ``The Fish and Wildlife Service's decision not to list the
spotted owl as an endangered species appears to have been based on
politics, not science or law,'' said Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass. He
said he planned to ask Fish and Wildlife Service Director Frank
Dunkle about the case at a hearing Wednesday.
   Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., said the GAO report shows the
decision not to protect the owl was a ``simple case of political
expediency winning out over sound scientific evaluation and good
policy.
   ``We need the scientific facts about the spotted owl, not the
biased views of political appointees at the Department of Interior.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
