<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Sanctions     02-21 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Sanctions,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Justices Will Weigh Sanctions Against Defunct NY Law Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court said Tuesday it will use a
case involving an abandoned movie project to examine penalties for
law firms accused of breaking a rule against needless lawsuits.
   The court agreed to hear an appeal by a defunct New York City law
partnership ordered to pay $50,000 for violating the rules.
   The case stems from a lawsuit filed by Northern J. Calloway, an
actor who plays the character David on television's ``Sesame
Street.``
   Calloway sued Marvel Entertainment Group and others, accusing
them of copyright and other violations on a proposed animated
science fiction movie to be called ``The Skyrider.''
   Calloway sought $44 million in damages.
   A federal judge imposed $100,000 in sanctions against Calloway,
$50,000 against his attorney, Ray LeFlore, and $50,000 against the
now dissolved law firm of Pavelic &amp; LeFlore.
   The penalties were imposed for violating a court rule aimed at
preventing frivolous lawsuits and herassing and delaying tactics by
lawyers.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in upholding the penalties
against LeFlore and the law firm last August, said, ``Calloway's
case was at all times very weak. From the very beginning, (his) case
suffered from obvious and grave weaknesses.''
   For example, the appeals court said, none of the people sued made
any money from the proposed movie project and most lost money on the
venture.
   In its appeal to the Supreme Court, Pavelic &amp; LeFlore said the
$50,000 sanction against the firm should be thrown out because only
LeFlore _ and not the firm _ signed key papers in the suit.
   LeFlore did not appeal to the high court to throw out the $50,000
penalty against him personally.
   The case is Pavelic &amp; LeFlore vs. Marvel Entertainment, 88-791.
</TEXT>
