<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev     02-21 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet President Defends Policy on Cooperatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Tuesday defended
a government order freezing cooperatives out of the medical
business, saying the private business was taking up too many
government resources.
   His remarks, broadcast on the evening TV news program ``Vremya,''
came on a visit to Lvov on his trip to the Ukrainian republic.
   The 57-year-old Soviet leader toured a television factory,
addressed city scientific and cultural leaders, and held discussions
with groups of citizens at the airport and on street corners.
   The official Soviet media said Gorbachev will visit the Chernobyl
area on his trip, nearly three years after the world's worst nuclear
power plant disaster occurred there.
   Gorbachev said in response to a complaint from an elderly woman
about medical cooperatives that Moscow officials heard some medical
equipment was not being used in the state-run system so it would be
ready for cooperatives, which charge their patients.
   ``After 2 or 3 o'clock, everything worked fine,'' Gorbachev said.
``It turned out that in the first part of the day it was being
prepared to be used for cooperatives.''
   In late December the government ordered cooperatives out of the
medical field, TV stores and other potentially high-profit services
that also require relatively big investments.
   Government officials said they moved against medical cooperatives
to ensure public health.
   But leaders of the cooperative movement saw it as an effort to
keep them out of profitable areas.
   Gorbachev has pushed the cooperative movement as a means to
provide goods and services that the state-run economy cannot or will
not provide. He said the Soviet Union needs them but should control
them through taxation and efforts to limit the amount of money their
workers can earn.
   Lvov, a railway, automobile assembly and oil refining city with a
population of 753,000, lies 260 miles west of Kiev, in a part of the
Ukraine that became part of the Soviet Union only at the end of
World War II.
   Lvov is still a center of Ukrainian nationalism.
   Gorbachev toured the Elektron factory, and factory workers told
him about plans to increase output of TV sets, which Tass said were
in short supply.
   Aside from being scarce, Soviet television sets are notoriously
dangerous. The state-run press has carried articles saying
Soviet-made color TV sets are prone to explode and are a major cause
of fires.
   Gorbachev found out Monday in Kiev, the republic's capital, that
the dangers of nuclear power are still much on the minds of
Ukrainians.
   In a street encounter broadcast on television, an elderly woman
asked Gorbachev why another nuclear power plant was being built in
the Crimea.
   The area contains some of the country's most popular beach
resorts and is home to 2 million people.
   Gorbachev said he was aware of worries about plant safety. He
said American specialists had been asked to study the Crimean
facility.
   ``Construction is under way,'' he said. ``But if the conclusion
(of the specialists) is that it is not advisable to build a station
there, then it will be turned into a training center for personnel,
not an atomic power station.''
   An explosion and fire at a nuclear reactor at Chernobyl on April
26, 1986, killed at least 31 people and sent a radioactive cloud
around the world.
   Since then, the Soviets have moved away from complete faith in
the safety of nuclear power, and public opposition to it has grown.
   Last week, Moscow News said cancer cases have doubled in a region
30 miles from Chernobyl where people were not evacuated.
</TEXT>
