<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Katyn     02-21 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Katyn,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government to Change Inscription on Katyn Monument</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday it will change
a monument inscription saying the Nazis killed more than 4,000
Polish army officers during World War II. It cited a Polish Red
Cross document that indicates the Soviets killed them.
   The announcement came from government spokesman Jerzy Urban, who
stopped short of saying that the Soviets were guilty of the crime in
the Katyn Forest in western Russia. He also did not say what the
Warsaw monument will read.
   ``We expect that this problem will be explained by the two sides
and on the basis of more comprehensive information,'' Urban told a
news conference.
   Urban referred to a broadcast by Radio Moscow on Monday which,
according to Urban, said the Red Cross report was ``serious evidence
requiring serious examination that the Katyn crime was committed by
Soviet security forces in the Stalinist epoch, and not by the
Nazis.''
   The 12-foot granite monument at Warsaw's Powazki Cemetery has an
inscription at its base saying it is ``To Polish Soldiers _ Victims
of Hitlerite Fascism Resting in the Ground of Katyn.''
   Urban said the government also plans to move the monument, now in
an out-of-the-way corner of the cemetery.
   The massacre in the Katyn Forest, 12 miles west of Smolensk, is
one of the most searing issues in Polish-Soviet relations, and for
years the word itself was too sensitive to be uttered in public.
   Official postwar histories all maintained the officers were
killed by Nazis in winter 1941, but most Poles and Western
historians have said they were killed by the Soviets in the spring
of 1940, when the Soviet Union and Nazi Germany were still allied.
   In addition to the 4,300 bodies found at Katyn, 11,000 other
officers are unaccounted for and presumed dead after they were
imprisoned in the Soviet Union in the first days of World War II.
The officers represented about half of Poland's prewar officer corps.
   The monument blaming the Nazis for Katyn was erected in April
1985 and unveiled without public notice after some family members of
Katyn victims erected unauthorized crosses at the site in memory of
the slain officers. The crosses were taken down.
   Each Aug. 1 and Nov. 1, dates when Poles remember their war dead,
large groups of people gather at the monument, and many use candles
and flowers to cover over the inscription they regard as false.
   A joint committee of Polish and Soviet historians created in
April 1987 is examining the Katyn issue as part of an effort to
correct ``blank spots'' in the two countries' history.
   In November, the Soviet newspaper Izvestia reported that the
Soviet Council of Ministers approved plans for a monument in Katyn
for prisoners of war, but the report gave no construction schedule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
