<DOCNO> AP890221-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2004EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Yeutter-Jamaica     02-21 0114</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeutter-Jamaica,100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expanded Food for Peace Agreement Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jamaica will be able to buy wheat and lumber
under a $10 million expansion of a Food for Peace agreement with the
Caribbean nation, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter announced the amended
agreement in Kingston, Jamaica, after meeting with officials there,
including Prime Minister Michael Manley and Governor General Sir
Florizel Glasspole, the department said.
   Yeutter's visit to Jamaica had not been announced by the
department in advance.
   The Food for Peace arrangement allows Jamaica to buy $5 million
worth of wood products and $5 million worth of wheat or wheat flour
under the program's long-term credit provisions.
</TEXT>
