<FIRST>r p AM-GOP-Duke 1stLd-Writethru a0667 02-21 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GOP-Duke, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Tops with 9 grafs to update with conflict between national and
state GOP; picks up 5th graf previous: For national x x x</HEAD>
<HEAD>GOP Chairman Thinks His Comments May Have Aided Ex-Klansman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Republican Party officials were in
conflict with Lousiana GOP legislators Tuesday over how to react to
the election under the GOP banner of former Ku Klux Klansman David
Duke.
   Duke won a seat in the Louisiana House of Representatives on
Saturday and national party chairman Lee Atwater declared the party
had no intention of accepting him as a member.
   Under Atwater's direction, a resolution was prepared declaring
that Duke was ``not a Republican in gesture, deed or belief.''
   The resolution is expected to be adopted by the party's 11-member
executive council, which will confer by telephone Friday.
   However, in Baton Rouge, La., Republican legislators said they
saw no reason to reject Duke.
   ``We can't be responsible for what he did before he was
registered as a Republican,'' said Rep. Art Sour, a Republican. ``I
don't understand what Atwater is talking about. Censure him for
what? The only control we have over him is what he's done since he's
been a Republican.''
   ``We will see if Mr. Duke is what he says he is or what the media
says he is,'' said Rep. Peppi Bruneau of New Orleans, GOP caucus
chairman. ``If he's what he says he is, he has no problem. He got to
the House the same way everybody else did.''
   Atwater also voiced concern that his effort to denounce the
former Ku Klux Klansman ``plays right into his hands'' by giving
Duke a new forum.
   ``I'm going to refrain from discussing Mr. Duke anymore,''
Atwater told reporters at the White House.
   For national party officials, the election of Duke came as the
GOP was launching an intensive campaign to win support among blacks
who have voted overwhelmingly Democratic in national elections.
   At a brief news conference Tuesday, President Bush conceded his
endorsement of Duke's opponent might have been viewed by Louisiana
voters as ``improper or overkill.''
   But, the president said, ``I did what I did because of principle
... this man, his record is one of racism and bigotry, and, I'm
sorry, I just felt I had to speak out.''
   Duke, 38, defeated homebuilder John Treen, 63, in Saturday's
election for a seat in the Louisiana House of Representatives
despite endorsements for Treen by Bush, former President Reagan and
the most powerful political figures in the suburban New Orleans
area. Both candidates were registered as Republicans.
   ``I have no desire to impeach him from office,'' said Atwater.
   The GOP chairman said he wanted Republicans to ``officially
disassociate ourselves as a party from Mr. Duke.''
   Atwater noted that Duke had previously run for office as a
Democrat and had re-registered as a Republican only three days
before the election.
   ``He is not a man, who, I think, stands for either party,'' said
Atwater. ``He's an opportunist. ... There's a 20-year career there
in which he was a man of the swastika, vehemently anti-Semitic,
vehemently racist.''
   The GOP chairman said he would henceforth refrain from discussing
the Duke matter because ``it plays right into his hands. What he
wants is to get into a prolongued argument with me on television,
any other kind of media.
   ``He's a very effective demagogue and I'm not going to give him
an opportunity to do that any more. ... I'm not going to let myself
become a dupe in his play to get more free media coverage.''
   Atwater reiterated his contention that Duke ``does not represent
our party in any shape, form or fashion.'''
</TEXT>
