<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1725EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ParachutingDeath     02-21 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Parachuting Death,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Record Holder Dies in Parachute Jump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHERIDAN, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Frenchman fell to his death doing what he
had done more than anyone else in the world _ parachute jumping.
   ``He would jump with anybody anytime,'' said Ted Mayfield,
founder of the Pacific Parachute Center, where 59-year-old Roch
Pierre Charmet died Monday when his parachute failed to open
properly. ``That was his whole life.''
   Charmet, who held the world record for the most parachute jumps
with more than 14,000, had made six jumps when he went up for what
was to be the last for the day.
   Mayfield on Tuesday recalled that on the way up Charmet played a
French drinking song, something about knights of the Round Table
drinking wine, on a harmonica he recently learned to play. Charmet
jumped out at 2,500 feet.
   ``Normally, you wait three or four seconds and pull out a
hand-deployed pilot chute,'' said Mayfield. ``I could see him
fighting with something. At 500 feet the pilot chute came out, then
just a ball of material is all we could see.''
   He pulled the release on his back-up parachute, but it was too
late, Mayfield said. Charmet landed on a stack of lumber.
   An investigator from the Federal Aviation Administration arrived
Tuesday to inspect the parachute gear, which Charmet had packed
himself.
   Charmet lived in Montlhery, France, and was an instructor with
the Parachute Institute of France, authorities said.
   Small and lightly built with a gray beard and long gray hair, he
learned to jump while serving with the French Foreign Legion in
Algeria in the 1950s, and his 14,600-odd parachute jumps were
recognized as the world record by the United States Parachute
Association, Mayfield said.
   ``His favorite saying was, `Only skydivers know why birds
sing,''' Mayfield said. ``It's the freedom he would feel of leaving
the aircraft and being able to fly. That's what he felt.''
   For the past 15 years, Charmet had been spending a few months
each winter in this town of 2,400 people situated about 45 miles
southwest of Portland.
   ``He originally came here because he fell in love with a girl
traveling in France who was from here,'' Mayfield said. ``He
followed her here. When he arrived she was married to somebody else.
He liked the area and the people here, so he just came back every
year.''
   While in Sheridan, Charmet jumped repeatedly and broke the world
record here last year.
   Charmet's passion was accuracy jumping, leaving an airplane at
2,500 feet and landing on a 5-centimeter target.
   ``He'd make like 800 jumps in three months,'' Mayfield said. ``He
would line up four or five parachutes, pack them all, then make four
or five jumps. He would do this all day long.''
</TEXT>
