<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2009EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LouisianaTaxes     02-21 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Taxes,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Louisiana Special Session on Tax Overhaul Opens Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Legislature meets in special session
Wednesday to debate Gov. Buddy Roemer's second plan to overhaul
Louisiana's tax system.
   Roemer, who pledged during the 1987 campaign to change the
state's populist-based tax system to lighten some of the burden on
businesses in order to create jobs, saw his original outline fail
before lawmakers in October.
   Legislators said their chief objection was a proposal to lower
the state's $75,000 homestead exemption from property taxation to
$25,000. Roemer has dropped the proposal, conceding it is
politically impossible now.
   ``It's much more of a consensus plan,'' Roemer said of the
revamped proposal. ``The Legislature has been much more intimately
involved in this. It's not everything I'd like to have, but I think
it's possible to pass.''
   Roemer said his plan would reduce state sales taxes by $100
million, increase income taxes by $175 million, give businesses a
tax break and create a highway, airport and port construction
program through a 4-cent excise tax on gasoline.
   The $75 million tax break for businesses would be made up through
income tax increases, mostly in the upper-income levels, the
governor said.
   Roemer said the move would help create jobs in a state plagued by
unemployment of more than 10 percent and help stabilize state
government, which has stumbled through several fiscal crises since
the collapse of oil prices and faces a $654 million shortfall for
the 1989-90 budget year.
   If the plan receives the necessary two-thirds vote from both
chambers, parts of it, such as the income tax increase, still must
be approved by the voters on April 29 in the form of a
constitutional amendment.
   Getting voters to back the plan may be the most difficult task,
one of Roemer's legislative floor leaders predicted.
   Rep. Ron Gomez, chairman of the House tax-writing committee, said
the program may be read by some voters as shifting business taxes
``on the backs of the people.''
   ``That's because we've operated so long under the rule of `Don't
tax you, don't tax me, tax the man behind the tree.' Well, there's
no one left behind the tree,'' said Gomez.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
