<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     02-21 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stabbed, Israeli Soldier Kills Palestinian Assailant</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviets-Mideast, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Palestinians attacked and stabbed an
Israeli soldier during an army raid in a small West Bank village
late Tuesday, and the wounded soldier opened fire, killing one of
his assailants, the army said.
   Elsewhere in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, army gunfire
wounded eight Palestinians on Tuesday, including a 14-year-old hit
in his thigh, a 13-year-old shot in the leg and an 18-year-old
critically wounded in the shoulder, Arab doctors said.
   Businesses in the occupied territories remained shut for a third
straight day in the longest work stoppage ordered by underground
uprising leaders.
   Observance of the strike was seen as a key test of the strength
of pro-PLO leaders of the uprising that began on Dec. 8, 1987. The
rebellion has killed 384 Palestinians and 16 Israelis.
   Dedi Zucker, a left-wing legislator, said Tuesday that most
Palestinian victims in the West Bank were killed during army raids
in remote villages and a growing number of the fatalities were
teen-agers rather than adults.
   Zucker, of the Citizens' Rights Movement, said a new Israeli
human rights group called Image was formed this week to rouse public
awareness of complaints of abuses by soldiers in the territories,
which were captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   ``People are ignoring what is happening,'' Zucker told a
gathering of the Foreign Press Association in Jerusalem.
   An army spokesman said a band of Palestinians attacked troops
making a security sweep on Tuesday in Abu Dis, a village of 3,000
about three miles east of Jerusalem, and that one of them stabbed
and slightly wounded a soldier while ``the others assisted in the
attack.''
   He said the injured soldier fired on the group, killing one Arab,
and that the others were detained. The spokesman, who remained
anonymous under army rules, did not elaborate, and it was not
immediately clear whether the victim actually did the stabbing or
assisted in it.
   An official at east Jerusalem's Mukassed Hospital identified the
man as 57-year-old Mohammed Said Rishik, and said he was shot in the
heart.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, quoted family
members as saying Rishik was shot inside his house by men in
civilian clothes. But the army spokesman said he ``definitely
participated in the attack.''
   Zucker said a study of the 322 Palestinians the army says were
killed in the first 13 months of the uprising showed most West Bank
victims were from isolated villages rather than refugee camps, often
considered hotbeds of anti-Israeli activity.
   He said the raids are often staged to root out popular committees
who declare autonomy from Israeli authorities.
   Zucker's contentions challenged a key army assertion that
soldiers use violence in the occupied territories mainly in response
to stoning and firebomb attacks on troops and civilians.
   An army spokesman said raids in villages were essential to
maintaining order on West Bank highways.
   Zucker, whose party advocates a separate Palestinian state, urged
the army to help prevent shootings by soldiers by giving stiffer
punishments to troops convicted of violating open-fire regulations.
   Also Tuesday, police officials said a Jewish cabbie whose taxi
burst into flames in the West Bank on Feb. 8 was killed by a fire
resulting from a technical fault in his vehicle, and not a firebomb
attack as earlier believed.
   Immediately after the death, Jewish settlers stoned Arab-owned
cars and injured two Palestinian motorists.
</TEXT>
