<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Trade-Telecommunications     02-21 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade-Telecommunications,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consider Trade Sanctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Tuesday targeted
South Korea and the 12-nation European Community for possible trade
sanctions if the countries do not agree to lower trade barriers
blocking U.S. export sales of telecommunications equipment.
   The decision was announced by U.S. Trade Representative Carla
Hills, who acted after a five-month investigation required under the
1988 Trade Act.
   The law requires the United States to open negotiations with
countries deemed by U.S. trade officials to be blocking sales by
American firms of telecommunications equipment.
   If the talks don't succeed in removing trade barriers within a
year, the law requires the administration to impose trade sanctions.
However, the administration has the option of extending the talks
for as long as two more years if U.S. officials believe that
progress is being made.
   The announcement said the decision was made by Mrs. Hills after
reviewing comments from industry, labor, other federal agencies,
members of Congress and foreign governments.
   ``Criteria for the examination included not only trade barriers,
but also each nation's market potential and any measurable progress
that it might be making toward (trade) liberalization,'' the trade
office said in a statement.
</TEXT>
