<FIRST>u w AM-BushtheTraveler 1stLd-Writethru a0630 02-21 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush the Traveler, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Goes Abroad with Well-Stamped Passport</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Japan Memories Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 12th graf bgng: Bush first ... to CORRECT dates of trips.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush has never been to Sarawak. He
hasn't made it to Benin either. He's also passed up Suriname and has
not set foot in Chad, although he flew over it once.
   From a look at the president's itinerary as a government
official, however, it appears these are among a relatively few
countries he hasn't visited.
   Unlike President Reagan, who had made only a few trips abroad
before entering the White House, Bush goes to Japan, China and Seoul
this month with a well-stamped passport already in his pocket.
   In eight years as vice president, he visited 82 countries.
   This will be his fifth trip to China, where he has traveled to
Soujou, Chengdu, Guilin, Guanzhou and Shenzen as well as Beijing.
   He has sailed through a gorge of limestone peaks along the Li
River, cruised on the Nile to view the tombs and temples of the
Pharaohs, and gone speedboating on the Gulf of Aqaba with Jordan's
King Hussein.
   He has toured a Pepsi-Cola bottling plant in Shenzen, an oil
refinery in North Yemen, a water treatment plant in Cairo and a farm
in Poland with a thatch roof on its 100-year-old barn.
   He bumped through a desert game preserve in four-wheel-drive vans
in North Yemen, made a bumpy landing in a helium-filled craft Expo
86 in Vancouver, B.C., and stood atop a Jordanian bunker overlooking
the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights.
   He has met in his travels with Solidarity leader Lech Walesa,
Pope John Paul II, French President Francois Mitterrand, British
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, among others.
   On the way he has made some provocative comments. On the deck of
the carrier Enterprise in the Gulf of Oman, he called Libyan leader
Moammar Gadhafi a ``mad dog.'' Touring the Persian gulf, he touched
a political nerve by expressing concern about plummeting oil prices.
In Belgium, he heard a report of a new Soviet tank and said if
Soviet tank mechanics ran out of work ``send them to Detroit because
we could use that kind of ability.''
   He has attended the funerals of three Soviet leaders.
   Bush first went to China in September, 1974, and spent 16 months
as the U.S. envoy to Beijing. He returned in 1977 as a guest of the
Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs, went back as
Republican vice presidential candidate in 1980 and carried out
missions to China for President Reagan in 1982 and 1985.
   In 1972, while U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, Bush
traveled to Khartoum, Sudan, and Nairobi, Kenya.
   Here is a rundown of his travels as vice president:
   June, 1981 _ France, England and the Philippines, where he
represented the United States at the inauguration of President
Ferdinand Marcos.
   September, 1981 _ Independence celebration in Mexico.
   October, 1981 _ Dominican Republic, Colombia and Brazil.
   April, 1982 _ Japan, Korea, Singapore, Australia, New Zealand and
China.
   November, 1982 _ Cape Verde, Senegal, Nigeria, Zimbabwe, Zambia,
Kenya and Zaire, then to Moscow for funeral of Soviet President
Leonid Brezhnev.
   February, 1983 _ West Germany, The Netherlands, Belgium,
Switzerland, Italy, France, England.
   March, 1983 _ Canada.
   June and July, 1983 _ England, West Germany, Norway, Sweden,
Finland, Denmark, Ireland and Iceland.
   September, 1983 _ Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, Yugoslavia, Romania,
Hungary and Austria.
   October, 1983 _ Jamaica, Lebanon.
   December, 1983 _ Argentina for inauguration of President Raul
Alfonsin, Panama and El Salvador.
   February, 1984 _ England, Italy, France, Luxembourg, and to
Moscow for funeral of Soviet leader Yuri Andropov.
   April, 1984 _ Switzerland, for disarmament conference in Geneva.
   May, 1984 _ Japan, Indonesia, India, Pakistan, Oman.
   March, 1985 _ Sudan, Niger and Mali, then to Geneva to report on
the African drought and on to Moscow for the funeral of Soviet
leader Konstantin Chernenko and a meeting with Gorbachev, followed
by stop in Brazil for inauguration of President Tancredeo Neves and
visits to Grenada and Honduras.
   June, 1985 _ Italy, West Germany, The Netherlands, Belgium,
Switzerland, France, England.
   October, 1985 _ China, Hong Kong.
   April, 1986 _ West Germany, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Oman, North
Yemen.
   June, 1986 _ Canada.
   July, 1986 _ West Germany, Israel, Jordan, Egypt.
   October, 1986 _ Private fishing trip to Mexico.
   March, 1987 _ Ecuador in the wake of an earthquake there.
   September, 1987 _ Italy, Poland, West Germany, France, England,
Belgium.
   Bush's office said he also visited Venezuela, Bermuda and Guinea
as vice president.
   On the African trip, he flew over war-torn Chad to get from Sudan
to Mali, but did not stop.
</TEXT>
