<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2019EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Afghanistan-Mines     02-21 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Mines,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>US: Soviets Left Millions of Mines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet military forces left 10 million to 30
million land mines behind them when they pulled out of Afghanistan,
posing a ``tremendous impediment'' to the safe return and
resettlement of millions of refugees, a Defense Department official
told Congress on Wednesday.
   The official, Edward W. Gnehm Jr., deputy assistant secretary of
defense for Near Eastern affairs, said the Pentagon, operating under
United Nations auspices, has begun a comprehensive program of mine
awareness and disposal training for Afghan refugees in camps inside
Pakistan.
   A State Department witness reported, meanwhile, the Soviets have
halted air strikes into Afghanistan from bases inside Soviet
territory, ending the largest remaining problem of active warfare in
the country.
   Howard Schaffer, deputy assistant secretary of state for Near
Eastern Affairs, said also that because the level of human need
inside the country is ``enormous,'' the Bush administration is
``taking a fresh, sympathetic look'' into the possibility of
extending humanitarian assistance.
   He also said _ without offering an explanation _ the State
Department is confident that whatever government emerges in Kabul in
the aftermath of the withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan
``will be neither communist nor messianic Islamic.''
   Testifying before the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on Asian
and Pacific Affairs, Gnehm said a 40-person military training team,
part of a project dubbed ``Operation Safe Passage,'' has been
dispatched to Pakistan and will spend six months ``increasing the
awareness of large numbers of Afghan refugees of the threats they
will face as they return to their homes.''
   He said Afghan teams will be trained and given special equipment
to ``neutralize and dispose of land mines in their country.''
   Gnehm said that training posters have been produced in some of
the principal languages of Afghanistan which warn: ``Thousands of
people have been martyred by mines;'' ``Don't touch mines, they are
deadly'' and, ``All kinds of mines have been placed in Afghanistan.''
   Gnehm called the training program ``an unprecedented application
of special military skills for alleviating suffering from the
aftermaths of a terrible and brutal war.''
   ``Estimates of the number of mines range from 10 million to 30
million,'' Gnehm said. ``Most of the mines are antipersonnel devices
that have been scattered almost indiscriminately.''
   Responding to questions, he said that while the Soviets have said
they would they were defusing mines and were giving the communist
government in Kabul maps showing their location, ``to our knowledge
neither of these things has happened.
   He said the locations of the mines would be extremely difficult
to map since many of the antipersonnel devices were sewn from planes
and helicopters.
   He said an another danger is posed by the fact that heavy rains
have washed some of the explosive devices down from hill and
mountainsides into valleys used for farming.
   Gnehm also reported that since the first flight of an Air Force
C-5 cargo plane to Pakistan in March 1986, there have been a total
of 76 relief flights carrying more than 4.7 million pounds of excess
Defense Department property and privately donated supplies, all
intended to aid the refugees.
   Additionally, he said some 680 injured Afghan citizens have been
flown to Western Europe, Egypt and the United States to receive
medical treatment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1804EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AmocoCadiz     02-21 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amoco Cadiz,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Additional $30 Million Damages Recommended in 1978 Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired judge Tuesday recommended a $30 million
increase in his $85.2 million judgment against Amoco Corp. for
oil-spill damage from the 1978 wreck of a supertanker off the French
coast.
   The revised award would be shared by the government of France _
which would receive the single largest portion, $44.4 million _ and
some 100 French towns affected by the spill that fouled 100 miles of
coastline.
   Frank McGarr, who retired as a U.S. District Court judge after
his 1988 ruling, continues to serve as special master in the case
and made the recommendation after being asked by parties in the case
to reconsider the award.
   The recommendation is subject to approval by another federal
judge; no date has been set for a final judgment.
   Both sides objected to the revised award as well and vowed to
appeal. None of the money has been paid. The towns had received $7.3
million in the original judgment and sought an additional $8 million
but received only $200,000 more.
   ``Today's damage determinations continue to support the position
the Amoco parties have maintained throughout: that the claims of
damage from this unfortunate incident were exaggerated,''
Chicago-based Amoco said in a statement.
   ``What we will be asking the appeals court to do is recognize the
damage to the environment, the livelihoods of the people in
Brittany, and the quality of life,'' said attorney Barry Kingham,
who represented the towns, association of oystermen and fishermen,
hoteliers, and the two French counties most affected by the spill.
   ``The judge refused to recognize those damages and he continues
to reject them. He simply gave out-of-pocket expenses for the
cleanup effort.''
   Attorneys for both sides said the revised award totals about $115
million _ $61 million in damages and between $54 million and $60
million in interest.
   The supertanker Amoco Cadiz ran aground two miles off the
Brittany coast. The tanker, which had lost the use of its rudder,
had been under tow through the English Channel when the towlines
snapped in hurricane-force winds and heavy seas.
   The tanker lost 68 million gallons of mostly Iranian light crude
oil valued at $24 million. The spill killed thousands of birds and
millions of sea creatures and washing wave after wave of thick black
tar along the coast.
   In 1984, McGarr ruled that Amoco and two subsidiaries were liable
because of negligence in the design, repair and maintenance of the
vessel, which was 300 feet wide and longer than three football
fields.
</TEXT>
