<FIRST>r w AM-NorthTrial-Glance     02-21 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial-Glance,250</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief summary of opening statements
made Tuesday as the trial of Oliver North on 12 criminal charges in
connection with the Iran-Contra affair began.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Prosecution</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The government maintains North is a liar who placed ``himself
above the law'' when he lied to congressional committees and the
president about a secret operation conducted by government officials
and private businessmen from 1984 when Congress forbade further aid
to the Contras until the fall of 1986 when the public first learned
of the activities.
   ``The need for secrecy is no excuse for lies,'' said John Keker
who presented opening arguments from the office of independent
prosecutor Lawrence E. Walsh. Keker said North also used $4,000 of
the money secretly raised for the rebels from foreign countries and
private donors.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Defense</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Chief defense attorney Brendan Sullivan said North is a man who
worked in a world of secrets and had no criminal intent when he
obeyed orders and followed instructions from the government's
highest-ranking officials.
   Sullivan said North ``always acted with the approval of his
superiors; he acted always with the best interests of his country
... as any Marine Corps officer would.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Other Participants</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell is presiding in a 120-seat
courtroom. Sixty seats have been assigned to the press, 15 to the
public and the remainder to lawyers, prosecutors and government
security and intelligence personnel who will monitor the use of
classified information as evidence in the trial.
</TEXT>
