<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary     02-21 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Leadership Asking Whether 1950s Political Trials Were Rigged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leaders have asked historians
and jurists to determine whether political trials in the 1950s were
rigged, an official said Tuesday.
   The move could be a step toward rehabilitating leaders of the
1956 anti-communist uprising, some of whom were executed and buried
in unmarked graves.
   The Communist party leadership, on the second and final day of a
Central Committee meeting, also heard a report on the new
constitution, which is to leave out any reference to the leading
role of the party and allow a multi-party system.
   Gyoergy Fejti, secretary of the party Central Committee, said the
party has asked that a panel of legal experts and historians look
into the period from 1946 to 1962 to ``expose any possibility of
rigged procedures'' at trials conducted during that period.
   ``In search of a public consensus, we must strive to see that
suitable amends are made to those affected within the rehabilitation
process,'' Fejti told a news conference at the close of the meeting.
   But he appealed for patience and understanding, saying the
historical review would ``take time and we don't know what the
results will be.''
   The announcement came less than 10 days after the 108-member
Central Committee partially reassessed the 1956 revolt. That meeting
was provoked by leading reformer Imre Pozsgay, who said the revolt
that for 32 years was termed a counterrevolution was a popular
uprising.
   The leadership of the ruling Hungarian Socialist Workers'
(communist) Party reached a compromise formulation saying the revolt
had both popular and counterrevolutionary elements.
   The revolt, led by Imre Nagy against the regime of the Stalinist
Matyas Rakosi, started Oct. 23, 1956, and was brought to a bloody
end Nov. 4 that year when it was quashed by Soviet troops.
   Nagy and his associates were executed in June 1958. According to
a Ministry of Justice decree issued at the time, he and his
associates were sentenced to death for ``conspiracy to overthrow the
Hungarian People's Democratic System.''
   There have been repeated calls in Hungary for the rehabilitation
of Nagy and his associates. Authorities announced recently that they
would allow their reburial in marked graves.
   The purpose of the meeting ending Tuesday was to review main
concepts in the new constitution that will allow a multi-party
system, place greater emphasis on human and civil rights, and
strengthen political institutions, including giving the president
and Parliament a larger role.
   Fejti presented the main concepts of the new constitution, which
is to be adopted next year.
   ``We do not see the need and sense of the constitutional
formulation on the leading role'' of the Communist party, he was
quoted by the official MTI news agency as saying.
   However, he added that this ``does not mean that the HSWP
(Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party) renounces the political effort
and intention that it wishes to remain the determining factor of the
social processes,'' MTI said.
   Justice Ministry officials said in December that the draft of the
new constitution did not contain a reference to the leading role of
the party.
   Fejti said it is necessary to set down in the new law the
criteria that groups will be allowed to form if they are ``in
harmony with the values and efforts formulated in the constitution.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearPlants     02-21 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Plants,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Says Too Little Government Focus on Nuclear Weapons Cleanup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department's master plan for
refurbishing its nuclear weapons plants puts too little emphasis on
environmental cleanup at the decrepit facilities, a General
Accounting Office official told a House panel Tuesday.
   J. Dexter Peach, the GAO's assistant comptroller general, also
raised questions about the department's proposal for building two
new nuclear reactors to produce tritium, a perishable gas used in
the manufacture of nuclear warheads.
   The agency, the investigative arm of Congress, has prepared more
than 50 reports on pollution and operational problems in the weapons
industry since 1981 and has been critical of the Energy Department's
past management of arms plants.
   Peach told a House Armed Services subcommittee that the Energy
Department's plan, if carried out, would revitalize the nation's
nuclear weapons complex by the year 2010 but would leave key
environmental problems unsolved. The plan envisions spending at
least $244 billion over the next 21 years, with $32 billion is
earmarked for cleaning up environmental damage.
   ``In our opinion, the plan does not adequately address the
cleanup of existing facilities and decontamination of facilities as
they are retired from service,'' Peach said.
   The Energy Department plan was endorsed by former President
Reagan shortly before he left office. President Bush has not said
whether he supports it.
   James D. Watkins, Bush's designated energy secretary, has not
commented publicly on the modernization report, but he was almost
certain to face intense questioning about it at his Senate
confirmation hearing Wednesday.
   Peach, in his testimony, said Congress should closely review the
Energy Department's announced plans to build two new reactors to
produce tritium. The department's only existing tritium-producing
reactors are shut down because of safety and technical faults, and
they are expected to be permanently retired in the 1990s.
   The Energy Department wants to spend $6.8 billion to build the
two new reactors. Some critics have questioned the need for both
reactors, in view of the possibility that future U.S.-Soviet arms
control deals could reduce the need for tritium.
   Troy E. Wade II, the department's acting assistant secretary for
defense programs, told the House panel the high cost of building the
new reactors was justified.
   ``It is an issue of capacity ... to assure the necessary supplies
over the next two decades,'' he said, adding that it would be
prudent to have new reactors based on two different technologies in
order to guard against possible failures.
   Peach criticized the Energy Department master plan for failing to
spell out how, and over what time period, the environmental damage
caused by nuclear weapons production _ such as contaminated soil and
groundwater _ could be cleaned up.
   ``Uncertainty still exists not only regarding the size of the
problems but also regarding the extent to which DOE sites can be
cleaned up. Some locations may be irreversibly contaminated,'' Peach
said.
   Peach said the master plan calls for spending $401 million in the
coming budget year on environmental cleanup that eventually will
cost up to $70 billion.
   Several members of the House panel, including John Spratt,
D-S.C., also criticized the Energy Department, saying it has put
more emphasis on nuclear materials production than on safe and
environmentally sound operations.
   Ray Berube, the department's deputy assistant secretary for
environment, said, ``There is no current immediate public health and
safety risk'' posed by the weapons plants. He said there would be a
threat if the environmental issues were put off.
   Wade, meanwhile, said the department still expected to restart at
least one of its tritium-producing reactors, at the Savannah River
Plant in South Carolina, by the end of the year. He said a firm
timetable would be available next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0196 </DOCNO>
