<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Election     02-21 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Election,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Portrays Self as Gorbachev Backer in Electoral Show-Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris N. Yeltsin, the maverick former Moscow party
chief, called himself a close supporter of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policies Tuesday as he sought to represent the capital
in a new legislative body.
   Yeltsin, fired by Gorbachev in November 1987 after he criticized
the Communist Party's style of leadership, was one of 10 candidates
for nomination to go before an electoral commission of almost 900
members in the chandelier-lit, red-and-white Hall of Columns in
downtown Moscow's House of Unions.
   ``From the viewpoint of the strategy of external politics, I
fully support him,'' Yeltsin said. ``From the viewpoint of the
strategy of internal politics, fully. From the viewpoint of tactics,
I have my own opinion.''
   ``That's only natural,'' he added.
   The burly, 57-year old Yeltsin's shock of white hair stood out at
the podium and his voice boomed through the hall.
   The commission is one of the stages set up by a confusing
electoral law approved last December. Candidates for a new
2,250-member Congress of People's Deputies nominated by workers'
collectives must pass through the commissions before they are placed
on the ballot for the March 26 election.
   The commissions can place all the candidates on the ballot, or
limit it to any number. The House of Unions gathering met late into
the night to choose the slate for a seat in the congress that will
represent all of Moscow.
   It originally was to consider the candidacies of human rights
campaigner Andrei D. Sakharov and Politburo member Vitaly I.
Vorotnikov, but both pulled out. Sakharov demanded to be considered
as a candidate from the Academy of Sciences, and Vorotnikov opted to
run in Voronezh, a city south of Moscow.
   While one commission met in the House of Unions, another reviewed
a list of candidates for a Moscow district that included
controversial editor Vitaly Korotich of Ogonyok magazine.
   Yeltsin, who became first deputy chairman of the State
Construction Committee after falling out with Gorbachev, still has a
large following in Moscow.
   Dozens of his supporters held Yeltsin's portrait and banners at
police barricades around the building, and Yeltsin's seven-minute
address to the electoral commission was interrupted six times by
applause.
   But Yeltsin faced stiff competition from Yevgeny Brakov, director
of the giant ZIL automobile factory, and former cosmonaut Georgy
Grechko.
   Brakov presented a mainstream program supporting Gorbachev's
reforms and focusing on the need for better supplies of food and
consumer goods.
   He was nominated by 33 workers' groups compared to 19 for Yeltsin.
   Several Brakov supporters taunted Teltsin, saying they did not
want a candidate who was not a Moscow native.
   Yeltsin built his career in the Ural Mountains city of Sverdlovsk
before moving to the capital in 1985.
   Under the election law, candidates may be nominated in more than
one geographical area in the initial campaign stages. Yeltsin also
has been nominated in Sverdlovsk where he could stand a better
chance of being elected than in Moscow.
   Until he was removed as a candidate member of the party's ruling
Politburo in February 1988, Yeltsin was one of the staunchest
backers of Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or greater openness.
   But Gorbachev accused him of being overly ambitious and blaming
others for his mistakes.
   Yeltsin said in his speech that bureaucrats seeking to retain
their privileges comprised the biggest danger to reform. He urged
that the number of government ministries be cut.
   Yeltsin said the Soviet Union must create a system that will not
allow Stalinist abuses in the future.
   Hospitalized with heart trouble after being dismissed as Moscow
party chief, Yeltsin said he now was ``physically healthy and ready
to fight.''
</TEXT>
