<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Escape     02-21 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Escape,0234</SECOND>
<UNK>Newspaper: East German Border Guards Killed Man In Berlin Wall Escape
Attempt</UNK>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German border guards shot and
killed a 22-year-old man attempting to flee over the Berlin Wall, a
newspaper reported Tuesday.
   The mass-circulation Bild Zeitung tabloid said a companion was
severely wounded when troops fired more than a dozen shots at the
pair as they attempted to overcome barriers that divide the city on
the night of Feb. 6.
   A West Berlin police spokesman speaking on condition of anonymity
said witnesses reported hearing about 10 shots fired near the wall
that night.
   Police said the witnesses observed border guards carrying a man
to a car and forcing another man to accompany them.
   The police spokesman said officials could not confirm the
witnesses' report.
   Bild said communist East German officials denied the reports and
contended only a flare was shot into the air, the newspaper said.
   The newspaper did not give sources for its report, to appear in
its Wednesday editions. A copy of the report was telexed to other
news media in advance Tuesday night.
   At least 77 people have been killed trying to escape over
communist-built barriers blocking off West Berlin, according to
Working Group August 13. The human rights organization took its name
from the day East Germany began building the wall Aug. 13, 1961.
</TEXT>
