<FIRST>r a AM-Indelicato     02-21 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indelicato,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Dukakis Adviser Sentenced to Serve At Least 1 More Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former education adviser to Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis was sentenced Tuesday to a seven- to 10-year state prison
term on an array of corruption charges, or three years on top of his
current federal prison term.
   Allowing for early release, the judge who sentenced Gerard T.
Indelicato said he anticipated the former Bridgewater State College
president would spend 2{ years behind bars on the federal and state
charges, then serve a lengthy probation.
   Indelicato administered an adult education program designed to
help immigrants and the illiterate. He was considered the mastermind
of a plan that involved paying inflated classroom rent and receiving
some of the money back, taking the salaries of fictitious employees
and skimming funds intended to pay for classroom renovations.
   Led into court in handcuffs, Indelicato pleaded guilty to eight
counts of forgery, larceny, conflict of interest, filing a false
income tax return and lying to the state. Under a plea bargain
arrangement, Indelicato was spared a trial and 33 other counts were
placed on file. Under Massachusetts law, the state reserves the
right to prosecute those charges at a later date.
   On the two forgery counts, Superior Court Judge Robert W. Banks
imposed a sentence of 7 to 10 years in the maximum-security prison
in Walpole, with three years to be served, after Indelicato finishes
the federal term. Under state law, Indelicato would be eligible for
parole after one year.
   On the other six counts he pleaded guilty to, Indelicato received
concurrent sentences that would have totaled 18 to 25{ years if
imposed consecutively.
   The 42-year-old Norwood resident is serving his federal prison
term in Pennsylvania.
   Indelicato's attorney, Steven Brooks, called the sentence
``severe'' for a public official who ``made a few mistakes,'' but he
did not say whether he would appeal.
   As a special assistant to the governor, Indelicato is the
highest-ranking Dukakis administration official to face criminal
charges. Dukakis has publicly condemned Indelicato's actions and
said his administration cooperated in the state and federal
investigations.
   Last July, Indelicato was sentenced to 2{ years in prison after
pleading guilty in U.S. District Court in Boston to five charges of
conspiracy, mail fraud and tax evasion in a scheme involving his
brother and two other men to skim more than $80,000 from the adult
education program funded by the federal government and run by the
state.
   His case centered on activities that began between 1979 and early
1983. He was Dukakis' education adviser from February 1983 to
September 1986.
</TEXT>
