<FIRST>r w AM-US-Paraguay     02-21 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Paraguay,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Paraguan Leader Vows To Fight Drug Trafficking, Congressman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new leader of Paraguay has promised to help
fight drug trafficking and cooperate in hunting Nazi war criminals
who may be hiding in the South American nation, the first
congressman to visit Paraguay since the coup said Tuesday.
   Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn., said Gen. Andres Rodriguez told
him during an hour-long meeting last week that Rodriguez ``wants to
change the reputation of Paraguay as a refuge for thieves and
scoundrels to a very different, more positive place.''
   ``In our conversation, the provisional president was very
specific. He even assured me that he is willing to receive requests
from those who hunt war criminals, because he wants to end
Paraguay's historic reputation as a haven for ex-Nazis, drug dealers
and Third World dictators,'' Morrison said.
   The congressman said Rodriguez also promised to help fight drug
trafficking. Paraguay is known as a key money-laundering center for
cocaine profits and there have been reports that Rodriguez received
some of the profits.
   But Morrison, who later in the day briefed State Department
officials on his visit, cautioned that the Bush administration
should ``base its policies toward Paraguay on future actions,'' not
promises.
   ``I'm not in any position to make a judgement about what's inside
his head. I think we have to judge him by the actions he takes,''
Morrison said. ``There have been steps, and they're not
insigificant.''
   Rodriguez, 65, ousted President Alfredo Stroessner in a coup Feb.
3. Stroessner came to power in a 1954 coup and used torture to
repress political opposition in his early years of power. Later, he
eased up on the most blatant human rights violations, relying on
harassment, detentions and explusions.
   Rodriguez already has vowed to respect human rights and pledged
to respect freedom of the press. ABC Color, a prominent
investigative newspaper shut down for nearly five years, has been
allowed to reopen.
   But many are skeptical about how far reform will go under
Rodriguez, who until recently was an ally of Stroessner and who does
not consider the former president a dictator.
   This week, Rodriguez said elections will be held May 1 despite a
request by the opposition to delay them. Opposition party leaders,
who had little chance under Stroessner's election rules, wanted more
time to organize. They are considering an election boycott.
   Morrison said the quick election in the wake of the coup ``is
clearly favoring the (majority) Colorado Party (of Rodriguez) over
the opposition. ... But there are many people who would say that
even a signficant delay of several months wouldn't be likely to
allow the opposition to overcome the problem of years and years of
being out of power.
</TEXT>
