<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     02-21 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Detain Students Marching Toward Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police blocked about 80 students marching
to Parliament on Tuesday with a petition calling for free elections.
An opposition activist said at least 15 people were detained.
   Four more people were detained in Krakow at a demonstration in
support of Czechoslovak playwright Vaclav Havel, who was sentenced
in Prague on Tuesday to nine months in prison on charges stemming
from a Jan. 16 protest there.
   Two banned political groups, the leftist Polish Socialist Party
and the rightist Confederation for an Independent Poland, organized
the Warsaw demonstration.
   It began with a rally at Warsaw University of about 200 young
people, who signed the petition calling for free elections and
legalization of their groups. Then 80 to 100 of them began walking
toward the Sejm, or parliament, about one mile away.
   Police blocked the students after they walked a short distance to
a major intersection and wrestled some of them into police vans.
   Leszek Moczulski, leader of the Confederation, said at least 15
people were detained and three were still held by evening.
   Moczulski said police beat one Confederation activist, Slawomir
Gasior, as he was being detained.
   The Confederation also organized a rally in Krakow's market
square, where about 1,000 people gathered to hear speeches
supporting Havel, said Robert Bogdanski, a spokesman for the
Solidarity Information Service.
   He said police quickly blocked a march toward former offices of
the security services and detained three students.
   Bogdanski said a fourth person was detained when other protesters
were dispersed while marching toward the police chief's apartment.
</TEXT>
