<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-21 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Sweep Across Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms rumbled across the southern Atlantic states
Tuesday, bringing strong winds and at least two tornadoes to the
Carolinas.
   Warm and humid air rushing northward ahead of a cold front set up
favorable conditions for severe weather. Severe thunderstorm and
tornado watches were in effect for several hours along the middle
and southern Atlantic coast.
   Tornadoes touched down in Fayetteville, N.C., near the Cape Fear
Valley Medical Center, but no injuries were reported. A tornado also
touched down near Benson, also in eastern North Carolina.
   Elsewhere around the state, strong winds ripped through Anson,
damaged a school in Morven, knocked down trees and power lines at
Cordova and in Johnston County, and damaged mobile homes and
outbuildings in Lee and Moore counties and near Greenville and
Williamston.
   Wind gusts were clocked at near 70 mph Tuesday morning at
Charleston, S.C. Wind gusts of 81 mph occurred at Rocky Mount, N.C.
Strong winds lifted a mobile home off the foundation near Barnwell,
S.C.
   A severe thunderstorm watch was posted for parts of eastern
Virginia, eastern and southern Maryland, southern New Jersey and
much of Delaware.
   Heavy rain was reported during the morning in southern Georgia
into the Florida Panhandle. Nearly 4{ inches of rain was reported
Tuesday morning at Mary Esther, Fla., and 3{ inches at Macon, Ga.
   Rain was widespread from the Ohio Valley into New England. More
than 1} inches fell during a 24-hour period at Huntington, W.Va.,
and up to 3 inches in Kentucky. Numerous streams and creeks were
flooded in southeast Kentucky.
   Snow showers were widely scattered from the northern Plains into
the Great Lakes. Widely scattered showers occurred along the Pacific
coast and snow was scattered over the Cascades of southern Oregon
into the Shasta Siskiyou Mountains in Northern California.
   High temperatures included 75 degrees at Cape Hatteras, N.C.,
which broke a record for the date of 71 established in 1891, and a
record 86 degrees in Miami.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 10
degrees at Alexandria, Minn., to 88 degrees at Melbourne, Fla. The
nation's low was 5 below zero at Grand Forks, N.D.
   In the forecast for Wednesday was rain widespread along the
Eastern Seaboard, showers and thunderstorms from the Carolinas into
Florida, and rain widespread across the Northwest. Snow showers were
expected to be scattered from the eastern Great Lakes region into
the Ohio Valley, and most numerous from central West Virginia
through western Pennsylvania into northern Vermont.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 40s or 50s across much of
the nation, except single digits and teens from the northern Plains
through the upper Mississippi Valley into the upper Great Lakes, 20s
and 30s from the northern High Plains through the middle and lower
Missouri Valley, the middle Mississippi and Ohio valleys into the
eastern Great Lakes. Highs should reach the 60s from central
California through the southern Great Basin of Nevada and western
Utah into the Rio Grande Valley of Texas and across northern
Florida, and into the 70s from Southern California into the southern
Plateau, and across central Florida. Highs were expected to be in
the low to mid 80s across the Arizona deserts and across southern
Florida.
</TEXT>
