<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     02-21 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maoist Rebels Kill 7, Wound 3; Shops Close After Guerrilla Strike
Call</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist Shining Path guerrillas on Tuesday
killed one soldier and wounded three, police said, in the outskirts
of this Andean city where the prime minister urged residents to
ignore a guerrilla strike call.
   Police said the guerrillas buried explosives on a road in
northern Ayacucho and exploded the charge as the soldiers passed in
a troop truck.
   Elsewhere, rebels Monday fatally stabbed four women and two men
in Huichinga, a hamlet 50 miles northwest of Ayacucho, in
retaliation for selling cattle to the government, police said.
   ``We cannot permit the threat of violence to paralyze a city,''
said Prime Minister Armando Villanueva. He promised police
protection from the guerrillas, who threatened reprisal for those
not following their weeklong strike announced Monday.
   An Associated Press reporter on the scene said most business were
closed early Tuesday but began reopening during Villanueva's visit.
   A similar strike called in November by the Shining Path, whose
stronghold is the Ayacucho region, paralyzed Ayacucho for a week.
   More than 12,000 people have been killed in the Shining Path
guerrilla group's 9-year-old insurgency, which has increasingly been
oriented toward disrupting Peru's fragile economy.
