<FIRST>r i AM-Amnesty-Bulgaria     02-21 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amnesty-Bulgaria,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Group Calls On Bulgaria to Improve Human Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International appealed to the Bulgarian
government Tuesday for information about ethnic Turks imprisoned
mainly for peacefully opposing a forced assimilation campaign.
   The London-based human rights group said some members of
Bulgaria's Turkish minority have been jailed on terrorism or
espionage charges for protesting a name-changing policy which took
effect four years ago, and some have been tortured.
   Many were among hundreds arrested in 1984 and early 1985 for
resisting or protesting the assimilation campaign, which restricted
language and religion and forced Turks to give up their Islamic
names.
   ``The Bulgarian authorities have charged many with criminal
charges like `terrorism' or `hooliganism' but Amnesty International
believes that the real reason for their imprisonment may be their
non-violent opposition to the assimilation campaign,'' the report
said.
   In addition, an increase in independent human rights activities
in the past year has been followed by a crackdown on activists,
Amnesty warned in a report.
   Amnesty International said Bulgaria ratified in 1970 the
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, which
guarantees free expression, association and movement.
   ``Amnesty International is calling on the government to end
violations of these basic rights,'' it said in the report.
   The group seeks information on more than 150 prisoners, mostly
from the 900,000-strong ethnic Turkish minority which makes up about
10 percent of the population, said the report.
   Since 1984, the Bulgarian government has denied that a Turkish
minority exists in the country. It also says there are no human
rights abuses.
   Ahmed Hasanov Aptullov, a 29-year-old philosophy lecturer from
Sofia University, and three others were arrested after producing
leaflets in 1986 rallying Turks to oppose the assimilation, Amnesty
International said.
   They were imprisoned for eight to 10 years each. Amnesty
International considers them prisoners of conscience, the human
rights group's term for people who use non-violent means to express
themselves.
   The report described in detail the cases of 11 prisoners of
conscience, and said Amnesty International seeks information on
another 144 prisoners.
   The group said another prisoner of conscience, Ismail Mehmedov
Hyuseinov, was arrested in 1985 for refusing to accept his new name
and applying to emigrate to Turkey.
   He was badly beaten in prison but released to internal exile
after losing 88 pounds on a hunger strike. The government said he
was freed in 1987, but Amnesty International said it has been told
he remains in exile in northwest Bulgaria.
   Other prisoners have been tortured by prolonged beating on the
soles of the feet, the report said.
   Amnesty International said it has long been concerned about
prisoners of conscience in Bulgaria, and welcomed the recent
dialogue begun with the Bulgarian government.
   It said Bulgarian authorities supplied information in 1987 after
repeated requests by Amnesty International. The group met with some
officials, including a newly formed Committee on Human Rights, in
1988.
   The report said concerns remain and reliable information has been
scarce because of censorship and contradictory official statements.
Name changes have made identification difficult.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0217 </DOCNO>
