<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     02-21 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Killed in Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded Tuesday inside a
restaurant in Colombo, killing four people, and a shopkeeper was
shot and killed as Sinhalese extremists protesting last week's
Parliament election tried to force a strike.
   Police and military officials said extremists set fire to 10
government-owned buses and hurled smoke bombs in and around the
capital.
   The government declared a security alert and appealed to
residents not to give in to the threats by the extremists, state-run
radio reported.
   Most shops owned by Sinhalese, the island's majority ethnic
group, stayed open, but many Tamil and Moslem shopkeepers heeded
warnings issued by the extremists and kept their establishments
shuttered.
   A bomb concealed in a bag exploded inside the restaurant at
Narahenpitiya, about four miles east of Colombo city center, killing
four people and injuring eight others.
   A Sinhalese cashier who did not heed the strike call and kept his
store open was shot and killed in Colombo.
   The deaths were blamed on the radical Sinhalese group, the
People's Liberation Front.
   Police and military officials said the front, which has been
waging a campaign of assassinations and intimidation against the
government, had distributed leaflets calling for the strike to
protest the Feb. 15 Parliament election.
   The front had vowed to disrupt the election, which gave President
Ranasinghe Premadasa's United National Party 125 of 225 seats. More
than 1,000 people were killed during the five-week campaign.
   Police blamed most of the slayings on the front and said others
were the work of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, a Tamil
separatist group that also had vowed to disrupt the election.
   More than 10,000 people have died in ethnic violence since the
Tamil insurrection started in 1983. Efforts by Premadasa's
predecessor, President Junius R. Jayewardene, to make peace with the
Tamils prompted a Sinhalese backlash spearheaded by the People's
Liberation Front.
   Premadasa and Jayewardene are Sinhalese, as are most top
government and military officials.
   Sinhalese make up 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Tamils account for 18 percent and Moslems 7 percent.
</TEXT>
