<HEAD>U.S. Airman Questioned in Shooting, Third Incident Near Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. airman was being questioned
Wednesday in connection with the air gun shooting of a South Korean
citizen near a U.S. air base, the third incident involving American
servicemen in the same area, U.S. officials said.
   U.S. officials at Kunsan, a provincial port city about 130 miles
southwest of Seoul, said Air Force Sgt. John D. Wilson was being
held for investigation in the case.
   Wilson is with the 8th Equipment Maintenance Squadron and is
stationed at Kunsan Air Force Base. No hometown was available.
   Newspapers in Seoul quoted Yun Chun-ho, 33, a farmer, as claiming
Wilson fired at him Monday when he shouted and gestured to prevent
the airman from aiming his gun at two women passers-by. Yun was
wounded slightly in the thigh, newspapers said.
   ``The latest incident came as anti-American sentiment is running
high,'' said Wednesday's Korea Herald.
   An investigation was still under way in the involvement of U.S.
servicemen in two apparently unrelated deaths of Korean citizens
last week. Those deaths brought violent anti-American protests and
the city was placed off limits to U.S. military personnel.
   U.S. officials said restrictions were lifted Tuesday, but a
midnight weekday curfew was imposed for the 3,500 military personnel
stationed at Kunsan Air Base.
   On Feb. 11, a mushroom grower, Chong Pan-yong, 54, died after an
altercation in a residential area of Kunsan. Police said Air Force
Tech. Sgt. Bruce A. Harayda, 29, of Bridgeport, Conn., was being
questioned.
   On Feb. 15, a military vehicle driven by Army Spec. Dale J. Green
of the 501st Signal Company struck and killed Song Yun-jae, 36, on a
city street. Green is stationed in Kunsan.
   Students staged rallies and clashed with riot police to demand
that South Korean police punish the U.S. soldiers for the two deaths
and the United States pay compensation to the Korean families.
