<FIRST>u p AM-Duke-GOP 3rdLd-Writethru a0768 02-21 0890</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Duke-GOP, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0768,0911</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Klan Leader Likely Member of GOP Legislative Caucus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Duke's opponent filing motion
challenging residency in district, Duke reax, tightens. No pick up.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly elected state Rep. David Duke's
opponent filed a court motion Tuesday seeking to block the former Ku
Klux Klan grand wizard from taking the legislative seat he won last
Saturday.
   The motion filed by homebuilder John Treen asks that Duke's
candidacy be declared illegal because he lives outside the New
Orleans district that elected him. State law requires a one-year
district residency by candidates.
   District Judge Clarence McManus said he was studying the request
and probably would decide the matter Wednesday morning.
   Duke said late Tuesday that he met the residency requirements
``in every respect. It's a frivolous challenge.'' Duke has said he
has proof he lived in the district, a nearly all-white bedroom
community of New Orleans.
   Earlier Tuesday, state GOP legislative leaders said Duke probably
would be accepted by Republicans as one of their own if he's seated
in the House when it convenes for a special session Wednesday. A
freshman independent had said he would raise the residency issue,
but Democrats and Republicans alike had said they didn't expect the
move to succeed.
   Both Duke and Treen ran as Republicans.
   Treen's motion, filed along with a district resident, asks that
Treen be declared the winner. According to the motion, Duke listed a
home address outside the district when he qualified as a Democratic
primary candidate for president on Jan. 15, 1988, and for state
primaries.
   The motion also asked for a temporary restraining order
forbidding the secretary of state from certifying Duke as the winner
until McManus decides whether Duke fulfilled the residency
requirements.
   However, the secretary of state's office certified the results
Tuesday after Jefferson Parish Registrar Sam Altobello officially
counted the votes from Saturday's race and found Duke's 227-vote
margin of victory intact.
   Duke gave the thumbs up and smiled broadly Tuesday at the
announcement.
   ``I'm just really proud to live in America,'' Duke said. ``I'm
also looking forward to an end to the hoopla.
   ``I'm anxious to meet with the legislators,'' he said. ``I have a
lot to learn.''
   If the Republican Legislative Caucus lets him in, Duke will be
one of 18 Republicans in the 105-member House. There are six
Republicans in the 39-member Senate.
   Also Tuesday, Republican National Chairman Lee Atwater softened
his aggressive campaign to drive Duke from the party, saying he
feared such a public forum might be exactly what the man wanted.
   Republican legislators Tuesday said they saw no reason to reject
Duke from the caucus despite Atwater's repudiation of him as a
``charlatan.'' The Legislature convenes in special session Wednesday
to take up tax issues.
   Rep. Odon Bacque of Lafayette said Monday he intended to
challenge Duke on grounds that he did not live in his district for
the required year.
   ``We will see if Mr. Duke is what he says he is or what the media
says he is,'' said Rep. Peppi Bruneau of New Orleans, GOP caucus
chairman. ``If he's what he says he is, he has no problem. He got to
the House the same way everybody else did.''
   There is at least one precedent for a state legislature refusing
to seat a member because of his views, said Dan O'Connor of Atlanta,
a spokesman for the Southern Legislative Conference of the Council
of State Governments.
   Julian Bond was barred from taking a seat in the Georgia
Legislature in January 1966 because of his opposition to the Vietnam
War. The U.S. Supreme Court in December 1966 said Bond had to be
seated since the only issue was his political views.
   Both President Bush and former President Reagan endorsed Treen in
the runoff election. After Duke won, Atwater vowed to have Duke
censured and barred from using the GOP name.
   A resolution is expected to be adopted by the party's 11-member
executive council, which will confer by telephone Friday.
   At a brief news conference Tuesday, Bush conceded his involvement
might have been viewed by Louisiana voters as ``improper or
overkill.''
   Duke, 38, registered as a Republican days before filing as a
candidate. He left the Klan in 1980 but remains the president of the
National Association for the Advancement of White People, which he
describes as a civil rights group for everyone.
   I'm certainly not the David Duke I was during my years in the
Klan but I'm certain I've grown like all people do, mentally,
spiritually,'' he said at a news conference Tuesday in Baton Rouge.
``I believe in the civil rights of all people. I think the criticism
I've endured will be muted by my activities in the House of
Representatives.''
   ``We can't be responsible for what he did before he was
registered as a Republican,'' said Rep. Art Sour, a Republican. ``I
don't understand what Atwater is talking about. Censure him for
what? The only control we have over him is what he's done since he's
been a Republican.''
   Democratic Rep. Ron Gomez, legislative party leader, said he
hoped Duke would be seated without problems.
   ``If anyone wanted to challenge Duke they should have done so
when he qualified as a candidate,'' he said.
</TEXT>
