<FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela-Riots     02-21 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Riots,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Employee Reported Killed in Student Riots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A university employee was killed in
battles between police and students protesting government austerity
measures and the purported police slaying of a student, newspapers
said Tuesday.
   More street violence Tuesday was reported by the El Nacional
newspaper.
   Student leaders from Central University in Caracas told reporters
they were protesting an economic reform package announced by the
government that eliminated subsidized prices on most goods.
   They also complained that an engineering student died at the
hands of local police and that a vagrancy law allowed police to
detain and jail people without trial for periods that could run into
years.
   The students said law authorities vowed to apply the vagrancy law
more forcefully to keep criminals off the streets.
   The student leaders told reporters that a university employee,
whom they identified as Carlos Yepez Perez, was killed in cross fire
by a bullet fired by police in battles with students Monday night.
   No reports emerged of other injuries and no confirmation or
denial of the employee's death came from police sources.
   Student leaders said they expected the riots to continue and that
they planned a joint march with students from across the country.
