<FIRST>u a AM-AirForceCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0693 02-21 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Force Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bulldozers, Bridge Building Equipment Used in Search for Crew</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with late information on search,
description of scene, officer doubting anyone will be found alive, deletes
outdated information. Picks up 11th graf, `Small fires...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XFTW1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HURLBURT FIELD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers used a helicopter,
bulldozers and bridge-building equipment in an unsuccessful search
Tuesday for the eight people aboard an Air Force cargo plane that
crashed and burned in a swamp.
   An officer who waded through 5-foot-deep water to reach the site
said no bodies were found and it was unlikely anyone could have
survived.
   ``From the looks of it, that's the conclusion any reasonable
person would draw,'' said Col. Howard Oakes, commander of Eglin Air
Force Base in the Florida Panhandle.
   The four-engine C-141B jet, based at Norton Air Force Base at San
Bernardino, Calif., crashed Monday night about four miles north of
Hurlburt Field while on its landing approach.
   Seven crew members from Norton were on board. Also, a retired
military passenger boarded during a refueling stop in Colorado
Springs, Colo., officials said.
   Air Force civil engineers planned to work through the night with
bulldozers and other heavy machinery to build a half-mile dirt road
through the swamp and bridge a creek so vehicles could reach the
crash site Wednesday.
   The site is within Eglin's 720-square-mile military reservation,
which is used for training maneuvers and weapons testing.
   ``The C-141 location along with heavy rains that have been
falling since the crash are hampering rescue and recovery efforts,''
said Technical Sgt. David Torrence, an Eglin spokesman.
   Rescuers arrived by climbing down a rope from a hovering
helicopter or by wading through water and underbrush, Torrence said.
   Oakes said the front part of the aircraft was severely damaged
and its left wing was completely sheared off. The rear two-thirds of
the plane was visible, but the nose was obscured by thick foliage,
he said.
   Army Rangers who have a camp on the reservation were conducting
manuevers in the area and were the first to arrive, about 30 minutes
after the crash, Oakes said.
   ``They saw the fireball,'' he said.
   Small fires burned hours after the crash. No munitions were
aboard, said Col. Dale Stovall, commander of the 1st Special
Operations Wing at Hurlburt.
   An Air Force safety team is investigating the accident. Stovall
said there were severe thunderstorms in the area at the time, but he
declined to say if weather figured in the crash.
   The $32 million C-141B is capable of carrying up to 200 soldiers
in combat gear. The huge aircraft has a wingspan of 160 feet and is
168 feet long. The only U.S. cargo plane larger than a C-141 is the
C-5A Galaxy.
</TEXT>
