<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Timeline ADV22   02-21 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Timeline, ADV 22,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, Feb. 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Timeline' Presents `News' from the Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What if television news had been around to report
on historic events, such as the Crusades?
   The producers of ``Timeline'' asked that question, and the
result, a six-part series on PBS, premieres tonight.
   The answer is _ it would look pretty dumb.
   The series premieres tonight with ``The Crusades, 1187.'' The
other episodes, airing in coming weeks, are ``The Black Death,
1361,'' ``The Vikings, 1066,'' ``The Fall of Byzantium, 1453,''
``The Mongol Empire, 1247'' and ``Granada, 1492.''
   If this is what it takes to make people swallow history lessons,
we're doomed. Anyone dim enough to need former network newsman Steve
Bell _ dressed in Medieval costume, no less _ to explain the Plague
in sound bites, will sit still only long enough to realize this is
not the Monty Python sketch it at first appears, then switch to
``Who's the Boss?''
   The only immediate use for the six-part series would seem to be
presenting it to caged junior high schoolers.
   First, there's the problem of making what is basically a
historical documentary look like a news report, so there are
confusing graphics on top of various scenes declaring the footage
``File'' or ``Live'' _ from the year 1187, or whatever, of course.
Correspondents in period costume _ with names such as Owen of
Canarfon or Siboletto of Zimbabwe _ also confuse the viewer since
they are intercut with ``interviews'' with participants in the
events. Then, if that weren't enough, we're presented with
explanations of past events that led up to the ``current''
situation, labeled ``91 years ago,'' for instance.
   The history lesson is perfectly serious _ even though it seems
John Cleese will appear at any moment _ but there are lame attempts
at humor. The programs are interrupted occasionally by period
``commercials,'' such as one hawking chimneys, a new concept.
   The dramatizations are impressive in their careful attention to
authentic detail in the costumes and sets _ if not in the rather
overly enthusiastic acting. The series was taped on locations in
Turkey, England and Spain.
   But the programs are extremely wordy. The basic problem with
``Timeline'' is that it ultimately is not like television news _
television news would never bombard viewers with so much information.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   HOW GOOD IS YOUR CHILDREN'S SHOW? _ You've got a new children's
program, but you don't know if it's good or not. What do you do?
Peggy Charren, president of Action for Children's Television, has
five questions producers and presenters of children's programming
should ask themselves:
   1. Does the program have something to say instead of just
something to sell?
   2. Would you submit it to an international animation or film
festival for an award?
   3. Would you put it at the top of a list for the lawyer who is
defending you against a station's challenge?
   4. Would parents tape it if their children were at the dentist?
   5. Would you mention it by name if your child's teacher asked you
what you do for a living?
   Charren presented the list at a recent National Academy of
Television Arts and Sciences dinner where she was awarded the
Trustees' Emmy Award for her watchdog efforts on behalf of youthful
viewers. ...
   ``BABAR'' ON HBO'' _ Home Box Office, which has gotten into the
children's programming business with good results so far, is giving
the beloved children's book character, Babar the elephant, his own
series. The series, based on the 28 stories written by painter Jean
de Brunhoff and his son, Laurent, will premiere April 2. ...
   THE FAMILY THAT WATCHES TOGETHER, ISN'T _ According to Nielsen
Media Research, families with pay cable and children _ not
necessarily in that order _ are more than twice as likely as other
households to watch more than one set at the same time. Prime time
was the most popular time for watching more than one set, presumably
with the kids in one room and the parents in the other. ...
   CNN IN THE U.S.S.R. _ CNN's international news compendium ``CNN
World Report'' made its debut on Soviet television as part of
``Mezdunardony Televestnik'' or ``International TV Herald'' last
month. The half-hour program, anchored by Soviet host Al Gurnov,
utilized CNN-provided reporting on the worldwide spread of AIDS.
Soviet television will continue airing its version of the program
monthly until May, when it becomes a bi-weekly series. ``CNN World
Report'' is comprised of reports from various broadcast news
organizations around the world, and many other nations make use of
the reports in their newscasts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Feb. 22</NOTE>
