<DOCNO> AP890221-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-GreenConsumers Adv01   02-21 0890</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Green Consumers, Adv 01,0919</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, March 1, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Green Consumer Movement Gains Momentum in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``green consumer'' movement is gaining momentum
in Western Europe, and environmentalism is becoming mainstream.
   Now many Europeans need only to go to the neighborhood
supermarket if they want organically grown vegetables, low-mercury
batteries, or what have become known as environment-friendly diapers
and cruelty-free cosmetics, those marketed without being tested on
laboratory animals.
   Consumers increasingly are demanding products that don't ``cost
the earth,'' and companies are seizing the new opportunity, experts
say.
   ``People realize that by exercising choice on the high street
(main street) they can change the way the environment is treated,''
said Virginia Bottomley, a British environment official.
   ``There's a growing acceptance that we can't go on using and
destroying the world's natural resources.''
   She was one of 11 speakers at a recent London conference of
officials from government, industry and environmental groups called
``Attracting the Green Consumer.''
   Robin Sadler, an advertising consultant, told the conference:
``Green issues are not just flavor of the month. This could become
the world's central project for the next century.''
   Here are just some of the steps governments have taken:
   _The 12-nation European Economic Community and 23 other countries
have committed themselves to cutting back the use of CFCs, or
chlorofluorocarbons, by 50 percent by the end of the century. CFCs,
used as propellants, are thought to deplete the earth's protective
ozone shield.
   _Italy plans a 100-lire (8-cent) tax on consumers for each
non-biodegradable plastic bag they take from the store.
   _The Netherlands is offering tax breaks to people who buy cars
that meet strict anti-pollution standards.
   _West Germany for years has put ``Blue Angel'' labels on products
that meet its environmental standards. The Scandinavian countries,
the Netherlands, France, Japan and Canada are following suit.
   Queen Elizabeth II has switched her fleet of cars to lead-free
gasoline, and her son Prtince Charles has banned aerosol sprays from
his home.
   Green consumerism offers many opportunities to companies, but
confronts them with a complex market, the experts said.
   ``The highest levels of concern are shown by the more affluent
groups of society,'' said Dorothy MacKenzie, a marketing expert. But
``there are lots of different green consumers. They are motivated by
different concerns and have widely different patterns.''
   They range from 1960s-style hippies and current-day ``guppies''
(green yuppies) to mothers concerned about their children's future,
she said.
   The green opportunities mean companies can make money directly,
by selling green products, as well as indirectly, by enhancing their
reputation.
   ``Our reputation clearly helps our business,'' said John Hume,
director of Johnson Wax Ltd., the British subsidiary of the
similarly named U.S. household products maker. His company removed
CFCs from its aerosols in 1986, a costly exercise, and labels
products environment-friendly.
   Disposable diapers are one of the latest products to go green and
earn the reputation of being environment-friendly. Procter and
Gamble, joining other companies, is selling chlorine-free diapers in
six countries. The chlorine-processed diapers contain tiny residues
of the highly poisonous chemical dioxin.
   Safeway PLC, no relation to the U.S. supermarket chain, has
removed contentious or detrimental ingredients from its own
products, such as artificial color in its own-brand orange soda.
   It also recycles its cardboard and offers its customers free,
recycled paper bags. It has built a CFC-free refrigeration center in
Scotland.
   The British confectioner Cadbury Ltd. is among companies that
have opted for a link with a worthy cause. In 1985 it began donating
a percentage of sales of a chocolate Wildlife Bar to the World
Wildlife Fund to help endangered animals. The animals are depicted
on the bars' labels.
   Research has found that consumers are willing to pay more for
environment-friendly products.
   Marek Mayer, an expert on environmental issues, said some West
German retailers are believed to charge more for products that carry
the ``Blue Angel'' label, even though some of these products are
cheaper to make.
   Julia Hailes, co-author of ``The Green Consumer Guide,'' said
green products initially will cost more, but their prices will
decline as they are mass-produced.
   Despite green consumerism's growing momentum, both consumers and
companies remain reluctant to embrace it wholeheartedly, the experts
said.
   Organic produce still represents less than 5 percent of Safeway's
total produce sales, said Tony Combes, a director. The government's
Mrs. Bottomley lamented that only 2 percent of the auto fuel
consumed in Britain is unleaded.
   ``People will not do what they say they do for the environment
unless its very easy,'' Sadler said. ``Personal benefit may still be
the key to adopting green issues. The idea of doing something for
the common good is still not a motivation for people yet,
unfortunately.''
   The experts said the threat of consumer criticism is very real.
   ``There's a very great danger that we could have an inconsistency
here of polluting the environment while producing green products,''
Hume said. For instance, he added, lead-free gas might reduce air
pollution, but its manufacture produces at least one highly toxic
byproduct.
   Walter Guthrie, a manager at Boots MicroCheck Group, a chemicals
maker, said: ``Some manufacturers have made preservative-free claims
when the product didn't need to be preserved in the first place.
These attempts to mislead the consumer should be actively
discouraged.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, March 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--PhoneFun Adv05-3Takes   02-21 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Phone Fun, Adv 05-3 Takes,0850</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 graphic.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Time was the telephone came in one basic shape
and, like Henry Ford's Model T, in one basic color, black. It had
simple functions. It tied neighborhood and family together with
voices, the whispered devotions of lovers, the reassurance of
distant parents, the first words of a grandchild, a reminder that a
bill was due, an order for groceries. But look what's happening to
it now.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By JOHN BARBOUR</NOTE>
<NOTE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beware the telephone. TV ads may tease and
promise adventure at the fingertips. But it's call now, pay later,
when the monthly bill shows where late night loneliness and the
pursuit of romance dug into the wallet.
   That once-friendly instrument, masquerading in the colors of the
rainbow and shapes that range from computer clever to Space Age
gothic, is at your service with services you never dreamed you'd
want.
   Everything from pay-as-you-talk to Santa to pay-as-you-dream
about sex.
   A firm in Seattle brought down the wrath of parents with a
half-hour Christmas show featuring Santa Claus. Children were told
to hold their telephones toward the screen, whereupon tone-activated
signals dialed up that jolly old elf so the kids could chat with
him, while the computer logged and charged for the calls.
   Things have changed in the telephone world, not so much because
the changes are needed, but because they are possible. And
profitable.
   Today's telephone junky can have intimate chats with all kinds of
strangers.
   Now a whole new series of 1-900 numbers are opening up. On some
you are a quiz show guest, answering with your push-button phone to
maybe win a prize. But you pay for the call, perhaps $2 for openers
and more if you stay on the line.
   A simple call on one adult sex line in New York City can run $20
or more, whether you talk or not.
   The telephone has spawned a new business that some say is
eclipsing $400 million a year and growing. An evening of letting
your fingers do the walking can ring up a $200 phone bill in a
couple of hours.
   The same comforting device that gave you grandma's warm and
comforting voice now gives you everything from strange sex to sexy
strangers, from gays in search of companionship to high school kids
on a high.
   It offers up the stock market, the latest interest rates, advice
on mortgages. Its recorded voices tell you what meetings there are
in your community, where to shop for an auto loan, when to get up,
how to pray, what your biorhythms are, when your stars are
favorable, when they are not, how to get a date whatever your sexual
or racial choice, who is going to win the Super Bowl and what the
point spread is, where to get free money for college.
   Dial and get the latest jokes, the top horse racing picks,
lottery results, a daily diet, skiing bargains, sports scores,
government job openings, insults, wine choices, movie reviews, soap
opera reviews, music trivia, sports trivia, trivial trivia.
   That's not all.
   On the gab lines you can chat with strangers, search for a date,
leave your number for promised human adventure, dispel in seven
push-button digits that most universal of all human conditions,
loneliness. And if one is too shy, dial the adult lines (in New York
there are more than 200 of them) and become an aural voyeur to kinky
sex, erotic fantasy. From their lips to your ear, and only the
telephone billing computer will know.
   It is 5:30 a.m. in New York City and CBS has sandwiched in
between its late-night rerun and morning business shows a commercial
or two showing a black-dressed villain and a pretty blonde a la
Perils of Pauline urging viewers to call a certain 970 number and
rescue this damsel from certain boredom.
   When the number is reached (after several tries) a woman's voice
says the call will cost $5 unless you hang up now. Then you are
assigned your personal code number and given another telephone
number to call. After several tries again, you enter your code, then
push another number as instructed and finally reach a young,
breathless voice named Linda. She is apparently ready to field your
favorite fantasy, although she volunteers nothing.
   You find that she is a 22-year-old college graduate (political
science) from a New York state university, is thinking about joining
the Peace Corps, and is saving money to go to Europe to visit a
friend.
   You hesitate to ask, ``What's a nice girl like you doing in this
racket,'' and inquire instead, ``Are you well-paid for this?''
   She answers no. Then someone steps in and terminates the call.
Either time was up or the questions were going too far.
</TEXT>
