<FIRST>s i BC-APN--SpaChic Adv05   02-21 1117</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Spa Chic, Adv 05,1146</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 4 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 3 35mm slides.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ For centuries they were the playgrounds of the
rich, but in recent years the lavish health spas of West Germany
have depended mainly on the aging and infirm who could take the
waters at government expense. Now the pendulum is swinging again and
guess who gave it a big push. Health-conscious yuppies, known among
Germans as ``Schickimickis,'' have discovered the spa scene.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associatred Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BADEN BADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's most-famous
health spas, like this 19th century playground for the rich, royal
and renowned, are enjoying a renaissance among an emerging class of
European yuppies.
   ``Take a look _ and get looked at,'' is one of the advertising
slogans luring a hedonistic crowd into the spa social scene that for
the past 30 years has been dominated by the weak and aging.
   In a period of federal belt-tightening, the resorts that in the
postwar years have focused on government-sponsored health care are
now turning back to the healthy and wealthy who bestowed their
original fame.
   A modest trimming of social security benefits that took effect
with the new year promises to cut into the ranks of 8.4 million
``cure guests'' who take the waters each year in West Germany.
   But administrators of the most distinguished baths say they had
long been expecting fiscal conservatism to catch up with the cushy
health care system.
   Some, like Baden Baden, Bad Aachen and Wiesbaden, have begun
catering to a new generation of guests, a younger crowd of
well-heeled professionals known among Germans as ``Schickimickis.''
   Sequined and tuxedoed, the elite envoys of the 30-to-40 set
saunter and gamble in the path of Feodor Dostoevski and Kaiser
Wilhelm in Baden Baden's glittering casino. Dwindling in number are
the elderly and ailing bingo players in an adjacent parlor of the
Kurhaus.
   A sprawling seven-pool, glass-enclosed ``bathing temple''
completed three years ago draws 1,500 guests a day, increasingly
from among younger couples and singles who come here for long
weekends to play tennis, relax and flaunt their newfound prosperity.
   Hans Berg, manager of the German Bathing Association office in
Bonn, says the spas are attracting a broader group of guests and
becoming less dependent on the publicly insured clientele.
   Under the 1956 legislation that set up today's elaborate social
security net, West Germans are entitled to a spa treatment as often
as every three years if their doctors recommend it.
   Until this year, the federally funded health insurance network
paid the full cost of a three- or four-week bathing cure for those
recuperating from illness or taking a respite from the stresses of
work or family life.
   Cure clients must now pay 10 percent of the cost of their
treatments, which run an average of $2,750 for four weeks, plus most
of their hotel and food expenses.
   ``We don't know exactly what effect the changes in the law will
have on the industry, and we hope this isn't too strong a blow,''
Berg says. ``But we have been enjoying a steady growth over the past
year or two of younger visitors, and by younger I mean those in
their 30s who want to go away for a few days for a small vacation
rather than a cure.''
   Josef Bartholemy, Baden Baden's spa association general manager,
contends the cutbacks are shortsighted.
   ``Some of those who would benefit from rest and recuperation will
put off taking a cure because of the expense, then end up in the
hospital which will cost more for a few days than a preventative
cure,'' he says.
   But spa administrators expect that a trend among younger Germans
to take better care of their health promises to more than compensate
for an expected drop in visits by guests on social security.
   ``The changes in our clientele have had a positive economic
effect,'' says Sigrun Lang, chairwoman of Baden Baden's spa
association. ``While the guest here for a publicly funded cure is
often on a restricted budget during his four-week stay, those
staying for a three-day convention or a long weekend tend to spend a
lot in the shops and the casino.''
   A slender, 40-ish executive, Mrs. Lang says the more successful
spas are cashing in on the younger generation's growing absorption
with health and appearance.
   Despite a nationwide unemployment rate of 8.5 percent, a new
affluence is visible among the younger, college-educated crowd in
major cities like Hamburg and Munich. And like their baby boom
contemporaries in the United States, West Germans in their 30s and
early 40s are gradually moving into the upper echelons of government
and industry.
   Foreign guests continue to account for more than a quarter of the
spa patronage, with wealthy Americans, Arabs, Japanese and Europeans
replacing the Russian nobility of the last century.
   Fewer turn to the mystic healing effects of water to cure serious
illnesses these days, but the younger generations frequenting the
spas are bringing along new health challenges for the resorts to
tackle.
   The opulent art deco complex at Bad Nauheim, for example, now
offers a program to break the smoking habit.
   Bad Mergentheim, nestled in a scenic valley of vineyards along
the famous Romantic Road, attracts a new clientele with its
weight-reduction course.
   Bad Aachen, at the three-nation crossroads with Belgium and
Holland where Charlemagne took the waters 1,200 years ago, now
offers stress-management clinics.
   Managers of smaller spas and the hotels and restaurants supported
by cure guests are nervous about the effects of the streamlining.
They point out that only a few dozen of the 264 officially
recognized health spas in West Germany are esteemed enough to get by
on the clientele that pays its own way.
   ``There is no other industry here except the spas,'' says Elke
Requeer, treatment director at the city cure house in Bad
Muenstereifel, a scenic hamlet in the foothills of the Eifel near
the border with Belgium. ``We don't get a lot of younger visitors
here because most of our patients are elderly and the atmosphere
must remain quiet.''
   School director Anita Meinhardt of Fulda, taking a cure at Baden
Baden this winter at her own expense, said the federal cutbacks are
unlikely to deter those strongly in need of rest and may encourage
more personal responsibility about one's health.
   Referring to her countrymen's propensity to drink and smoke more
than other Europeans, she contended that, ``One shouldn't expect the
government to provide an all-expense-paid cure for a lifetime of bad
living habits.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 5</NOTE>
