<FIRST>s a BC-APN--SnowshoePriest Adv05-2Takes   02-21 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Snowshoe Priest, Adv 05-2 Takes,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ He trudged the frozen wilderness around the Great
Lakes in the middle of the 19th century, spreading the Christian
religion among the Indians. While establishing his missions, Bishop
Frederick Baraga also put the spoken tongues of the Ottawa and
Ojibwa Indians into written words. Some say he performed miracles
and for years have been urging the Roman Catholic Church to have him
canonized as a saint.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>L'ANSE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scholars count the miracles and Pat and Myra
Ellico count the winters as Michigan's ``Snowshoe Priest'' travels a
long path toward possible sainthood.
   To many around here, Bishop Frederick Baraga, a Roman Catholic
missionary who spent a lifetime converting Indians to Christianity
in the 19th century, is a saint already. They believe canonization
of Baraga is inevitable.
   ``There isn't much doubt in our minds. We believe he is a
saint,'' says the Rev. Guy Thoren at the Sacred Heart Church in
L'Anse, where Baraga built his last mission.
   Thoren's mother was part of the first move to canonize Baraga
that began 37 years ago. Since then, the church has approved
Baraga's writings and has verified his sanctity. Now it must accept
the miracles.
   ``Either it will be very soon, or it will be an extremely long
process,'' says Regis Walling, who for five years has gathered
Baraga material and sent it to Rome. ``I have no doubt that it will
happen.''
   While Walling works for the Catholic diocese, Pat and Myra Ellico
keep the faith at the Baraga Shrine in L'Anse.
   The elderly couple sells trinkets to the tourists who stop at the
shrine to see a 35-foot brass and copper statue of the traveling
priest. When they can, they sit strangers down over hot tea and
cookies and tell them of their candidate for sainthood.
   Baraga was born in 1797, the son of wealthy landowners in
French-occupied Slovenia, now a part of Yugoslavia. The young priest
left a fractured church in his homeland in 1830 to establish
missions among the Ojibwa and Ottawa Indians in the Northwest
Territory.
   He spent 23 years among Indians and settlers on Lakes Michigan
and Superior, traveling hundreds of miles by canoe, snowshoe and
even ice floe, spreading the Gospel and putting the Ottawa and
Ojibwa tongue into written words.
   Baraga used the Indians as guides. He also relied on them as
rescuers, for sometimes he was found to be wandering in circles in
the winter wilderness.
   His feats are legendary to the people of the northern woods,
where a county, town and state park are named after him.
   The Yugoslavian people also remain keenly aware of their native
son. They send representatives to Marquette each year for ceremonies
remembering him.
   But Baraga sometimes encountered hostility among the Native
Americans he worked with. Their reaction, then and now, has been
mixed.
   ``There are those who realize the Chippewa (Ojibwa) would have
moved West or simply disappeared if it hadn't been for him,''
Walling says. ``He helped save them by giving them a written
language.
   ``Then, there are some who feel all white men, missionaries
included, led to the destruction of the Indian nation. Actually, I
think the real cause was alcohol.''
   ``I guess there is mixed feeling,'' says the Rev. John Hascall, a
Catholic priest who is also an Ojibwa pipe carrier (religious man)
and president of the National Takakwitha Council based in Montana.
   Missionaries came close to robbing the Ojibwa and other Indians
of their native beliefs in God, or Kije Manito, the Great Spirit,
Hascall says.
   ``Baraga did not understand that,'' he adds. ``He thought he was
converting pagans.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--SnowshoePriest Adv05-1stAdd   02-21 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Snowshoe Priest, Adv 05-1st Add,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>L'ANSE, Mich.: converting pagans.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I'm not demeaning Father Baraga. Anybody bringing Christ would
enrich us. His every effort was to build us up, which he really did
accidentally by preserving our language. He was a man who was
sincere, which made him in the Indian way a holy man.''
   Donald LaPointe, a 58-year-old Ojibwa, grew up with the Baraga
legend, handed down from his father and grandfather.
   ``They held him in reverence,'' he says. ``One of my earliest
memories was seeing a picture of him.''
   Baraga built homes and schools for the Ojibwa and purchased 500
acres of land for the tribe, LaPointe says. Just recently the
Keweenaw Bay Tribe obtained the deed for the land from the Marquette
diocese.
   Today, Baraga's outpost at L'Anse is surrounded by an Ojibwa
reservation where children read their history in the language Baraga
penned.
   Summers at the shrine are crowded with tourists, but winter
leaves the Ellicos alone with a friendly Doberman pinscher named
Hans and the silent Baraga statue, shrouded in snow.
   Schoolchildren come out now and then to burn candles by the
shrine. A state plaque nearby marks an ancient Indian trail that
heads south to Wisconsin. At least one missionary is believed to
have died on the frozen path.
   This is the time of year the Ellicos, who have tended the shrine
for 14 years, notice the increasing cold and dream of retiring and
moving south.
   Pat and his brother once envisioned a tourist motel and
restaurant on the bluff overlooking Keweenaw Bay, but his brother
died and the Bishop Baraga Foundation asked if he would donate land
for the shrine. Pat Ellico agreed.
   Artist Jack Anderson's robed priest stands high on a giant
metallic cloud, atop copper arches that end in five tepees, one for
each of the Indian missions Baraga founded.
   To Walling, Baraga's own life was the greatest show of divine
intervention.
   ``That he survived under the conditions he lived _ that was more
a miracle than anything else,'' she says. ``He traveled from L'Anse
to Duluth, Minn., on snowshoes. His eyes froze shut and he survived
with no harm.''
   Walling has given Rome other evidence, though. From there, a
Franciscan priest, Father Bruno Korosak, sends them on to the Sacred
Congregation of Saints.
   ``There are over 110 very strong cases of miracles or
intercessions,'' Walling says.
   One involved Baraga County Clerk Bernard Lambert, who led the
effort in the early 1970s to build the Baraga shrine, Thoren says.
Lambert, who was crippled with arthritis at 28, died last year.
   ``He was totally invalid and then he walked,'' Thoren says. ``I
believe the statue was done in 1971 in thanksgiving.''
   The Catholic community has not waited for Rome to begin sending
prayers to Baraga. The faithful carefully pass among themselves
relics of his existence: thread from his woolen socks and splinters
of wood from his burial casket.
   A Hubbell woman's cancer completely vanished after she prayed to
Baraga with thread from his socks in her hands, Walling says.
   ``My mother had a thread,'' Thoren says. ``When my brother became
a sky diver, she gave it to him. Then he gave it to a friend who was
dying of cancer.''
   The cancer victim died, but the thread was preserved, a precious
token.
   If the miracles are accepted, Baraga's writings must be presented
in a document that explains the context of his work, a process
Walling says is two-thirds complete. Then the real journey begins,
as the Vatican considers Baraga first for veneration, beatification
and finally canonization.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 5</NOTE>
