<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1511EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   02-21 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Poltergeist III'' (MGM-UA Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95. PG-13)
   
   ``Poltergeist III'' should have had all the flaws of its
predecessors _ cubed _ in the negative exponential fashion of
Hollywood sequels. It doesn't. It's excellent. (Sadly, it was the
last film for child star Heather O'Rourke, who died during surgery
after the movie's theatrical release.)
   In this episode, the spirit world's demonic preacher Kane (Nathan
Davis) is again determined to get Carol Anne (Heather O'Rourke) to
guide him ``into the light'' on the Other Side again. No problem;
you wouldn't have it any other way.
   Tangina (Zelda Rubinstein), the chubby little medium from ``I''
and ``II'' returns to help Carol Anne, along with the doughty Tom
Skerritt and Nancy Allen, who play Carol Anne's devoted uncle and
aunt.
   Skerritt is the manager of a sleek, mirrored high-rise building,
the all-too familiar ``complex of shops, offices and apartments.''
So ... what if ... the evil spirit moves into the building? Why,
it's ... an Eighties nightmare!!! The building becomes a stunning,
surreal maze of endless-seeming stairwells, filled with mirrored
walls with spectral images, with crazy elevators that go crazy and
demonic cars in a frozen parking garage.
   Note that all the special effects were shot on-camera. Some of
them are ingenious and utterly simple _ and awfully scary.
   Director Gary Sherman couldn't get all the originals' stars and
couldn't afford the costly opticals and other lab effects, so he and
co-writer Brian Taggert went after something different and succeeded
brilliantly. Aces.
   _ By Scott Williams, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``A Fish Called Wanda'' (CBS-Fox Video. VHS-Beta, $89.98. Rated R)
   
   One of the biggest box-office surprises of the season was ``A
Fish Called Wanda,'' a juicy jewel heist romp starring John Clease
(who also wrote the screenplay) and Michael Palin of ``Monty
Python'' fame, Kevin Kline and Jamie Lee Curtis.
   ``Wanda'' is the type of comedy we long to see but only get once
every decade. It's wacky, sophisticated, obvious, raunchy,
irreverent, delicious and a laugh a minute.
   George (Tom Georgeson), Otto (Kline), Wanda (Curtis) and Ken
(Palin) pull a diamond heist and immediately set to double-triple
cross each other. Wanda and Otto set up George and get him arrested
for the crime. But before the cops take him off in cuffs, he hides
the key to the safety deposit box in which the gems are hidden in
Ken's fish food. Ken finds the key and hides it in the treasure box
in his beloved fish tank where his prize fish is an angel also named
Wanda. Stay tuned for a tragic scene later in the movie featuring
little Wanda.
   The only witness who can place George near the scene of the crime
is a little old lady who owns three tiny dogs. Ken decides to kill
her so she won't be able to testify. He misses three times. Go
figure. But the bit, as cruel and crazy as it is, is also one of the
funniest running gags on film.
   Cleese is George's defense counsel, Archie Leech. (Another gag
for film buffs.) Wanda decides to seduce Archie in order to learn
where George has hidden the loot. Only problem, she falls in love
with him.
   Otto, her true love, a maniacal former CIA operative who will
just about kill anyone who calls him ``stupid,'' keeps close watch
on Wanda and Archie _ like in putting stethoscopes to windows while
they attempt to make love inside.
   Kline is brilliant as Otto, who fancies himself an intellectual
because he reads Nietzsche. (But, as Wanda tells him, calling him
stupid is an insult to stupid people.) He prances, storms, postures
and leaps in and out of the type of character Cleese made
institutional as Basil Fawlty in ``Fawlty Towers.''
   Palin, as the animal-loving stutterer Ken, is a delight. Cleese
plays it pretty straight this time, but gets big laughs for his
Russian striptease and for the scene in which his wife comes home
just a little too early while Wanda is there.
   Curtis, however, is the weak link in an otherwise sprightly
flick. She has no timing for comedy. She's fortunate, though, in
having a superb cast to keep her afloat.
   Don't rent ``A Fish Called Wanda.'' Buy it. This is a video to
see again, and again and again.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
