<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Honky Tonk Angel'' (MCA) _ Patty Loveless
   
   Patty Loveless' crystal clear voice lends a subtle, rather than
overpowering, quality to her music. So ``Honky Tonk Angel,'' her
third album, doesn't score an immediate knockout.
   But it's an enjoyable, if not spectacular, record that sounds
better with repeated listening.
   Loveless works in the same musical territory as such hip country
traditionalists as Emmylou Harris, Rodney Crowell and Rosanne Cash.
She's at her best, however, with the pop-leaning ballads ``If You
Think'' and ``I'm on Your Side.''
   Also worth hearing is her rendition of the great ``Don't Toss Us
Away.'' Her version, with backround vocals by Crowell, is more
understated than the Lone Justice original but no less powerful as
Loveless makes a plea for keeping a romance alive even as all around
``it seems like everyone we've known, their love's grown cold.''
   Loveless' band, featuring fiddler Mark O'Connor and the always
impressive Albert Lee on guitar, is solid throughout on an album
that _ sort of like a good concert opening act _ gives the sense of
hearing an artist who may have something great in her future.
   
   _ By Marc Rice, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Symphonies No. 24, 26, 27 and 30 by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart;
Prague Chamber Orchestra, conducted by Sir Charles Mackerras (Telarc)
   
   For listeners not enchanted with performances on original
instruments but who want fresh-sounding, more authentic versions of
pre-20th century works, there is a middle course. Sir Charles
Mackerras and the Prague Chamber Orchestra take it in this Telarc
recording of four middle symphonies by the 17-year-old Mozart.
   The orchestra is scaled back, a harpsichord added and the style
of playing is that of original instrument recordings, though the
instruments are modern. The strings make more biting attacks and
lean into the beginning of notes, and the flutes and oboes leave out
vibrato. The sound is brisk and lean and full of life, and the
musicians play with a controlled exuberance.
   There is a little too much echo to the sound, a result probably
of the recording site, the Castle of Dobris in Prague. Mackerras
sometimes lets things move along a little too briskly, though there
are loving moments, especially in the masterful slow movement of No.
27, perhaps the best part of the disc. The main theme is a
descending string passage capped by plucked notes in the cello,
which become their own counter theme in the next section.
   As William Malloch's fine linear notes point out, these
symphonies are numbered out of chronological order: Nos. 26 and 27
were written before Mozart's July-September 1773 visit to Vienna,
and Nos. 24 and 30 after. Oddly, No. 24 sounds the earliest, with
its simple descending three-chord main theme in the first movement.
No. 26 sounds the most operatic, and was indeed used as an overture
to a play. No. 30 is full of humor, a light-hearted romp in the
opening Molto Allegro movement, followed by a stately Andantino,
Menuetto and Haydenesque surprise ending in the final Presto.
   The Vienna trip was Mozart's third to the European music capital.
As a 7-year-old prodigy, he jumped into the lap of Empress Maria
Theresa and gave her a kiss for her praise. The next time, he got a
gold watch. In 1773, he got another audience _ but not the court
appointment he had hoped for. The empress in a letter compared the
ever-touring genius to a travelling beggar.
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
