<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Will the Real Joe Clark Please Stand Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It could have been an actor's nightmare:
starring in a movie while the man you're portraying is always there,
peeping over your shoulder. But for Morgan Freeman, the results were
great.
   Freeman, who received an Academy Award nomination last year for
his supporting role as the terrifying pimp in ``Street Smart,'' is
the star of Warner Bros.' ``Lean on Me.'' He plays the role of Joe
Clark, the New Jersey principal who turned a drug-ridden wasteland
into a model high school with the symbolic weapons of a baseball bat
and a bullhorn.
   Not only is Joe Clark alive and functioning at Eastside High in
Paterson. He was also present while ``Lean on Me'' was being shot at
Eastside.
   ``Joe was there before we started,'' says Freeman. ``Since we
filmed in the school and school was in session, he was there every
day, doing his job.
   ``You want to know if that was daunting? Yes. Incredibly daunting
the first week and a half or two. I didn't know how I was going to
do it.''
   How much of the performance is Morgan Freeman and how much is Joe
Clark?
   ``All of the performance is Morgan Freeman,'' he replied. ``What
Morgan Freeman could bring in the way of Joe Clark was largely due
to Joe Clark. He was very available to me, extremely helpful, very
supportive. He made it easy, despite my own sense of inadequacy.''
   But Freeman still had to create a character, not merely imitate
Joe Clark.
   ``That's what I lost sight of,'' he admitted. `` I went into this
watching him and thinking, `I got to be Joe Clark,' rather than,
`I've got to give a performance.' I had to straighten myself out on
that. It was like trying to make a Studebaker look like a Buick.''
   Freeman was pleased to report that Clark has seen the film and
has given his seal of approval. ``That's the seal that counts,''
said Freeman. ``I really wanted him to like the movie. I like him a
lot.''
   Not everyone agrees. Clark was tagged ``Crazy Joe'' because of
some of his tactics, including the chaining of school exit doors to
keep out drug dealers. Or his initial act of expelling 300
under-achieving and trouble-making pupils. Freeman, however,
dismisses Clark's critics.
   ``He is universally beloved by his students, and that's all that
counts. People who disagree with him are meaningless. They're off in
some kind of ivory tower; I don't think they even know what he did.''
   Some might argue that Clark has been operating a fascist state.
   ``So what?'' answers Freeman. ``What do you think a school is?
It's not a democracy. You can't teach democracy if you can't catch
the attention of the students. No school I ever went to was (a
democracy).''
   His schools were in Chicago's South Side, an area not unlike
Paterson. Morgan had been born in Greenwood, Miss., but his family
moved north when he was young. He remembers school as being much
more orderly than what Joe Clark faces.
   ``The streets were what I had to negotiate; the schools were not
a problem,'' he remarked. ``Once you got through the doors of
school, you were safe. There the teachers had control.
   ``What (`Lean on Me') represents is what happened to schools,
particularly in the inner cities, in the '60s and '70s. The schools
were taken over by the students, and the teachers were shortchanged.
Their caseloads and classrooms were entirely too large. Their
ability to discipline miscreants was undermined by Supreme Court
rulings about corporal punishment in schools. And their salaries
were so low that they became second-class citizens.''
   Freeman first fell in love with acting in the third grade, when
he portrayed Little Boy Blue in a class pageant. In the seventh
grade he won the Illinois state prize as best actor in a drama
contest. But his real ambition was to become a ``hotshot pilot with
a scarf around my neck and strafe the enemy's flag.''
   In the Air Force he became a radar technician instead. After his
discharge he realized what he really wanted to do was act, and he
enrolled at Los Angeles City College to learn the basics. His first
professional job was dancing at the 1964 New York World's Fair, then
he joined a touring company of ``The Royal Hunt of the Sun.''
   Freeman managed to earn a living in plays such as ``Hello,
Dolly'' (with Pearl Bailey and Cab Calloway) and ``Purlie'' and in
TV shows such as PBS's ``The Electric Company.'' Then in 1980 the
jobs inexplicably stopped. He still doesn't know why, except maybe
he was too outspoken in rejecting material he deemed substandard.
   The drought lasted two years, and he credits Paul Newman with
helping him get work again, casting him in a film. The big
breakthrough came with ``Street Smart.''
   ``I always wanted to play a pimp,'' he admitted, ``and this guy
was real.'' Critics thought so. Pauline Kael even theorized in The
New Yorker: ``Is Morgan Freeman the greatest American Actor?''
   ``Street Smart,'' which starred Christopher Reeve, was released
early in 1987 to so-so business. Freeman's achievement might have
faded from view except that Los Angeles Times critic Sheila Benson
suggested to Cannon Films publicist Lynn Kwit that his performance
deserved an Oscar campaign.
   His reaction to the Academy nomination?
   ``I felt fine. It was like having a pat on the back and `Well
done.' You sort of kick the dirt and say, `Aw gee, thanks'
(laughing) and try to hold onto your sense of self and not go off
flying half-cocked. It's just a pat on the back.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 3-5</NOTE>
