<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Joy Adv03-05   02-21 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Joy, Adv 03-05,0883</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, March 3-5 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: ``Streets of Bakersfield'' Helps Career</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELK, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homer Joy recently got a call from a woman who
had once scolded him for his noisy guitar playing and singing.
   Joy, 43, said the former neighbor recalled the confident young
musician's reply 35 years ago that she wouldn't yell at him after
she heard his songs on the radio.
   The apologetic call came after his song, ``Streets of
Bakersfield,'' was nominated for a Grammy as country song of the
year and Joy was nominated as songwriter of the year.
   Now, Joy hopes the song that also helped Buck Owens and Dwight
Yoakam receive a Grammy nomination for country duo of the year will
also help him find a record company to distribute a gospel album.
   It was 16 years ago that Joy wrote and recorded ``The Streets of
Bakersfield,'' about the frustration he felt while recording a
``sound-alike'' album of Hank Williams Sr. songs at Owens'
Bakersfield, Calif., studio.
   ``It just wasn't what I wanted to do,'' Joy said during a recent
interview. But because he was under contract with Buck Owens
Enterprises, he finished the project, then insisted that producer
Bob Morrison listen to him play a song he'd written.
   ``I really got kind of redneck about it,'' Joy said, but the end
result was that Owens heard the song and loved it, and had Joy
record it.
   ``The Streets of Bakersfield'' was a Top 10 hit in 1973 for Joy,
a native of Heber Springs, Ark.
   Joy had another hit single with ``John Law'' in 1974, and Owens,
Freddie Hart and other big-name country singers were recording his
songs. He performed on the same bill with Nashville stars such as
Roy Clark, Mel Tillis and Tanya Tucker.
   The version of ``The Streets of Bakersfield'' recorded last year
by Owens and Yoakam hit the top of the country charts. But in the
years between his version and the latest version of the song, Joy
hit rock bottom.
   Joy said he and Owens mutually agreed to end his contract in 1976
because of ``artistic differences.'' After that, he proved unable to
cope with the pressures, traveling and temptations of being a rising
star. After Joy and his wife of 15 years, Lois, divorced in 1978,
his life changed.
   ``I sold 4.5 million records, and then I had everything I owned
in a cardboard box in 1983,'' Joy said. ``It was a real disaster.''
   But the down-and-out wanderer, who as a boy would sneak out of
Saturday movie matinees to sing with Salvation Army bands on
streetcorners in Spokane, Wash., said he got a dose of salvation
that helped him recover and gave him a new outlook on his music.
   ``I accepted the Lord six years ago,'' Joy said. He and Lois
remarried in June 1983, and the following year a daughter, Bethany,
was born.
   The Joys have seven children. Along with his wife, sons Morgan
and Preston accompany their father on the album of gospel songs he's
recording at a studio in Spokane.
   ``My wife and I said a prayer a year ago, and it couldn't have
been more than three weeks later that Dwight and Buck did (the song)
on the Country Music Awards anniversary show,'' he said.
   Their record was released last July and hit No. 1 on Oct. 15, but
Joy said that was just a start.
   ``I believed `Streets of Bakersfield' was No. 1 with a bullet,
that it being No. 1 was just really the beginning of things,'' he
said. ``And it's turned out to be true.
   ``It's been good for everybody this song has touched, and we're
really thankful. Our prayer was that we could have a way to finance
our gospel album.''
   For that project, Joy picked the 10 best songs he's written since
he became a Christian six years ago. They are songs he's sung in
performances at missions, penitentiaries and Christian services at
rodeos.
   ``I haven't ever written a song that isn't based on truth,'' he
said, including his old songs about getting drunk or stoned,
womanizing and ``all those other kind of things. But I don't believe
(in those things) now.
   ``There was a time when I did, and I lived like that. So now we
try to live what we write now.''
   Joy still enjoys playing ``secular'' music, and he says his
gospel songs aren't an attempt to ``stuff the Bible down people's
throats.
   ``We just try to do what we believe in and hope it will touch
people, like `The Streets of Bakersfield' touched a whole lot of
people.''
   He's well aware that the success of a song revived after 16 years
doesn't guarantee a good response for a new gospel album.
   ``This thing, with `Streets of Bakersfield,' will get it listened
to,'' Joy said. ``But I'm not ignorant, and I know that the album
has to stand on its own, aside from anything else. And I believe it
will.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 3-5</NOTE>
