<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday Feb. 23, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Budworm Infestation Slowing In Pacific Northwest Forests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAKER, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adverse weather, Forest Service
``search-and-destroy'' missions and its own insatiable appetite have
slowed the advance of the Western spruce budworm that has spread
across millions of acres this decade.
   ``The outbreaks are clearly on the decline,'' said James Hadfield
of the U.S. Forest Service. The infestation has been ``the worst one
that we have ever experienced, in terms of the extent of area
defoliated and damage caused.''
   The tiny brown caterpillar was first spotted in 1980 on 5,000
acres near Cove, Ore. It has spread through Oregon and Washington,
primarily east of the Cascades, feeding on needles of fir and spruce
and destroying vast numbers of ``understory'' firs growing in the
shadow of mature trees.
   ``The effects will continue to be felt as long as 70 years out
because of the effect on the growth of trees,'' Hadfield said.
   Adverse weather at critical developmental stages and Forest
Service eradication efforts using chemical and biological pesticides
have helped reduce the infestation. In addition, trees in areas
where the budworm has been present for several years are so damaged
that they can't sustain the insect.
   Budworms defoliated 2.8 million acres last year, down from 4.2
million in 1987 and from a peak 6 million in 1986. ``We ar still
predicting a very extensive area of defoliation in 1989, even though
the intensity of the defoliation, by and large, will be pretty
light,'' Hadfield said.
   The Forest Service plans to test a new biological pesticide,
Bacillus thuringiensis, which homes in on budworms, on two plots of
1,000 and 10,000 acres in Wallowa-Whitman National Forest in
northeastern Oregon.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Medical Imaging Techniques Used to Identify Mummies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took modern radiological techniques to
take the wraps off two mummies at the Albany Institute of History
and Art, demonstrating that the bodies were of a man and a woman _
and that the woman had a fake toe.
   The toe, possibly made of a ceramic material, may have been the
woman's ticket to the afterlife, said curator Tammis Groft.
Egyptians believed people had to be physically intact to enter the
hereafter and attempts were often made to restore missing body parts
during mummification, Groft said.
   Albany Medical Center radiologists used standard X-rays and
computed tomography scans _ which provide a computer-enhanced
cross-section image of a body _ to study the mummies, one of which
was only partially wrapped.
   That mummy was a man, as museum experts had suspected since
acquiring the mummies in 1909. It may have been a priest known as
Ankhefenmut who was buried in the temple of Mut at Karnak in Thebes,
Groft said.
   ``We were pretty sure the partially unwrapped mummy was a male,''
he said. ``The X-rays confirmed it, showing a male pelvis and
genitalia. But the wrapped mummy remained a mystery, until we saw
the X-rays.''
   The radiology tests showed that both are from the 21st Egyptian
dynasty, circa 1085 to 945 B.C. Both probably died of natural
causes, experts theorize, since the tests didn't reveal any trauma
to their bodies. It's estimated that the man died in his 50s or 60s
and that the woman was about a decade younger.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Researchers Hope Long-Ignored Plant Will Be Rediscovered As Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wild legume that has been eaten in
eastern North America for nearly 5,000 years needs less fertilizer
than potatoes and yields three times the crude protein, says a
researcher who sees it as a food crop.
   The ``groundnut'' or ``rosary,'' Apios americana, is a small
climbing vine that produces clusters of edible pea-like seed pods
and tubers. It grows along sandy creek banks, through bushes and
over fallen trees.
   ``Historically, the plant is important because ... very few crops
native to North America have been domesticated,'' said
horticulturalist William Blackmon of Louisiana State University's
Agricultural Experiment Station.
   A legume, like peas, peanuts and soybeans, the groundnut produces
nitrogen and so needs less fertilizer than some food plants,
Blackmon said. The plant can survive frost and other conditions
unsuitable for many other crops.
   The tubers taste like a cross between an Irish potato and a
peanut when boiled, and can be used in casseroles, corn bread and
stir-fry cooking. Work is just beginning on recipes and other uses
for the groundnuts, which are edible but harder to produce and might
be processed into flour.
   Blackmon has been joined by researchers at the University of
Minnesota and North Carolina State University. He began sending
seeds to home gardeners in the United States and 16 other countries
in 1986, with mixed results.
   ``These were wild seeds and some of the wild seeds were just not
productive,'' he said. ``A lot of times you'll have a gardener
who'll be real clever and will come up with something that's
productive.''
   Blackmon is trying to develop a plant with a more compact vine
and with tubers closer to the stem to facilitate mechanical
harvesting.
   ``I think that in some places it might be very beneficial to the
world food supply,'' he said. ``The thing will stay stored in the
ground, (so) you don't have to store it. You can pull it when you
need it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Feb. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
