<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0807</SECOND>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Eastern Corp., fighting a hostile takeover
attempt by Coastal Corp., has agreed to be acquired by Panhandle
Eastern Corp. after Panhandle outbid Coastal with a $3.2 billion
cash offer.
   The agreement, subject to approval by federal regulators, was
accepted Monday by the Texas Eastern board just hours after the
$53-a-share offer was approved by Panhandle Eastern's board of
directors, a Panhandle Eastern spokesman said.
   A Coastal Corp. spokesman said his company would study the
Panhandle Eastern offer before deciding whether to continue its $2.6
billion bid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minorco SA renewed its hostile bid for Consolidated
Gold Fields PLC and sweetened the proposed buyout to $5.7 billion,
the largest offer ever for a British company.
   Consolidated Gold Fields, a British gold mining group,
immediately rejected the long-awaited, renewed offer from Minorco,
the investment arm of the South African Oppenheimer family's mining
empire.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New figures show OPEC members are
complying with a new production accord designed to lift crude oil
prices, a top official of the organization said.
   Subroto, secretary-general of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, said Monday crude prices would definitely reach
the cartel's target of $18 a barrel in the second half of this year.
   According to figures released by OPEC, 12 of the countries
supplied a total of 17.42 million barrels a day in January, slightly
less than the quota of 17.51 million barrels set for them.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit narrowed to $137.34
billion in 1988, the government announced in a report economists
said showed how far America must go before its trade problems are
solved.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that exports, led by a surge
in manufactured goods, shot up a dramatic 26.8 percent last year to
an all-time high of $322.22 billion. This increase supplied much of
the economy's momentum in 1988 as factories hired more workers and
expanded production facilities to meet the export demand.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers of the European
Economic Community welcomed steps toward resolving a trade dispute
with the United States over an EEC ban on imports of beef treated
with growth-boosting hormones.
   EEC and U.S. negotiators agreed over the weekend to form a task
force to study the dispute over the next 75 days and try to find
ways to end it.
   The foreign ministers said in a statement Monday the creation of
a special panel was a step in the right direction to prevent a
full-fledged trade war.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators placed another 25 insolvent
savings and loan institutions in 14 states under government control
as part of President Bush's plan for resolving the S&amp;L crisis.
   The action, taken Friday by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.,
brings the total number of S&amp;Ls put under federal conservatorship
over the last two weeks at 36.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising auto loan defaults have bitten into profits
at Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp., partly as a consequence
of the longer terms the big automakers have been offering on new car
credit.
   The trend has some lenders taking a closer look at credit
requirements before approving car loans to consumers, who have
become increasingly burdened with debt in recent years, and
encouraging buyers to cut their loan requirements.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. said it has combined the Kraft
and General Foods food lines into a new division in the aftermath of
its $12.9 billion acquisition of Kraft Inc. in December.
   Kraft General Foods Group combines Kraft and the operating
companies of General Foods Corp., a big Philip Morris subsidiary,
into one organization, Philip Morris Chairman Hamish Maxwell said
Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. said it will ask the
U.S. Supreme Court to review a lower court ruling supporting prior
decisions in a patent infringement case with Polaroid Corp. by a
judge who owned Kodak stock.
   The move disclosed Friday is not expected to affect the scheduled
April 17 start of a trial to determine how much of a $5.7 billion
request Kodak must pay for violating Polaroid patents on instant
cameras and film.
</TEXT>
