<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0735EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OPEC     02-21 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OPEC,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subroto Says Non-OPEC Nations Likely to Cut Production</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subroto as one name is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent oil-exporting nations are
likely to agree to cut their crude production to give another boost
to prices, a top OPEC official predicted.
   ``It is in their interest to reduce the supply so that we can
reach 18 (dollars a barrel),'' Subroto, secretary-general of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, said Monday.
   The 13 nations that comprise OPEC agreed in November to slash
production as of Jan. 1 in an effort to raise prices to their target
of $18 a barrel.
   The agreement sparked a rally that has lifted the average price
of a basket of crudes monitored by OPEC to about $16 a barrel, up as
much as $5 from late November.
   OPEC officials want nations outside the cartel to join them in
trimming output to spur another price pickup.
   Representatives of a group of independent countries were meeting
Tuesday in London to discuss cuts. They met last month with OPEC
representatives.
   ``There is definitely a positive sign that, not only for our
interest but for their own interest, they will do something in
reducing the supply,'' Subroto, a former Indonesian oil minister,
said in an interview.
   ``The more they cut from their production, of course, the sooner
we can see it in dollars a barrel,'' he said.
   He declined to speculate on the level of cuts the non-OPEC
nations might put in place. But he said it was likely they would
make an offer to OPEC, possibly next month.
   One participant at the non-OPEC meeting said in London Monday he
was ``fairly optimistic about this meeting because we're all very
friendly.''
   Subroto predicted crude prices would definitely reach $18 in the
second half of 1989.
   New OPEC figures, he said, show member nations complied in
January with the new output accord. The agreedment set an overall
ceiling, or quota, of 18.5 million barrels a day for the 13 nations
in the first six months of this year.
   According to OPEC figures, 12 countries supplied a total of 17.42
million barrels a day in January, just under the quota of 17.51
million barrels.
   The cartel said figures from the United Arab Emirates had not yet
been received. That nation, however, has persistently overshot its
target in the past, according to private analysts. Its current quota
is 988,000 barrels a day.
   Subroto said the supply figures were ``a sign that we are abiding
(by) our quota.''
   Private analysts estimated OPEC exceeded its ceiling in January
by about a million barrels a day.
   OPEC said, however, it measures the quota by figuring crude
production and the amount of oil put into, or taken out of, stock.
Production, which it defines as the amount of crude measured at
storage facilities, was 18.13 million barrels a day in January for
the 12 reporting countries.
   It was the first time the cartel released monthly production
figures.
   Non-OPEC nations sending representatives to Tuesday's meeting
were Oman, Mexico, Egypt, Malaysia, China, Angola and Colombia. The
Soviet Union, Norway, the Yemen Arab Republic, the Canadian province
of Alberta and the American state of Alaska were expected to send
observers.
   OPEC members are Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates
and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0735EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TexasInsuranceWoes     02-21 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Insurance Woes,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texans Facing Latest Financial Crisis: Insurance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just as Texans are hearing reports of an economic
revival and new plans for reviving savings and loans, they're faced
with yet another industry crisis: insolvencies in dozens of the
state's insurance companies and the collapse of one of its largest.
   The $54 million failure of National County Mutual Fire Insurance
Co., which had an estimated 100,000 policyholders, triggered a state
inquiry into the State Board of Insurance and the industry itself.
   With 42 Texas-based insurance companies and 98 that do business
in the state being liquidated, fears are growing that Texas insurers
are following the same road as S&amp;Ls.
   ``The potential is there,'' said State Rep. Eddie Cavazos,
D-Corpus Christi, House Insurance Committee chairman of budget and
oversight. ``I don't think we have gotten to the bottom of the pit
(of insolvent insurance companies) and the closer we get to the
bottom, the more horror stories I hear.''
   A state auditor's report issued last week estimated the
liabilities of insurance companies in receivership exceeded their
assets by an estimated $200 million to $300 million as of Aug. 31.
   State officials say the factors that bedevil the insurance
industry are the same as those that endangered the thrifts: lax and
inept regulators, depressed real estate and oil markets and
freespending company officials.
   In 1987, Texans paid an estimated $26 billion for insurance
premiums, the audit said.
   The audit urged the insurance board to make identifying
financially troubled insurance companies its highest priority.
   Regulators came under sharp criticism for their handling of
National County, whose president, Robert H. Walker, is believed to
be in Switzerland.
   The insurance board staff knew about National County's problems
as early as 1986 but did not move to place the Dallas-based casualty
and property insurer in receivership until Oct. 24, 1988.
   A legislative report showed it took an average of more than one
year from the time examiners knew a company was in deep financial
trouble and the time it was placed into conservatorship.
   In December, when Insurance Commissioner Doyce Lee resigned under
pressure, he described the agency as under siege, trying to keep up
with the insurance industry after years of being understaffed and
underfunded while the sour economy brought on record insolvencies.
   During 1987 the agency was reorganized and its staff expanded
from about 850 employees to 1,300. Board members said the
reorganization contributed to the problems.
   But state Sen. John Montford, D-Lubbock, blamed ``inept''
management.
   ``They're running at a pace that would have worked in the
1930s,'' he said.
   Montford, who chairs the state Senate Affairs Committee that
conducted hearings on National County's failure, has sponsored 11
bills aimed at restructuring the insurance board. Also being drafted
is a measure that would set up an oversight panel.
   Regulatory and criminal investigations are under way to determine
what led to National County's insolvency, the costliest in Texas
history. The company's primary business was automobile insurance for
high-risk drivers.
   Insurance board liquidator James T. Odiorne has filed a lawsuit
against Walker and his sons, alleging that Walker ``and perhaps
others'' diverted premium money to affiliated companies.
   Also named in the suit are Texas National Insurance Co., Southern
Life Investment Co., Bent Tree National Bank, Western Fire &amp;
Casualty Insurance Co. Ltd., Walker National General Agency Inc. and
Superior Premium Finance Inc.
   As in the savings and loans crisis, consumers could end up
footing part of the bill to pay claims, which are expected to total
$40 million.
   Initially, claims will be paid through the Texas Property and
Casualty Guaranty Fund, supported by healthy insurance companies but
subsidized indirectly by the state.
   Tax credits the state gives to insurance companies that
contribute to the guaranty fund translate into lost state treasury
revenue, leaving taxpayers to make up the deficit.
   The new insurance commissioner, A.W. ``Woody'' Pogue, said he
expects more failures, but none of the magnitude of National County.
   ``We've made a lot of changes on the board,'' he said. ``I'm very
optimistic that we've turned it around.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0736EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-InsuranceTycoon     02-21 0886</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insurance Tycoon,0917</SECOND>
<HEAD>Absent Tycoon At Center Of Texas Insurance Collapse</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Texas Insurance Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert H. Walker may have swiped more than $20
million from the insurance company he led before it became one of
Texas' largest industry failures.
   Or he may be the most prominent insurance industry figure to fall
victim to the havoc wreaked on the Texas economy by the oil and gas
industry collapse.
   Or both.
   State and federal investigators trying to understand the failure
of Walker's company, National County Mutual Fire Insurance Co., may
have to wait for his explanations _ first they have to find him.
   The tycoon, they say, has ignored subpoenas and may have fled the
country.
   The 58-year-old Walker rose and fell in grand Texas style: buying
rounds for patrons of his giant honky-tonk, sailing a
multimillion-dollar yacht and flying several private planes before
being caught in the economic pinch.
   By the time National County was taken over by the State Board of
Insurance in October 1988, the property-casualty insurer was more
than $50 million in the red. The size of the failure prompted a
crisis of confidence in the state's insurance regulators, who have
been accused by some lawmakers of failing to act quickly to help the
company's estimated 100,000 customers.
   ``Mr. Walker is allegedly an example of what can happen when you
have this lethargic attitude by a regulatory agency,'' said state
Sen. John Montford.
   Montford serves on the Senate State Affairs Committee, which has
subpoenaed Walker to appear at a hearing.
   Insurance Board attorney Susan Martin said that based on reliable
sources, she believes Walker is in Switzerland.
   Walker is accused of concealing fraud and funneling premiums from
National County to Walker General Agency, his Dallas-based holding
company that owned the insurance operation, according to a lawsuit
filed by National County's state-appointed receiver, James Odiorne.
   The state has seized some of Walker's property, including two
sterling silver decorative saddles valued at $100,000 apiece.
   Walker owned a home in Dallas and a ranch in the Texas Hill
Country. His fortune was spread among more than 60 small companies
and real estate properties.
   Until he transferred his control last year, Walker was part owner
of the Million Dollar Cowboy Bar, a Jackson, Wyo., honky-tonk with
saddles for barstools, silver dollars embedded in the bar and an
11,000-square-foot dance floor. He and two others bought the saloon
in 1979.
   Walker became well-known in the small tourist town during his
visits several times a year. Stopping at the Million Dollar, he
often would buy a round for the house and occasionally fly friends
to Las Vegas.
   ``Mostly he just partied,'' said David Hauser, who managed the
Million Dollar for eight years. ``He was a nice guy. We seemed to
get along real fine.''
   Walker could not be reached by The Associated Press. Calls to
family members were unanswered. Calls to National County were
referred to the liquidation office of the State Board of Insurance.
   But Walker has said he tried to save the company at the expense
of his luxurious lifestyle.
   ``I never kept money from the company,'' he told the Dallas
Business Journal last fall, adding that he expected to be accused of
taking about $28 million from National County. He said he offered to
contribute $3 million to the company to help recapitalize it, but
the state turned him down.
   Walker told the Journal National County was crippled by the loss
of a reinsurance contract with Dallas-based Republic Insurance Group.
   Republic began providing reinsurance in 1984 for National County
under a seven-year contract that anticipated $15 million worth of
business transferred to the reinsurer each year.
   In 1985 National County transferred about $120 million in
premiums to Republic _ eight times the anticipated amount _ and
Republic suspended the contract, a spokesman for the reinsurer said.
   Republic's decision was upheld in court-ordered arbitration,
which Walker said rendered National County unable to maintain its
insurance portfolio, primarily automobile coverage to high-risk
drivers.
   Republic, which had honored previous reinsurance contracts with
National County, refused to enter another.
   Walker began cutting back. National County took in more than $200
million in premiums at its peak, but was down to $50 million by the
time state regulators took over last fall.
   As the insurance company's troubles grew, so did those in
Walker's other enterprises, particularly real estate investments for
which he'd guaranteed payments before the energy collapse devastated
the Texas economy.
   ``I would think that he did what almost every businessman in
Dallas on a big roll did when the tap went dry,'' said Nicholas
Ricco, owner of Diversified Insurance Systems, Inc. of Dallas.
``He'd just go to other taps that are available.''
   Ricco said he and Walker talked only a handful of times in the
past five years, but they've known each other for 25 years.
   ``This lack of integrity I've heard about goes against the
grain,'' Ricco said. ``I saw him honor agreements with everyone for
years, including me, even to the detriment of himself.''
   The U.S. Postal Inspector's office in Dallas is leading a
criminal investigation of National County's failure to determine if
fraud was involved, inspector Jesse Horton said.
   Walker is also embroiled in several lawsuits stemming from unpaid
real estate loans and other soured investments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0742EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GoldFields-Minorco     02-21 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gold Fields-Minorco,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consolidated Gold Fields to Fight Sweetened Minorco Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Gold Fields PLC has rejected as
inadequate a sweetened $5.7 billion hostile takeover offer by
Minorco SA.
   ``The board intends to resist the bid strongly,'' said
Consolidated Gold Fields Chairman Rudolph Agnew, who advised
shareholders Monday to take no action in response to the offer, the
largest bid ever for a British company.
   ``This renewed bid, which is of questionable value, bears no
relation to the underlying worth of the company and is clearly not
meant to be taken seriously by shareholders,'' Agnew said.
   Under British takeover rules, Minorco, the investment arm of the
South African Oppenheimer family's mining empire, needed to renew
its bid by Thursday or risk having to wait till next fall to bid
again. By announcing its offer now, Minorco gets nearly three months
to proceed with its takeover attempt.
   The renewed bid follows approval Friday by the European Community
Commission, which conducted an informal inquiry into whether the
proposed acquisition of the gold mining group would result in a
monopoly of platinum markets.
   It also follows clearance by Britain's Monopolies and Mergers
Commission earlier this month. Minorco's original bid automatically
lapsed when the matter was referred to the commission in October.
   Minorco faces at least one more major legal hurdle. The offer is
conditional on Minorco winning its appeal against a U.S. court
injunction which blocked it from acquiring more than 30 percent of
Consolidated Gold Fields' shares.
   Minorco's offer would top Nestle SA's 2.6 billion-pound, or $4.6
billion, purchase of British confectioner Rowntree PLC last year.
   The latest bid is worth 14 pounds, or $24.78, a share in cash and
stock, for a total of 3.2 billion pounds, or $5.7 billion. Minorco's
previous offer was 13.06 pounds, or $23.12, a share in cash and
stock, for a total of 2.9 billion pounds, or $5.1 billion.
   Consolidated Gold Fields' shares rose 8 pence to 14.43 pounds on
London's Stock Exchange Monday, suggesting that investors believed
Minorco eventually might make an even sweeter bid.
   Minorco's shares rose 10 pence to 766 pence.
   Most analysts were surprised by the latest bid, having expected
Minorco to offer between 15 pounds and 16 pounds a share.
   By putting forward a bid on the low side, Minorco might be buying
time while it overcomes obstacles to the takeover, analysts said.
   Minorco's latest offer ``isn't the end of the game,'' said
Christopher Spreckley, a mining analyst at CL-Alexanders Laing and
Cruickshank. ``There might be another pound (per share) in it.''
   Minorco also might be hoping to force Consolidated Gold Fields to
disclose the price at which it values itself.
   This is a ``sighting shot,'' Consolidated Gold Fields' Agnew
said. ``They don't know what to pay and they want to get our
defenses open.''
   Based in Luxembourg, Minorco is 60 percent-owned by the
Oppenheimers' Anglo American Corp. gold mining giant and the diamond
mining group De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd. It already owns 29.6
percent of Consolidated Gold Fields' shares.
   Part of Consolidated Gold Fields defense in the past five months
has been to raise objections to Minorco's South African connections.
   Sir Michael Edwardes, Minorco's chief executive, said, ``We have
now cleared all the U.K. and European regulatory hurdles put in
Minorco's way by the Gold Fields board.''
   ``Minorco believes that the owners of Gold Fields should now be
given the opportunity to consider the new offer on its merits and to
determine the issues which affect them as shareholders,'' he said.
   Minorco told the European Commission it would sell all
Consolidated Gold Fields' platinum interests should a takeover
succeed.
   Minorco also has said it intends to sell other minority stakes
held by Consolidated Gold Fields, including a 49-percent stake in
Newmont Mining Corp. of the United States, 48 percent in Renison
Goldfields Consolidated Ltd. of Australia, and 38 percent in Gold
Fields of South Africa Ltd.
   This would leave Minorco with Consolidated Gold Fields' ARC
construction materials businesses in Britain and the United States,
and with Gold Fields Mining Corp. in North America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
