<DOCNO> AP890221-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Europe-Airlines     02-21 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Europe-Airlines,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Association To Study Single Traffic Control System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Association of European Airlines
said Tuesday it will study the costs and savings of a single air
traffic control system for Western Europe.
   The 21-airline group said such a consolidation might help reduce
delays and it called upon the European Economic Community for help.
   ``There is no other chance for leadership. Someone has to take
the lead,'' AEA Secretary General Karl-Heinz Neumeister told
reporters.
   He said 19 percent of all medium and long-haul flights in Europe
were delayed more than 15 minutes last year, up from 15 percent in
1987 and 12.5 percent in 1986.
   Neumeister said 70 percent of thosee delays are due to Europe's
fragmented air traffic control operations and 29 percent to airline
operations.
   He said the AEA will study the cost of creating and running a
single air traffic control network for Western Europe. He said he
hoped to have a first draft of the report in May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
