<DOCNO> AP890221-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 0921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Amer-Wilson     02-21 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amer-Wilson,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Finnish Company Buys Wilson Sporting Goods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the best known U.S. names in sporting
goods, Wilson and MacGregor, will be united under the ownership of a
Finnish international conglomerate.
   Wilson Sporting Goods Co. announced Monday that it agreed to be
acquired by Amer Group Ltd. of Finland for $200 million in cash.
   Amer, which is expanding its stake in U.S. sporting-goods
operations, already holds an 80 percent controlling interest in
MacGregor Golf Co., a Wilson competitor based in Albany, Ga. Golf
superstar Jack Nicklaus holds the remaining 20 percent.
   The transaction will be accomplished through a merger between a
wholly owned subsidiary of Amer and WSGC Holdings Inc., Wilson's
parent company. WSGC was bought in 1985 by Morristown, N.J.-based
Wesray Capital Corp. in a $147 million leveraged buyout.
   Wilson, based in the Chicago suburb of River Grove, manufactures
and distributes a wide variety of athletic equipment and apparel
under the Wilson brand name. Wilson estimated net sales for 1988 of
$425 million, a 24 percent gain over 1987.
   Amer, based in East Rutherford, N.J., had sales estimated at $1.3
billion in the the fiscal year ended Feb. 28.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
