<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0353</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed in early dealings
today as trading resumed after a three-day holiday weekend.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose 38.75 points
last week, was up another 1.43 at 2,326.25 after 30 minutes of
trading.
   But declining issues took an early lead over gainers among issues
listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 462 up, 532 down and 520
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 22.78 million shares at 10 a.m.
on Wall Street.
   The U.S. financial markets were closed on Monday in observance of
the President's Day holiday.
   The stock market finished strongly last week with three
consecutive gains, lifting the Dow Jones industrial average by more
than 43 points.
   While some analysts say the market should extend those gains
these week, others say concerns that interest rates may be headed
higher could limit any price advance.
   On that score, traders eagerly awaited Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan's testimony today before the Senate Banking committee.
   In the credit markets before Greenspan's appearance, short-term
interest rates were little changed while long-term rates edged
slightly lower with the 30-year bond yields slipping toward 9
percent.
   In early trading, Texas Eastern jumped 3\ to 51}. On Monday, the
company agreed to a $53-a-share takeover bid from Panhandle Eastern.
   Also among the active issues today, Pacific Telesis slipped [ to
34[, Philadelphia Electric edged up [ to 20\ and Burlington
Resources was up | at 49}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.15 at 166.30. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 0.24 at 325.71.
   On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 13.39 to
2,324.82, stretching its gain for the week to 38.75 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by nearly 2 to 1 on the
NYSE, with 953 up, 497 down and 501 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 159.52 million shares, against 177.45
million in the previous session.
