<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-Workers     02-21 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Workers,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Will Take Up Rail Workers Case from Virginia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether a federal law primarily designed to compensate injured
longshoremen also applies to railroad employees who work at dockside
coal-loading facilities.
   The court, in cases involving three injured workers in Virginia,
said it will hear arguments by railroads seeking to protect
themselves from potentially costly lawsuits.
   The Virginia Supreme Court ruled last year that the
Longshoremen's and Harbor Workers' Compensation Act does not cover
the railroad employees.
   Instead, the state court allowed three injured rail workers to
seek potentially greater compensation under the Federal Employers'
Liability Act.
   The railroads said the compensation provided by the
longshoremen's act should be the exclusive remedy for the three rail
employees.
   The workers are Nancy J. Schwalb and William McGlone, who did
clean-up jobs for the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway Co., and Robert J.
Goode Jr., a machinist for the Norfolk and Western Railway Co.
   All three worked at coal-loading terminals in the Hampton Roads,
Va., area.
   Ms. Schwalb suffered a serious head injury Jan. 11, 1983, when
she fell from a catwalk while going to a nearby area to pick up
spilled coal. McGlone's arm was nearly severed as he was picking up
coal from beneath a moving conveyor belt Feb. 1, 1983. Goode
suffered a hand injury while repairing loading equipment Feb. 11,
1985.
   The three sued the railroad company that employed them under the
Federal Employers' Liability Act.
   Lower courts in Virginia threw out their lawsuits on grounds that
the workers were doing jobs essential to the loading of coal at the
terminals, and thus were eligible for compensation only under the
longshoremen's act.
   But the state Supreme Court reinstated the suits, deciding the
rail employees' jobs were not covered by the longshoremen's act.
   Justice Department lawyers supported the railroads' ensuing
appeals to the nation's highest court.
   They said the three workers could get ``potentially lucrative,
albeit uncertain, relief'' under the employers' liability law.
   But government lawyers said in other cases restricting the scope
of the longshoremen's act could mean workers in similar jobs would
be forced to sue under state laws that provide less compensation for
the injured.
   ``That result would be plainly inconsistent with Congress'
intent'' in 1972, when it amended the longshoremen's law to expand
its coverage, the government lawyers said.
   The Association of American Railroads also urged the Supreme
Court to overrule the Virginia court.
   The association said its members employ some 300,000 workers who,
if injured, could sue them for compensation if the Virginia court
ruling were applied nationwide.
   The cases are Chesapeake and Ohio vs. Schwalb, 87-1979, and
Norfolk and Western vs. Goode, 88-127.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
