<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   02-21 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in a largely technical reversal
of Friday's strong rally in the soybean market.
   Precipitation in some key growing areas during the 3-day weekend
also weighed on prices, analysts said.
   Argentina, a major South American soybean producer, had its
heaviest showers in several weeks while snow and rain improved the
outlook for corn, soybean and winter-wheat production in the United
States.
   But the main factor in the decline appeared to be a bearish
backlash after Friday's runup, which was not supported by
significant changes in supplies or demand.
   ``When that happens, you often have some sort of reaction the
following day as equilibrium returns,'' said Walter Spilka, a
grain-market analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp;
Co.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.22{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent
to 2 cents lower with March at $2.68{ a bushel; oats were unchanged
to 1 cent lower with March at $2.05{ a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents
to 10 cents lower with March at $7.40 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .70 cent higher with April at 77.62
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to .78 cent higher with
March at 83.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .35 cent to .82 cent
higher with April at 42.40 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.53 cent to .85 cent higher with February at 39.35 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled sharply higher on Friday while pork
futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
