<FIRST>u f BC-Unisys     02-21 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Unisys,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys Announces Minicomputers; Plans Employee Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. today announced three minicomputers
that are built around microprocessors from Intel Corp. and use the
industry-standard Unix operating system.
   The new computers are at the forefront of Unisys's efforts in the
field of network computing, which Paul Ely, president of the Network
Computing Group, described as ``by far the highest growth
opportunity in the industry.''
   The computers are known as the U 6000-30, U 6000-70 and U
6000-80. The U 6000-50 was announced last year. Members of the line
cost from $11,500 to $1 million and can serve up to 400 users at
once.
   Ely joined Unisys when it bought Convergent Inc. of San Jose,
Calif., in a $332 million transaction that was announced in August
and completed in December. He had been chairman and chief executive.
   Unisys has headquarters in Blue Bell, Pa., and Detroit.
   The computer announcement came following last week's statement
that Unisys planned to reduce its workforce of 93,000 by 3 percent,
about 2,800 people this year through layoffs and retirements. The
company also plans to cut back on swollen inventories.
   Unisys's statement about job cuts was made in response to a
question at a security analysts' meeting on Thursday. Unisys
spokesman J. Peter Hynes said there was no formal announcement
because the cutbacks were in line with previous steps.
   Since Unisys was formed in 1986 through Burroughs Corp.'s $4.8
billion acquisition of Sperry Corp., it has pared 18,000 people from
its payroll by selling off operations and cut 12,000 more through
early retirements and layoffs, leaving it with 89,500 employees.
Last year's acquisition of Convergent added 3,500 to the rolls.
   Unisys Chairman W. Michael Blumenthal acknowledged last week that
1988 had been a tougher year than anticipated and he expected a
weakness in sales to continue in the first half of 1989.
   Sales in 1988 increased just 2 percent from 1987, to $9.9
billion. Although Unisys' profits rose about 18 percent in 1988,
most of the increase was attributable to lower tax rates, not bigger
profit margins. The company's operating profits slumped nearly
one-quarter on the final quarter of 1988.
</TEXT>
