<DOCNO> AP890221-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Fed-Economy 1stLd-Writethru   02-21 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 15 grafs of testimony, picks up 12th graf pvs, Most
private ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<UNK>AP Economics Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan today
said inflationary pressures are unacceptable and that the central
bank would continue fighting higher prices by driving up interest
rates.
   Greenspan's remarks could spell bad news for the Bush
administration, which is counting on robust economic growth to
reduce the federal budget deficit without the need to increase taxes.
   Greenspan released an economic forecast prepared by the central
bank which showed growth significantly lower than the Bush
administration's estimate.
   Greenspan's comments were made in testimony to the Senate Banking
Committee as part of the requirmeent that the central bank reveal
its economic assumptions and monetary policy targets twice a year.
   The central bank has been pushing interest rates higher in an
effort to restrain domestic demand since March of last year, an
effort which has sent a variety of short-term interest rates
climbing by about 3 percentage points.
   In his testimony, Greenspan discussed this effort and said the
central bank ``remains more inclined to act in the direction of
restraint'' on the supply of credit.
   For the past two years, consumer prices have increased 4.4
percent annually, a rate of increase which Greenspan said was
worrisome.
   ``The wage and price process may have developed some momentum,''
Greenspan said, citing reports showing that wage increases were
rising at a faster clip because of the tight labor markets.
   ``Let met stress that the current rate of inflation, let alone an
increase, is not acceptable, and our policies are designed to reduce
inflation in coming years,'' he said. ``This restraint will involve
containing pressures on our productive resources and, thus, some
slowing in the underlying rate of growth'' of the overall economy.
   Since taking office, President Bush has on several occasions said
he believed the Fed's worries about inflation were misplaced, saying
he saw no need to push interest rates higher.
   However, the central bank has so far ignored those comments,
launching its latest credit-tightening effort just last week
following a report on prices at the wholesale level which showed an
unexpectedly sharp 1 percent increase in January.
   In his report to Congress, Greenspan said the Fed was predicting
the overall economy, as measured by the gross national product,
would expand by between 2.5 percent and 3 percent in 1989. The
administration, however, is basing its budget on a forecast which
expects growth to be a more robust 3.5 percent this year.
   To support its move to restrain inflationary pressures, Greenspan
said the central bank policy-makers reaffirmed a decision made last
summer to lower money growth targets for 1989. For M-2, the measure
of the money supply which includes currency in circulation and
interest-bearing checking accounts, the Fed said it would aim for an
increase of between 3 percent and 7 percent, down a full percentage
point from the 1988 growth target.
   Greenspan said he understood that moves toward tightening the
availability of money and driving up interest rates could have an
adverse impact on the savings and loan crisis, the Third World debt
situation and the debt problems of some American businesses.
   But he said that ``backing away from policy adjustments needed to
contain inflation'' would not solve the various problems and would
put the overall economy in more trouble.
   Most private economists believe the Fed has no choice but to keep
tightening credit in an effort to dampen inflationary pressures,
even at the risk of another downturn.
   Bruce Steinberg, senior economist at Merrill Lynch in New York,
said he believed the Fed has acted responsibly over the past year in
gradually pushing interest rates higher in response to indications
that excessive economic growth and tight labor markets were
threatening to set off another inflationary spiral.
   ``If you postpone the day of reckoning, it will still come and it
will be a lot harsher,'' he said. ``If inflation rises significantly
above levels where it is now, then interest rates would have to go
much higher and the negative effects would be that much greater.''
   That is what occurred in the last economic downturn in 1981-82
when then-Federal Reserve Chairman Paul Volcker pushed the prime
rate up to a high of 21.5 percent in a battle to control the worst
bout of inflation in this country since the Civil War.
   Volcker won the struggle but not without plunging the country
into the 1981-82 recession, the worst downturn since the Great
Depression.
   c
</TEXT>
</DOC>
