<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0389</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices slumped today amid worries about the
outlook for interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose 38.75 points
last week, was off 5.36 at 2,319.46 at noontime.
   Declining issues led gainers by a margin of 2 to 1 among issues
listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 431 up, 879 down and 524
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 70.97 million shares at noon on
Wall Street, compared with 72.42 million shares at the same point
Friday.
   The U.S. financial markets reopened today for the first time in
three days after being closed on Monday in observance of the
President's Day holiday.
   The stock market finished strongly last week with three
consecutive gains, lifting the Dow Jones industrial average by more
than 43 points.
   While some analysts say the market should extend those gains this
week, others say concerns about interest rates could limit any price
advance.
   On that score, traders were closely following reports of Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's testimony today before the Senate
Banking committee.
   Larry Wachtel, a vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., said Greenspan appeared to repeat earlier assertions that the
Fed would lean toward restraint to curb inflation.
   Wachtel said that after last week's gains, the stock market ``was
ready for a bit of a pullback. It is more a lack of buyers than an
abundance of sellers.''
