<DOCNO> AP890221-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Wendy'sCEO     02-21 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wendy's CEO,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wendy's Appoints New CEO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James. W. Near, Wendy's International Inc.
president and chief operating officer, has been appointed chief
executive officer of the fast-food restaurant chain, the company
announced Tuesday.
   Chairman Robert L. Barney, who had served as chief executive
officer, said Near has played a major role in the company's
improvement since 1986, when Wendy's lost $4.9 million. The company
reported profits of $28.5 million last year and $4.5 million in 1987.
   ``He's an outstanding operator whose attention is clearly focused
on the customer,'' Barney said. ``It is appropriate that he be given
more responsibility for the direction of this company.''
   The board of directors approved the appointment Monday.
   Near, 50, became Wendy's president an chief executive officer in
August 1986. He still serves in those positions.
   Near joined Wendy's in 1974 as a franchise owner, developing 40
restaurants in West Virginia and southern Florida. He sold them to
Wendy's in 1978.
   ``When Jim returned to Wendy's in 1986, the game plan was to help
him eventually become CEO,'' Barney said.
   Barney, 52, will remain chairman of the board and a member of the
executive committee. He was elected to Wendy's board when the
company was founded in 1969.
   Near was elected to Wendy's board of directors in 1981.
   ``As a former franchise owner, I know how corporate decisions can
affect the local operator,'' Near said. ``I want our franchisees to
provide their expertise to the corporate decsion-making process. One
of my goals is to have excellent operations consistently in every
Wendy's throughout the country.''
   There were 3,762 Wendy's Old Fashioned Hamburger restaurants
worldwide at the end of last year.
</TEXT>
