<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Computer     02-21 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Computer,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard's Quarterly Earnings Rise 8 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. said Tuesday its net
earnings rose 8 percent in the first quarter of fiscal year 1989
when compared to the first quarter of the previous year. Per-share
earnings were up 17 percent, the electronics giant said.
   Net earnings rose to $193 million, or 83 cents a share, from $179
million, or 71 cents per share, in the first quarter of last year.
Revenue rose 21 percent to $2.66 billion from $2.19 billion.
   Earnings from operations grew by 20 percent, but reductions in
interest income softened their impact in net results. The company
said its cash balance dropped from the year-ago quarter due to the
high level of stock repurchases during 1988.
   Orders climbed to $3.0 billion from $2.4 billion a year ago, with
U.S. orders rising 17 percent and international orders up 29 percent.
   ``We are pleased with the substantial increase in orders
throughout the quarter, and with the growth from the first quarter
of fiscal 1988, which was also an especially strong period for us,''
John A. Young, the company's president and chief executive, said in
a statement. ``The U.S. order growth rate also was good news.''
   Hewlett-Packard, which celebrates its 50th anniversary this year,
has 87,000 employees and 1988 revenue of $9.8 billion.
</TEXT>
