<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     02-21 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mixed Tuesday in choppy European
trading, losing early gains when U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan signaled no significant change in American monetary
policy. Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said Greenspan did not say anything new or surprising in
his testimony to the U.S. Senate's banking committee but many
regarded his comments as less aggressively bullish than had been
expected.
   ``(U.S.) monetary policy remains unchanged,'' said a dealer in
Frankfurt, West Germany. ``It looks like further interest rate
increases are out of the question for the time being.''
   Greenspan called for financial restraints to prevent further
rises in inflation but said U.S. monetary policy ``appears to be on
track'' and that he expected the dollar to remain stable for some
months.
   The dollar had gained in Asian and early European dealings on
expectations that Greenspan would strongly emphasize the Fed's
commitment to fighting inflation, dealers said.
   ``Ultimately, the market actually wants to see higher (interest)
rates rather than just forecast that they will materialize,'' said a
senior dealer in London.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 1.40 Japanese yen to a closing 127.15
yen. Later, in London it eased to 126.75 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Monday:
1.8420 West German marks, down from 1.8435; 1.5685 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5683; 6.2735 French francs, down from 6.2825; 2.0910 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0820; 1,356.00 Italian lire, up from 1,350.50;
1.1897 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7565 from $1.7665 late
Monday.
   Gold prices rose in London to a late bid price of $384 a troy
ounce, up from $382.25 bid late Monday.
   In Zurich, the metal rose to $383 from $382.20 bid late Monday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose to a closing bid of $384.34 from
$384.01 Monday.
   Silver was quoted in London at a late bid price of $5.93 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Monday's late bid.
</TEXT>
