<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed narrowly mixed
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade after a late surge of buying
by commercial interests erased losses that prevailed for most of the
session.
   The buying may have reflected a desire of grain handlers and
processors to lock in their supply costs at current levels and avoid
a sudden runup in prices like the one that ended Friday's session.
   But analysts also said much of the day's activity was motivated
by technical traders' interpretations of recent chart patterns.
   The session opened on a low note after the 3-day weekend, with
much of the selling attributed to improved growing conditions for
the South American soybean crop and weekend precipitation in some
key U.S. crop regions.
   At the close, wheat was { cent lower to 2{ cents higher with
March at $4.24{ a bushel; corn was unchanged to 2\ cents lower with
March at $2.69{ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 6\ cents higher
with March at $2.12 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 2 cents
higher with March at $7.46{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
