<HEAD>IBM Announces Upgrades Of Mid-Size Computers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. on Tuesday
announced improvements to its Application System-400 line of
mid-size computers, which it is using as a weapon in a war for
market share with Digital Equipment Corp.
   IBM announced expansion features for the smallest models of the
AS-400 line _ the B10 and B20 _ and a new B70 that extends the range
of the line. They will be available in June.
   IBM introduced the first six models of the AS-400 line with great
fanfare in June 1988. It announced more than 1,000 programs that
would run on the machines, a number that it said has since grown to
more than 4,000.
   The price of the B70 is about $400,000, including
operating-system software and a 16-megabyte main memory card.
