<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-George Bjt   02-21 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-George, Bjt,0762</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Eastern Pilots Union's George: Flyboy With a Harvard MBA</BYLINE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Lorenzo, the tough-as-nails chairman of
giant Texas Air Corp., has a master's degree in business
administration from Harvard University.
   So does Wright B. George, who flies planes for Eastern Airlines,
the besieged carrier owned by Texas Air.
   The two are on opposite sides of a bitter, escalating conflict
that could result in a March 4 strike by the airline's Machinists
union, which the Eastern pilots and flight attendants have pledged
to honor.
   George, a member of the master executive council of the pilots
union at Miami-based Eastern, is spreading the union gospel about
Eastern and Lorenzo to Wall Street analysts, creditors of the
strapped airline and the public.
   The campaign is aimed at forcing Lorenzo to sign what George
called acceptable contracts with the Machinists, pilots and flight
attendants at Eastern.
   George, 46, doesn't pull punches. He's going after his
cost-cutting boss with nearly the same fervor he showed flying
combat support missions as an Air Force captain in Vietnam.
   Lorenzo is ``looking at the abyss. The evil empire is
tottering,'' he said in a recent interview in New York. ``We
understand the risk (of striking). The worst thing that can happen
to us is that we lose our jobs.''
   That risk appears real. Many financial analysts and other
observers believe a strike against Eastern could jeopardize the
airline's survival.
   Eastern recently reported a record net loss of $335.4 million in
1988, nearly double its $181.7 million loss the year before. Revenue
dropped to $3.8 billion from $4.4 billion in 1987.
   The airline's latest contract offer _ rejected by the Machinists
_ calls for $150 million in wage cuts.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said no Eastern officials wished
to comment on George or his activities.
   George, Harvard Business School Class of `74, calls Lorenzo,
Class of `63, ``a financial genius but a business moron.''
   George has organized a presentation for Wall Street analysts and
Eastern creditors in New York on Wednesday _ the same day
intensified talks involving Eastern management, the Machinists and
federal mediators are set to start in Washington.
   Among other things, George said, the pilots and their financial
consultants plan to warn the airline's creditors of the risk to them
if Eastern is hit by a strike.
   George, who is a manager of the Eastern pilots' pension fund,
masterminded a session with analysts last September. He also was a
prime organizer of a demonstration against Lorenzo later that month
at the 25th reunion of Lorenzo's Harvard Business School class in
Cambridge, Mass. The Rev. Jesse Jackson Jr. was among the speakers
addressing the rally.
   How did an Eagle Scout and church altar boy from rural Illinois
arrive at center stage in the high-stakes conflict?
   ``I'm a pilot and I'm basically fighting for the profession,''
said George, who manages to look like a boxer, Ivy League banker and
farm boy. ``This profession is in a death struggle with Mr.
Lorenzo.''
   Sitting in the paneled mahogany caverns of the Harvard Club in
midtown Manhattan, he seems more culturally akin to the corporate
dealmakers he assails than the mechanics and baggage handlers he
supports.
   George grew up on a farm in Sycamore, Ill., studied mathematics
and economics at the University of Wisconsin, and later flew support
missions in Vietnam, evacuating casualties.
   After his Air Force service from 1967 to 1971, George attended
Harvard while starting to fly for Eastern, getting his MBA in 1974.
Wall Street was the next move, but he didn't stay there long.
   ``I had a brief but mediocre career,'' he said, referring to his
stint at Bankers Trust Co. ``I don't particularly like being tied to
a desk.''
   But George does like flying. He left the desks of Wall Street to
return to the cockpits of Eastern in 1974 and has been flying for
the carrier ever since. He's clocked around 10,000 hours of flight
time, he reckons, on domestic routes and in Latin America.
   His jabs at Lorenzo aren't all deadly serious. At the pilots'
meeting with financial analysts last September, George caught the
attention of the normally blase analysts and news reporters by
bouncing a striped beach ball during his opening remarks.
   ``Mr. Lorenzo agreed to cater the meal today,'' he told the
participants solemnly, as waiters proceeded to serve peanuts from
silver trays.
</TEXT>
