<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-LBOSurvey     02-21 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LBO Survey,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most People Believe Takeover Process Is Corrupt, Poll Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of people interviewed in a national
survey believe the corporate takeover process in this country is
corrupt and should be regulated by Congress.
   In the survey released Tuesday, 84 percent of the respondents
said they believed mergers and acquisitions take place in a corrupt
environment, and two-thirds said the government should place more
restrictions on leveraged buyouts. In a leveraged buyout, investors
buy a company with largely borrowed funds, and then pay off the
loans with the company's cash flow or by selling its assets.
   The survey, conducted for the National Law Journal and Lexis, a
computerized legal data base operated by the information firm Mead
Data Central, polled 808 people between Jan. 28 and 30. During that
time, two congressional committees were holding hearings into
possibly restricting LBOs.
   Public awareness of and concern about LBOs have increased in
recent months as a result of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.'s record
$24.53 buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc.
   In the survey, which has a margin of error of 3.5 percentage
points, 32 percent of the respondents endorsed restructuring tax
laws to make it more difficult for LBOs to be accomplished, a step
that has received support in Congress and the Bush administration.
   Twenty-four percent of the respondents said consumers are hurt
the most by takeovers. Fifty-four percent said employees are hurt
the most, but one-third also said the gretest benefit of takeover
activity was the creation of new jobs.
   More than one-fifth of the respondents said they or a member of
their immediate family had worked for a company that was involved in
a takeover in the last three years. Of that group, almost 50 percent
reported negative consequences of the takeover, including the loss
of a job.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
