<FIRST>u f AM-ManufacturersHanover     02-21 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manufacturers Hanover,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manufacturers Hanover Says Trader Lost $14 Million In Unauthorized
Dealings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. said Tuesday a
vice president in its government bond trading department lost $14
million for the bank last year through unauthorized, secret dealings
in Canadian bonds.
   The bank refused to identify the individual but said the person
``has been relieved of his or her duties.''
   The bank said the loss, discovered earlier this month in a
routine review, caused it to reduce its reported profit for 1988 by
1.4 percent to $952 million, instead of $966 million as reported in
a January news release.
   ``The employee is not only very experienced but clever and
sophisticated,'' said John Stefans, a bank spokesman. He said the
person had been with Manufacturers Hanover about five years and in
the business about 20 years.
   The vice president, without authorization, bought about $600
million worth of Canadian federal and provincial bonds over at least
a year, mainly in the final weeks of 1988, Stefans said.
   To conceal the transactions, the person put them in the bank's
investment account instead of its trading account, Stefans said.
   Securities held in the investment account are carried on the
books at what they cost. When the securities were moved to the
trading account, where they belonged, they had to be booked at their
lower market value, resulting in the $14 million loss, Stefans said.
   Stefans said the bank had been in contact with the Federal
Reserve and the New York state Banking Department. He said it has
not yet been determined whether to lodge civil or criminal charges
against the executive.
   The bank has reviewed its procedures for preventing unauthorized
trading, Stefans said. But he added, ``A sophisticated enough
person, for a particular period of time, if intent on doing
something, can probably get away with it.''
   ``Everybody on the floor was surprised'' when word of the
unauthorized trading got out, said Bill Pike, who is in charge of
U.S. Treasury bond and municipal bond trading.
   In addition to the correction in full-year earnings, the bank cut
its reported earnings for the fourth quarter by $14 million, to $210
million from $224 million. The earnings did not have to be formally
restated because they had never been officially stated, only put out
in a press release, Stefans said.
   Losses from unauthorized trading in recent years have prompted
scrutiny of management controls at some Wall Street firms. The giant
investment firm Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. reorganized its mortgage
securities unit after unauthorized trading in a risky form of
security caused a $275 million pre-tax loss in April 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
