<DOCNO> AP890221-0300 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1749EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     02-21 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Surge On Reports Of Zambian Flooding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices posted their sharpest gains in three months
Tuesday as reports of flood-related mining disruptions in Zambia
refocused attention on the difficulties faced by many Third World
copper producers.
   On other markets, gold futures rose sharply; cotton futures
soared; livestock and meat futures rallied; grains and soybeans were
mixed; and energy futures were mostly lower.
   Copper futures settled 2.9 cents to 8.3 cents higher on New
York's Commodity Exchange with the contract for delivery in March at
$1.345 a pound, representing a one-day gain of nearly 6.6 percent in
the contract's value.
   The concerns raised by flooding at a Zambia Consolidated Copper
Mines Ltd. facility spread well beyond the implications for copper
output from Zambia, the world's fourth-largest copper producer.
   The incident served to remind traders of the strain on copper
producers in Africa, Latin America and Asia as they strive to catch
up with the demand created by the strong economies of the
industrialized world.
   Copper production hurdles and labor difficulties have cropped up
during the past year in Peru and Chile while the major African
coppper countries have struggled with transportation problems.
   Those factors helped push copper futures prices to the record
high of $1.6475 reached on Dec. 8. But production concerns have
faded in recent weeks as copper stockpiles increased.
   ``A market is very much a forum for changes in sentiment,'' said
George Anagnos, a metals analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities
Inc. in New York. ``The flooding was important but it also focused
people's attention on broad output problems throughout the Third
World.''
   The London Metal Exchange on Monday reported a 1,750-metric-ton
decrease last week in its warehouse stocks of copper, to 85,025
metric tons. Anagnos said the market had been expecting an increase
of more than 5,000 metric tons.
   Gold futures advanced strongly on the Commodity Exchange
following Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan's testimony
before the Senate Banking Committee.
   Analysts said Greenspan was perceived as being too soft on
inflation. Gold is often seen as an investment hedge against
inflation.
   Gold settled $5.10 to $5.60 higher with April at $389.40 a troy
ounce; silver settled 0.5 cent lower to 0.1 cent higher with March
at $5.935 a troy ounce.
   Cotton futures rallied on reports that the Plains Cotton
Cooperative in Lubbock, Texas, had sold from 250,000 to 300,000
bales of cotton, an unusually large amount, to unknown destinations.
   Cotton settled .88 cent to 1.54 cents higher with March at 58.57
cents a pound.
   Feeder cattle led the livestock and meat futures markets higher
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in reaction to continued strong
demand among meat packers for fattened cattle.
   Live cattle settled .28 cent to .83 cent higher with April at
77.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .70 cent to 1.35 cents
higher with March at 84.30 cents a pound; live hogs were .35 cent to
1 cent higher with April at 42.82 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .45 cent to the limit 2 cents higher with February at 39.32
cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures finished narrowly mixed on the Chicago
Board of Trade after a late surge of buying by commercial interests
erased the losses that had held sway for most of the session.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 2\ cents higher with March at $4.25 a
bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to \ cent higher with March at $2.69}
a bushel; oats were { cent to 7\ cents higher with March at $2.13 a
bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 2 cents higher with March at
$7.46{ a bushel.
   Energy futures prices finished mostly lower on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in nervous trading while traders kept one eye on
a London meeting of oil ministers from non-OPEC countries.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .13 cent lower to .03
cent higher with March at $18.59 a barrel; heating oil was .27 cent
to .98 cent lower with March at 48.92 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .30 cent to .94 cent lower with March at 48.35 cents a
gallon.
</TEXT>
