<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   02-21 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones industrial average posted a tiny
gain Tuesday but broader market measures slumped in what some
analysts said was a reflection of deepening worries about inflation
and interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which climbed 38.75
points last week, eked out a gain of 1.61 points to close at
2,326.43.
   But declining issues outnumbered gainers by nearly 3 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
611 up, 872 down and 505 unchanged.
   ``The market seems to have lost its momentum, its gusto, the
urgency to buy coming off the lows of last November,'' said Edward
P. Nicoski, a market strategist for the investment firm Piper
Jaffray &amp; Hopwood Inc. in Minneapolis.
   He said traders were becoming more concerned about inflation, a
concern that Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan acknowledged in
an appearance before the Senate Banking Committee.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 141.95 million
shares, down from 159.52 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 173.90 million shares.
   The U.S. financial markets reopened Tuesday for the first time in
three days after being closed on Monday in observance of the
President's Day holiday.
   The stock market had finished strongly last week, propelling the
Dow Jones industrial average up by more than 43 points in the last
three sessions alone.
   Traders closely monitored Greenspan's congressional testimony on
Tuesday, and some came away disappointed that he wasn't more
forceful in repeating an earlier pledge that the central bank would
continue fighting higher prices by driving up interest rates.
   Piper's Nicoski said Greenspan left open the possibility that the
Fed officials ``may not be able to tighten as much as they'd like''
because of the financial failures in the savings and loan industry.
   ``People are really starting to get concerned here about
inflation,'' Nicoski said.
   Few traders appeared ready to buy stocks in advance of
Wednesday's scheduled report on consumer prices in January. Earlier
this month, the government reported a bigger-than-expected rise in
producer prices in January.
   Larry Wachtel, a vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., said the market may simply have been due for a correction.
   ``It is more a lack of buyers than an abundance of sellers,'' he
said.
   Sonat was the most active issue on the NYSE, rising ~ to 32 after
a pair of 2 million share blocks were traded.
   Texas Eastern was second most active on the NYSE, jumping 3~ to
52]. On Monday, the company agreed to a $53-a-share takeover bid
from Panhandle Eastern.
   Polaroid fell ] to 43]. The company said it was beginning a
tender offer of $50 a share for up to 22 percent of its stock in a
bid to fend off a hostile suitor.
   Hewlett-Packard fell 1 to 59 despite reporting its earnings per
share rose to 83 cents in its first quarter from 71 cents per share
a year earlier.
   Holly Corp. surged 9| to 35\ on the American Stock Exchange after
disclosing it had hired an investment adviser to consider the
possible sale of the company and other alternatives.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market fell $7.148 billion, or 0.24
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.39 to 166.06.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 0.59 to 342.07, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index dropped 0.78 to 295.98.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market lost
0.81 to 406.38. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 324.86, off 1.09.
</TEXT>
