<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     02-21 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most oil futures prices ended lower in volatile
trading Tuesday, reflecting uncertainty over the outcome of a
non-OPEC producers conference.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, closed 3
cents higher at $18.59 after trading as high as $18.93 during the
session. All other contract months fell.
   Refined product prices fell sharply. The March contract for
heating oil dropped 0.98 cent to settle at 48.92 cents a gallon,
after trading at a session high of 50.35 cents.
   Unleaded gasoline scheduled for March delivery fell 0.94 cent to
a closing price of 48.35 cents a gallon. Other contract months also
closed down.
   Crude prices opened higher with buyers caught up in last-day
trading on the March contract, analysts said. Prices fluctuated
throughout the session on various OPEC-related rumors, they said.
   Late in the day, a group of producers who don't belong to the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, meeting in London,
released a statement saying some producers had agreed to either cut
or freeze exports during the second quarter of 1989 to help
stabilize world prices.
   However, the group said it would not disclose details of the
agreement until next week, which created uncertainty and pressured
prices, analysts said. ``It's disappointing because investors were
expecting concrete numbers,'' said Nauman Barakat, vice president of
energy investments at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``As long as
they don't know it's difficult to say what the bottom line is ... so
the market sold off.''
   Analysts have predicted that any cutbacks by non-OPEC nations
will be minimal and probably will not alter the current
supply-demand balance. Since OPEC reduced its production by 3
million barrels daily at the start of the year, prices have risen
nearly $5 a barrel.
</TEXT>
