<FIRST>r f AM-Pepperell 1stLd-Writethru   02-21 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepperell, 1st Ld-Writethru,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Deadline Passes With No Word On Bids For Pepperell</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf with Farley extending offer to Thursday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest deadline for takeover bids on
West Point-Pepperell Inc. passed Tuesday with no word on whether the
textile company would extend the bidding or which suitors might have
submitted offers.
   ``We're still not commenting at all on the bidding process,''
said spokeswoman Toni Cauble.
   The Wall Street Journal, quoting an unidentified person familiar
with the bidding, reported Tuesday that Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. or a
subsidiary, Merrill Lynch Capital Partners, had submitted a bid.
Pepperell officials declined comment on the report and Merrill
officials did not return telephone calls.
   Two other companies, Dominion Textile Inc. of Montreal and
Milliken &amp; Co. of Spartanburg, S.C., were rumored to be interested,
but both have declined to comment.
   Pepperell's directors put the textile and apparel company up for
sale Feb. 3 in response to a hostile takeover bid from Chicago-based
Farley Inc. They originally set a Feb. 15 deadline for bids, but
extended it until noon Tuesday.
   Farley's public offer of $52 per share, or $1.5 billion, was to
expire at midnight Tuesday, but the company said it had been
extended to Thursday.
   West Point-Pepperell, the nation's largest publicly held textile
company, makes sheets and towels under the Martex, Lady Pepperell
and Utica brands, as well as Arrow shirts. It has steadfastly fought
the bid by Farley, which controls underwear manufacturer Fruit of
the Loom Inc. and Acme Boot Co. Inc.
   Farley originally made its bid for the company last October,
offering $48 per share, or $1.4 billion, for Pepperell's outstanding
stock. The offer was increased to $52 per share on Feb. 1.
   Merrill Lynch Capital Partners last fall completed raising money
for a $1.5 billion buyout fund. In 1987, the Capital Partners unit
financed buyouts of Borg-Warner Corp. for $4.78 billion and
Supermarkets General Corp. for $2.07 billion, but last year the unit
completed just five purchases totaling $1 billion.
</TEXT>
