<FIRST>r f AM-Computer-AidedDesign     02-21 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer-Aided Design,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockheed's Cadam Expands Design Software</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp.'s Cadam Inc., branching out into
new territory, said Tuesday it was making its design software
available on workstations made by Sun Microsystems Inc. and Apollo
Computer Inc.
   The step should help Cadam's sales while making it easier for
engineers to work together on designs even if they use different
models of computers, said Eric Keller, senior research analyst at
Gartner Group in Stamford, Conn.
   Cadam Professional software is for designing objects ranging from
cars to printed circuit boards.
   Cadam said a feature called Power Link will make it easy for
designs that are developed on a Sun workstation to be moved to an
Apollo workstation, and vice versa.
   General Motors Corp. demanded that exchangeability in 1987 when
it authorized Cadam as one of its two suppliers of computer-aided
design software, along with McDonnell Douglas Corp.
   Eventually other computers, including International Business
Machines Corp.'s RT-PC, will be included in Power Link, Cadam said.
The RT-PC was the first workstation to run Cadam Professional. Cadam
also makes design software that runs on mainframes and personal
computers.
</TEXT>
