<FIRST>u f AM-Compaq-Businessland 2ndLd-Writethru   02-21 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Compaq-Businessland, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compaq Terminates Relationship With Businessland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs to UPDATE with reax from Businessland and
further further information from Compaq; picks up 13th graf, But Businessland
....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compaq Computer Corp. announced Tuesday it no
longer will market its products through Businessland Inc. stores in
the wake of a dispute with the huge retail chain.
   ``It has become apparent to us that continuing our relationship
with Businessland is not in the best interest of Compaq or our
customers,'' said Michael S. Swavely, vice president of sales and
marketing for Houston-based Compaq.
   Businessland last year accounted for about 7 percent of the $2.1
billion in annual revenue for Compaq, a leading maker of desktop,
laptop and portable personsal computers.
   At the same time, sales of Compaq products accounted for about 15
percent of the $872 million in net sales during fiscal 1988 for
Businessland, which is based in San Jose, Calif.
   Swavely said Businessland had requested a business relationship
in which the companies would have been ``strategic partners.''
   Swavely said that would have required Compaq to give Businessland
company preferential treatment, Swavely said. Compaq hasn't given it
and Businessland has elected not to support Compaq, he said.
   ``Simply put, Businessland has repeatedly requested special
treatment that would give them an advantage over other authorized
dealers. Compaq remains committed to the philosophy that authorized
dealers should be treated fairly and equally,'' he said.
   Compaq spokesman Bob Beach said Businessland over time kept
asking ask Compaq for preferential treatment in terms of profit
margins, certain support systems and other areas. Beach said he
could not provide specifics.
   Compaq's announcement surprised Businessland officials.
Businessland issued a statement saying that it was in compliance
with Compaq's authorized dealer agreement and that Compaq's
notification was unforeseen.
   Suzanne Crocker, Businessland's vice president for marketing and
communications, said the retailer had asked Compaq to reimburse it
for some of the cost of giving technical support to buyers of Compaq
computers. She said Businessland has such arrangements with other
computer makers.
   Adding to tension between Compaq and Businessland, David A.
Norman, Businessland's chairman and chief executive, told securities
analysts two weeks ago that Businessland would put the bulk of its
technical support behind computers such as International Business
Machines Corp.'s Personal System-2 line that are built on Micro
Channel Architecture.
   That was a rebuff to Compaq, which is working with other IBM
rivals on an alternative to Micro Channel called Extended Industry
Standard Architecture.
   ``Micro Channel is the best solution for the future given what we
know today,'' Ms. Crocker said Tuesday.
   The agreement between Compaq and Businessland, which has been in
effect since 1983, will terminate effective April 21.
   ``I think on a short-term basis, Businessland will sell their
current inventory and that may have a short-term negative pricing
effect,'' on Compaq, said Richard W. Davis, ana analyst with Advest
Group Inc.
   But Businessland officials say they are confident the addition of
new vendors and continuing sales of other products will restore
revenue.
   Swavely said the company anticipates Compaq customers to move
their business to other dealers.
   Compaq informed Businessland of its decision Monday. Swavely said
several Compaq dealers have been de-authorized during the past six
years.
   ``The action is specific to this single dealer, and, as such,
does not indicate any change in Compaq's strategic commitment to its
other dealers,'' Swavely said.
   For 1988, Compaq had record sales of $2.1 billion, up from $1.2
billion in 1987. The company also had a record net income of $255
million for 1988, up from $136 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
