<FIRST>u f AM-AFL-CIOMeeting 1stLd-Writethru f0164 02-21 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AFL-CIO Meeting, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0164,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dole Promises Open Door To Labor But Short on Specifics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 4th graf bg'ng, I want ... to UPDATE with
Democratic Chairman Brown addressing labor council. Picks up 5th graf pvs
bg'ng, At a meeeting ...; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole on
Tuesday promised to work with labor and piqued the interest of union
leaders by calling for a flexible pension system, but she also
disagreed with them on several issues.
   The tone of the first meeting between the AFL-CIO Executive
Council and Mrs. Dole was amiable despite the differences, a stark
contrast with the first such session of the Reagan presidency, when
then-Labor Secretary Raymond Donovan and the union leaders clashed
publicly over the president's economic plans.
   There was no such acrimony after the meeting with Mrs. Dole,
although federation President Lane Kirkland said it was inevitable
that labor would disagree with the Bush administration on some
issues.
   ``I want continued dialogue with the individuals in that room and
certanly I want to leave my door open and be in touch with them,''
Mrs. Dole said after her private meeting with the 35-member council.
   While Mrs. Dole represented the Republican administration at the
meeting, new Democratic Party Chairman Ronald H. Brown also was in
Florida to address the AFL-CIO's political committee.
   Brown said he briefed the labor leaders on party efforts to gain
500 seats in state legislatures by 1990 and 100 more by 1992, an
effort to increase the number of state legislatures, 28, in which
Democrats control all chambers.
   ``Labor's got an extremely important role in the party,'' Brown
said after the meeting. ``Labor has important political tentacles
around the country, it can be very important in electing Democrats.''
   At a meeting with reporters, Mrs. Dole raised a proposal to allow
workers who change jobs to carry pension funds with them. She said
that the administration was studying the issue and that she asked
the labor leaders for their input.
   Kirkland said the federation welcomed her interest and would
cooperate.
   An early disagreement likely will be on congressional proposals
to raise the minimum wage. Mrs. Dole said Bush would support that if
the legislation also carried a sub-minimum training wage for youths;
Kirkland said the AFL-CIO opposes the lower wage.
   Other areas of apparent disagreement are child care and parental
leave, with the administration favoring voluntary policies that
might include tax credits. Labor backs Democrat-sponsored bills that
mandate some programs.
   ``We never signed on for a honeymoon,'' Kirkland said when asked
to assess labor's early relations with the Bush administration.
   ``It's early on and we have yet to see what issues or areas we
can cooperate on. I'm quite certain there will be some where we
disagree.''
   The meeting with Mrs. Dole came on the second day of the annual
weeklong meeting of the governing body of the 1.9 million-member
federation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 1947EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Polaroid 1stLd-Writethru f0174 02-21 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polaroid, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0174,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polaroid Begins Stock Buyback, Including Possible Private Purchases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts first 3 grafs to CLARIFY that private purchases are
possible, but not certain; SUBS 11th graf pvs, `Shamrock spokesman ...,'
to ADD 2 grafs of Shamrock comment; INSERTS new penultimate graf with lawsuit.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. began a $1.1 billion stock
buyback Tuesday and said the plan may include $325 million in
privately negotiated share purchases, a move some analysts said was
aimed at the company's hostile suitor.
   The instant camera maker, which announced Jan. 30 that it would
undertake the buyback, began a cash tender offer for 16 million
shares at $50 a share. In addition, Polaroid said it would
repurchase $325 million of its stock on the open market or ``in
privately negotiated purchases.''
   The offer of private negotiations was seen by some as an
invitation to Shamrock Holdings Inc. of Burbank, Calif., which holds
a 6.7 percent stake in Polaroid and is pursuing a $3.2 billion
hostile takeover of the company.
   ``They're leaving the door wide open for greenmail,'' said Alex
Henderson, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities in New York.
``I can't think of any other privately held block of stock other
than Shamrock's that would be negotiated individually.''
   Greenmail is the practice of buying back shares held by a
corporate raider at a premium compared with the market price, in
order to thwart a potential or actual hostile bid. Critics say the
practice favors raiders at the expense of other stockholders.
   But some Wall Street analysts said Polaroid seemed to be making
an effort to placate its stockholders by offering a premium for some
of their shares.
   Polaroid's buyback offer of $50 a share is $5 over Shamrock's
last bid and $6.25 above Friday's closing price for Polaroid shares
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   On Tuesday, Polaroid stock fell 37{ cents to close at $43.37{ a
share.
   Charles K. Ryan, an analyst for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets,
said the drop reflected anxiety about the possibility of greenmail.
   ``Polaroid's announcement is good for 30 percent of the stock and
bad for 70 percent,'' Ryan said. ``It does provide shareholder value
for some of the shares, but if they remove Shamrock by doing this,
the remaining shares could decline in value.''
   Shamrock called the buyback a further attempt at entrenchment by
Polaroid's management.
   ``We believe that Polaroid's partial buyback is a far leass
attractive alternative than Shamrock's $45 cash offer for all
Polaroid shares,'' Shamrock President Stanley P. Gold said in a
statement.
   Shamrock, a television and radio concern owned by the Roy E.
Disney family, owns about 4.8 million shares of Polaroid and is
waging a proxy fight for control of the board of directors at the
May 9 annual meeting, in addition to its hostile tender offer.
   Polaroid has been resisting Shamrock since the California company
made a friendly but unsolicited offer of $40 a share last July. In
September, Shamrock launched a hostile offer of $42 per share. Last
month, it boosted that offer to $45.
   Polaroid last July put 9.7 million shares into an employee stock
ownership plan. In January, the company announced a recapitalization
plan that included selling $300 million of preferred stock to
Corporate Partners L.P., a private investment group.
   Shamrock has filed suit in Delaware Chancery Court in an effort
to block Polaroid's buyback, the ESOP and the sale of stock to
Corporate Partners. Polaroid is incorporated in Delaware.
   Polaroid said its stock repurchase offer expires March 20 and is
subject to various conditions, including definitive financing, an
absence of adverse decisions in lawsuits with Shamrock, and changes
in Shamrock's hostile bid. If more than 16 million shares are
tendered, Polaroid said it will buy shares back on a pro rata basis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
