<DOCNO> AP890221-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WorldsOfWonder     02-21 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Worlds Of Wonder,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troubled Toy Company Announces Plan To Sell To Investors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Worlds of Wonder Inc. announced Tuesday it
reached a definitive agreement to sell the troubled toy company to a
group of New York investors for an undisclosed amount, subject to
bankruptcy court approval.
   If the deal signed Monday is approved, Worlds of Wonder will
emerge from its reorganization, the company said in a statement.
   The company began in a trailer in 1985 and saw sales climb to
$300 million within two years with such toys as Teddy Ruxpin, the
talking teddy bear, and Lazer Tag.
   But it reported large losses after it encountered production
problems and failed to develop new hit toys. The company filed for
protection under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws in
December 1987 after it was sued by creditors seeking payment.
   Worlds of Wonder hopes to file the reorganization plan in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in Oakland within the next few weeks and expects
confirmation hearings to be held in April or May, said the company's
general counsel, Anne Jordan.
   Once the plan is approved, a newly formed company headed by
investor Eli Jacobs would acquire Worlds of Wonder's assets for an
undisclosed amount of cash, notes and preferred stock and continue
to operate the company in Fremont under the same name, Jordan said.
   ``It allows the company to move forward with the plans for a
revitalized business, which we developed over the past year,''
Stephen J. Hopkins, WOW's chairman and chief executive officer, said
in a statement.
   In addition to Jacobs, the investment group includes Franklyn S.
Barry Jr., former president of Fisher-Price Toys, and David Edelman,
former president of Ingram Software.
   Proceeds from the sale would go to Worlds of Wonder's secured
creditors, Algemene Bank Nederland and First National Bank of
Chicago, lead bank for a group of five financial institutions, the
company said.
   The company repeated its earlier announcement that current
stockholders would not receive any money, and that their stock would
be canceled. The new company would then issue its own stock, Jordan
said.
   Worlds of Wonder announced late last year it was talking with
investors about a possible sale. The company has been negotiating
the agreement with Jacobs and the other investors for the past few
weeks, Jordan said.
   Just before it filed for Chapter 11 protection, Worlds of Wonder,
which designs, develops, markets and distributes toys, employed
about 500 people. About 120 people now work for the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
