<DOCNO> AP890221-0311 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AFL-CIO-Eastern     02-21 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AFL-CIO-Eastern,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dole Says Too Soon For Bush Position On Eastern; Unions Plan for
Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole said
Tuesday that President Bush needs more time to decide whether to
accept an AFL-CIO request that he intervene to block a threatened
strike at Eastern Airlines.
   The AFL-CIO, meanwhile, intensified its preparations for a
strike, asking its affiliated unions to assist the Machinists union
if it goes on strike against Eastern and to boycott its parent
company, Texas Air Corp.
   ``The stakes are high and the IAM deserves the most thorough
support we can provide,'' AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland said in a
letter to the unions.
   Outside Eastern headquarters in nearby Miami, hundreds of Eastern
workers held a noon-hour rally as a show of solidarity with
negotiators on their way to Washington, D.C., Tuesday night for an
intensive round of mediated contract talks.
   Speaking at the rally as if a strike were a certainty, Eastern
Machinists leader Charles Bryan promised, ``Anyone who gives
services or aid and comfort to providing staff or help to (Texas Air
owner) Frank Lorenzo in the strike pending here will suffer the
wrath of organized labor.''
   The 9,000 Eastern mechanics and ground workers are scheduled to
strike March 4, but that deadline would automatically be pushed back
60 days if Bush named an emergency board to mediate the 16-month
dispute.
   Mrs. Dole said Bush was awaiting advice from the departments of
Labor and Transportation and a recommendation from the National
Mediation Board on whether an emergency board was needed. The
mediation board is coordinating talks scheduled to resume Wednesday.
   ``Give the president the opportunity to look at all the data
first,'' Mrs. Dole said.
   Eastern, which has asked the Machinists for $150 million a year
in wage and other concessions, has said it plans to operate in the
event of a strike. The union says the carrier has circulated memos
asking supervisors for a list of managers scheduled for work March
4, training records and parts in stock.
   The machinists are seeking raises totaling $50 million, which
means the two sides are $200 million apart.
   Labor leaders Monday promised to disrupt air travel and shipping
in the event of a strike by picketing Eastern, its sister carrier,
Continental Airlines, and any air or ground carriers that have
service agreements with Eastern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
