<DOCNO> AP890221-0312 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FairchildSuit     02-21 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fairchild Suit,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suit Claims Fairchild Unit Falsified Tests On Aircraft Parts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $200 million civil lawsuit against Fairchild
Industries' Voi-Shan unit accuses the defense contractor of
falsifying test results for nuts, bolts and rivets used in military
and commercial planes.
   The suit was filed in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles in May,
but it remains sealed while the government considers joining the
action, the Los Angeles Times reported Tuesday.
   Fairchild spokeswoman Deborah Tucker at the company's Chantilly,
Va., headquarters declined to comment on the suit.
   The news of the suit is the latest development in a controversy
over aircraft parts made by Voi-Shan. The Seattle Times reported
Sunday that the company is suspected of supplying substandard parts
to Boeing Co. that bear the approval stamp of a fictitious
quality-control inspector.
   Boeing said its own investigation turned up no problem with the
Voi-Shan parts.
   Fairchild said last week that there have been no claims from
customers that it shipped any unsafe fasteners. It said it was
conducting its own investigation into the allegations.
   The allegations prompted a criminal investigation, which included
a 48-hour search at the plant two weeks ago by federal authorities,
both newspapers reported.
   Tom Runion, a former lab technician at the Voi-Shan plant in
suburban Chatsworth, and two unidentified former employees filed the
suit under the False Claims Act, which allows plaintiffs to win a
part of any damages eventually awarded.
   The U.S. Justice Department may join such suits as a plaintiff if
it decides the allegations have merit.
   The suit alleges that Voi-Shan falsified the results of safety
tests on its fasteners, including tests to assess the parts'
durability under stress.
   The criminal investigation is being pursued jointly by the FBI,
Internal Revenue Service, Defense Department, the Navy and the Air
Force, the newspapers said.
   According to an affidavit filed by the FBI, the Federal Aviation
Administration has ordered Boeing Co. and McDonnell Douglas Corp. to
determine whether they used any fasteners for which tests are
questionable.
   The alleged falsifications took place because ``necessary testing
equipment was inoperative, the tests could not be accomplished in
the available time due to backlogs or because parts from a
particular lot failed a test, and it was decided by management to
approve the parts anyway,'' the affidavit alleged.
   The probe led the Carlyle Group of Washington, D.C., to announce
it is reconsidering its $230 million bid for Fairchild, the Times
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
