<FIRST>r f BC-LennaneRetirement     02-21 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Lennane Retirement,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head Of Newspaper Computer Maker Retires With A Bang</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of System Integrators Inc., a
major supplier of newsroom computer systems, announced his
retirement Tuesday with a flourish, placing full-page newspaper ads
saying he wanted to take a jet flight ``into the sunset and new
adventures.''
   James P. Lennane, 48, SSI's chairman and chief executive officer,
said in the ads in USA Today and several other newspapers that he
was ``unemployed but well-rewarded,'' and planned to travel on his
four-engine Gulfstream private jet. He gave no other details of his
plans.
   SII says it has installed newsroom computers in more than 250
newspapers worldwide, including The Washington Post, The Los Angeles
Times, The Detroit News, Die Welt, The Financial Times of London and
The Sydney Morning Herald.
   SII was formed by Lennane in the 1970s. Lennane will be succeeded
as chief executive of the Sacramento-based company by Al Edwards,
the company said.
</TEXT>
