<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ColemanBuyout     02-21 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coleman Buyout,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coleman Family SEC Filing Details Coleman Co. Acquisition Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coleman family may sell off parts of
Coleman Co. if it succeeds in its more than $330 million attempt to
take over the camping equipment maker, according to a document filed
Tuesday.
   The document filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission
contained the clearest public statement of the family's intentions
to date.
   Some analysts have speculated the $64-per-share offer from family
members was intended to put the company on the auction block. Others
said the family appeared to be serious about retaining control and
may have made the offer as a defensive move to ward off other
takeover attempts.
   The acquisition was undertaken ``in order to better enable the
family and the company's management to focus attention on the
long-term interests of the company,'' the SEC filing said.
   The family proposed the leveraged buyout to the Coleman board on
Feb. 14.
   Selling some of the assets of the acquired company is a
relatively common method of repaying money borrowed for
debt-financed takeovers.
   Coleman Co. officials refused to comment on the SEC document.
   Coleman stock continued trading heavily on the New York Stock
Exchange, closing Tuesday at $70.62{, up 12{ cents. Average daily
trading normally is 20,700 shares; On Tuesday, 108,300 shares
changed hands.
   In its filing, the family said it reserves the right to take
other action if its proposal fails.
   ``I think what they're saying is they don't have a secondary
plan, but they reserve the right to do anything else they darn well
please,'' said Ron Wade, managing partner at the Kansas City, Mo.,
office of the Arthur Anderson and Co. accounting and consulting firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
