<DOCNO> AP890221-0315 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-21-89 2239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Deere     02-21 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Deere,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deere Earnings Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deere &amp; Co. reported earnings of $48.4
million Tuesday for the three months ended Jan. 31, a 28.3 percent
decline compared with the same period of 1988.
   Deere, however, said the profit of $67.5 million reported in the
1988 period was inflated by a one-time gain.
   Earnings per share for the nation's largest farm-machinery maker
declined to 65 cents for the three months ended Jan. 31, compared
with 99 cents per share in the comparable quarter last year.
   Net income for last year's first quarter benefited from a
one-time gain of $38 million from the adoption of new accounting
rules for income taxes and tax losses that were carried forward, the
company said.
   Worldwide net sales to dealers for this year's first quarter
totaled $1.14 billion, up 9 percent from the $1.04 billion reported
in the year-ago period.
   ``During January 1989, the company introduced to its agricultural
equipment dealers a major line of new combines, large tractors and
other equipment,'' said Deere Chairman Robert A. Hanson.
   ``The manufacturing startup of these new products resulted in
some production and shipping delays as well as excess manufacturing
costs which affected our North American operating results in the
first quarter,'' Hanson said.
   ``Shipments to our dealers ... were approximately $75 million
less than scheduled,'' he said. ``However, we expect to make up this
shortfall in the second quarter.''
   Retail sales for the period were relatively unchanged from
first-quarter 1988, the company said.
   Deere is optimistic abouts its prospects for this year.
   Hanson said farmers' income, which hit a record high last year,
was expected to be strong again in 1989. He said Deere also could
benefit from reductions in the U.S. grain surplus that had long
dampened commodities prices. ``Additionally, land values have
continued to increase, and the overall level of famers' indebtedness
has been reduced significantly,'' Hanson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
